adim Radzievski]] (1962&nbsp;\u2013 July 63)\n*{{flagicon|USSR}} [[Sergei Korshunov]] (July 1963)\n* [[Vasiliy Yermilov (footballer)|Vasiliy Yermilov]] (1964\u201365)\n* [[Alexander Sagreski]] (1966)\n* [[Vladimir Eremeev (footballer)|Vladimir Eremeev]] (1967\u201368)\n* [[Viktor Korotkevich]] (1969\u201370)\n*{{flagicon|USSR}} [[Leonard Adamov]] (1971\u201372)\n* [[Leonid Yerochovich]] (July 1973)\n* [[Yevgeniy Glemboski]] (July 1973\u201374)\n* [[Viktor Korotkevich]] (1975&nbsp;\u2013 July 77)\n* [[Alexander Tschirimisin]] (July 1977\u201380)\n{{col-3}}\n* [[Kasimir Symanski]] (1981\u201383)\n*{{flagicon|USSR}} [[Nikolay Kiselyov (footballer)|Nikolay Kiselyov]] (1984)\n* [[Viktor Korotkevich]] (1985&nbsp;\u2013 July 87)\n*{{flagicon|Byelorussian SSR}} [[Valery Janotschkin]] (July 1, 1987&nbsp;\u2013 Dec 31, 1987)\n* [[Yuriy Golovey]] (July 1988)\n* [[Alexander Pryazhnikov]] (July 1988\u201390)\n* [[Kasimir Symanski]] (1991)\n* [[Vladimir Astratenko]] (1992\u201393)\n* [[Viktor Korotkevich]] (1993\u201394)\n*{{flagicon|Belarus}} [[Nikolai Gorjunov]] (1994\u201396)\n* [[Yuriy Grunov]] (1997)\n*{{flagicon|Belarus}} [[Valery Janotschkin]] (Jan 1, 1998&nbsp;\u2013 May 15, 1999)\n*{{flagicon|Belarus}} [[Vyacheslav Akshaev]] (Jan 1, 1999&nbsp;\u2013 June 30, 2000)\n{{col-3}}\n*{{flagicon|Belarus}} [[Aleksandr Dmitriyevich Kuznetsov|Alexandr Kuznetsov]] (August 2000&nbsp;\u2013 May 1)\n*{{flagicon|Belarus}} [[Valery Janotschkin]] (May 15, 2001&nbsp;\u2013 Sept 1, 2001)\n*{{flagicon|Russia}} [[Sergey Podpaly]] (Aug 1, 2001&nbsp;\u2013 June 26, 2004)\n*{{flagicon|Russia}} [[Aleksandr Dmitriyevich Kuznetsov|Alexandr Kuznetsov]] (July 1, 2004&nbsp;\u2013 Aug 12, 2005)\n*{{flagicon|Belarus}} [[Nikolai Gorjunov]] (Aug 15, 2005&nbsp;\u2013 July 1, 2006)\n*{{flagicon|Russia}} [[Viktor Papaev]] (July 5, 2006&nbsp;\u2013 Oct 27, 2006)\n*{{flagicon|Belarus}} [[Vladimir Golmak]] ''(interim)'' (Oct 28, 2006&nbsp;\u2013 Jan 8, 2007)\n*{{flagicon|Belarus}} [[Anatoly Yurevich]] (Jan 9, 2007&nbsp;\u2013 Aug 5, 2008)\n*{{flagicon|Belarus}} [[Andrey Yusipets]] (Aug 15, 2008&nbsp;\u2013 Aug 30, 2009)\n*{{flagicon|Belarus}} [[Leonid Borsuk]] ''(interim)'' (Sept 1, 2009&nbsp;\u2013 Dec 13, 2009)\n*{{flagicon|Belarus}} [[Oleg Kubarev]] (Dec 14, 2009&nbsp;\u2013 Dec 9, 2012)\n*{{flagicon|Belarus}} [[Alyaksey Merkulaw]] (Dec 10, 2012\u2013)\n{{col-end}}\n\n== References ==\n{{reflist}}\n\n== External links ==\n*[http://www.fcgomel.by/ Official Website]\n*[http://fcgomel.com/ Club's fans' site]\n*[http://www.uefa.com/teamsandplayers/teams/club=66169/domestic/index.html FC Gomel at UEFA.COM]\n\n{{Belarusian First League teamlist}}\n{{Belarusian Premier League teamlist}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Gomel, FC}}\n[[Category:Football clubs in Belarus]]\n[[Category:Sport in Gomel]]\n[[Category:1959 establishments in Belarus]]\n[[Category:Association football clubs established in 1959]]\n[[Category:FC Gomel]]\n", "text_old": "{{Infobox football club\n| clubname = FC Gomel\n| image    = FC Gomel logo.png\n| fullname = Football Club Gomel\n| nickname = \n| founded  = 1959\n| ground   = [[Central Stadium (Gomel)|Central Stadium]],<br/>[[Gomel]], [[Belarus]]\n| capacity = 14,307\n| chairman = Vitaliy Kushner\n| manager  = [[Ivan Bionchik]]\n| league   = [[Belarusian First League]]\n| season   = [[2019 Belarusian Premier League|2019]]\n| position = [[Belarusian Premier League|Premier League]], 15th (relegated)\n| pattern_la1 = _gomel19a\n| pattern_b1  = _gomel19a\n| pattern_ra1 = _gomel19a\n| pattern_sh1 = _gomel1819a\n| pattern_so1 = \n| leftarm1    = FFFFFF\n| body1       = FFFFFF\n| rightarm1   = FFFFFF\n| shorts1     = FFFFFF\n| socks1      = FFFFFF\n| pattern_la2 = _dordrecht1718h\n| pattern_b2  = _dordrecht1718h\n| pattern_ra2 = _dordrecht1718h\n| pattern_sh2 = _gomel19h\n| pattern_so2 = \n| leftarm2    = FFFFFF\n| body2       = FFFFFF\n| rightarm2   = FFFFFF\n| shorts2     = FFFFFF\n| socks2      = 008000\n}}\n\n'''FC Gomel''' ({{lang-be|\u0424\u041a \u0413\u043e\u043c\u0435\u043b\u044c}}), or '''FK Homel''', is a [[Belarus]]ian [[association football|football]] club, playing in the city of [[Gomel]]. Their home stadium is [[Central Stadium (Gomel)|Central Stadium]].\n\n== History ==\nTeams from Gomel (usually city or raion selection or railway-based team ''Lokomotiv'', but not always) played in Belarusian SSR championships since the early 1920s.<ref>[http://www.fcgomel.by/index.php?option=com_content&task=view&id=18&Itemid=32 History of FC Gomel and Gomel football] {{webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20100130171005/http://www.fcgomel.by/index.php?option=com_content&task=view&id=18&Itemid=32 |date=2010-01-30 }}</ref> In 1946 Belorusian SSR league for one season becomes one of the zones of USSR 3rd level league, and ''Lokomotiv Gomel'' became the first city team to play in Soviet league.<ref>[http://www.fcgomel.by/index.php?option=com_content&task=view&id=19&Itemid=34 Gomel teams in Soviet leagues] {{webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20100818114503/http://www.fcgomel.by/index.php?option=com_content&task=view&id=19&Itemid=34 |date=2010-08-18 }}</ref>\n\nThe modern Gomel team was founded in 1959 as ''Lokomotiv Gomel''. They played at the 2nd level of Soviet football between 1959 and 1968. The results varied between seasons, as the team managed to finish 1st in their zone in 1962 as well as last in 1959 and 1963. However, because Soviet league system structure was changing almost every season in the 1950s and 60s, Lokomotiv wasn't promoted or relegated until another league reorganisation in 1969.\n\n''Gomselmash'' played at the 3rd level of Soviet football between 1969 and 1989, until further league reorganisation in 1990, after which the team was relegated to the 4th level.\n\nIn 1992 Gomselmash joined the newly formed [[Belarusian Premier League]]. The first years were unsuccessful and the team relegated in 1995. They changed name to the current one, FC Gomel, the same year. In 1998 Gomel returned to Premier League and achieved much better results than before (champions title in 2003, 2nd place in 2007 and 3rd in 1999). The team also won [[Belarusian Cup]] in 2002 and made it to the final in 2004.\n\nIn 2012, they played English club [[Liverpool F.C.|Liverpool]] in the [[UEFA Europa League]] qualifying rounds. In the first leg they lost 0\u20131 and lost again away at [[Anfield]] in the second leg 3\u20130.\n\n=== Name changes ===\n*1959: Lokomotiv Gomel\n*1965: Spartak Gomel\n*1969: Gomselmash Gomel\n*1976: Mashinostroitel Gomel\n*1978: Gomselmash Gomel\n*1995: Gomel\n\n== Honours ==\n* '''[[Belarusian Premier League]]'''\n** ''Winners (1):'' [[2003 Belarusian Premier League|2003]]\n** ''Runners-up (1):'' [[2007 Belarusian Premier League|2007]]\n** ''3rd place (2):'' [[1999 Belarusian Premier League|1999]], [[2011 Belarusian Premier League|2011]]\n* '''[[Belarusian Cup]]'''\n** ''Winners (2):'' [[2001\u201302 Belarusian Cup|2002]], [[2010\u201311 Belarusian Cup|2011]]\n** ''Runners-up (1):'' [[2003\u201304 Belarusian Cup|2004]]\n* '''[[Belarusian Super Cup]]'''\n** ''Winners (1):'' [[2012 Belarusian Super Cup|2012]]\n\n== Current squad ==\n''As of April 2020'' <ref>http://www.fcgomel.by/team/main/players/</ref>\n\n{{Fs start}}\n{{Fs player|no=1|name=[[Andrey Shkvarkov]]|nat=BLR|pos=GK}}\n{{Fs player|no=3|name=[[Dmitry Kaplunov]]|nat=BLR|pos=MF}}\n{{Fs player|no=4|name=[[Anton Susha]]|nat=BLR|pos=MF}}\n{{Fs player|no=5|name=[[Ruslan Yudenkov]]|nat=BLR|pos=MF}}\n{{Fs player|no=7|name=[[Mikalay Ivanow]]|nat=BLR|pos=MF}}\n{{Fs player|no=9|name=[[Oleksandr Batyschev]]|nat=UKR|pos=MF}}\n{{Fs player|no=10|name=[[Artsyom Buloychyk]]|nat=BLR|pos=MF}}\n{{Fs player|no=11|name=[[Kirill Yermakovich]]|nat=BLR|pos=MF}}\n{{Fs player|no=12|name=[[Yevgeny Milevsky]]|nat=BLR|pos=MF}}\n{{Fs player|no=15|name=[[Kiryl Shawchenka]]|nat=BLR|pos=DF}}\n{{Fs player|no=16|name=[[Igor Zayats]]|nat=BLR|pos=DF}}\n{{Fs player|no=17|name=[[Mikita Nyakrasaw]]|nat=BLR|pos=FW}}\n{{Fs mid}}\n{{Fs player|no=21|name=