{"title_page": "Reginald Lewis", "text_new": "{{other people}}\n{{Infobox person\n| name = Reginald Lewis\n| image = Reginald-lewis.jpg\n| imagesize = 300px\n| caption = \n| birth_name = Reginald F. Lewis\n| birth_date = December 7, 1942\n| birth_place = [[Baltimore]], [[Maryland]], U.S\n| death_date = {{Death date and age|1993|1|19|1942|12|7}}\n| death_place = [[New York City]], [[New York (state)|New York]], U.S\n| parents =\n| children = Leslie Lewis, [[Christina Lewis]]\n| occupation =\n| relations = [[Loida Nicolas-Lewis]] (wife)\n| alma_mater = [[Virginia State University]]<br>[[Harvard Law School]]\n}}\n'''Reginald F. Lewis''' (December 7, 1942 \u2013 January 19, 1993), was an [[United States|American]] businessman. He was one of the richest [[African-American]] men in the 1980s, and the first [[African American]] to build a billion-dollar company, TLC Beatrice International Holdings Inc.<ref>https://www.theroot.com/billion-dollar-legacy-reginald-f-lewis-incredible-li-1823041385</ref>\n\nIn 1993, ''[[Forbes]]'' listed Lewis among the 400 richest Americans, with a [[net worth]] estimated at $400 million.<ref>https://www.sfgate.com/entertainment/article/A-Black-Man-s-Journey-to-the-Forbes-400-List-3045896.php</ref><ref>https://articles.latimes.com/1993-01-20/business/fi-1542_1_leveraged-buyout</ref>\n\n==Career==\n{{unreferenced|date=April 2018|section}}\nRecruited to top New York law firm [[Paul, Weiss, Rifkind, Wharton & Garrison LLP]] immediately after law school, Lewis left to start his own firm two years later. After 15 years as a corporate lawyer with his own practice, he moved to the other side of the table by creating TLC Group L.P., a [[private equity ]] firm, in 1983.\n\nHis first major deal was the purchase of the McCall Pattern Company, a home sewing pattern business, for $22.5 million. Lewis had learned from a [[Fortune (magazine)|''Fortune'' magazine]] article that the [[JBS USA#Esmark|Esmark]] holding company, which had recently purchased [[Norton Simon]], planned to divest from the [[McCall Corporation|McCall]] Pattern Company, a maker of home sewing patterns founded in 1870. With fewer and fewer people sewing at home, McCall was seemingly on the decline\u2014though it had posted profits of $6 million in 1983 on sales of $51.9 million. At the time, McCall was number two in its industry, holding 29.7 percent of the market, compared to industry leader [[Simplicity Pattern]]s with 39.4 percent.\n\nHe managed to negotiate the price down, then raised $1 million himself from family and friends and borrowed the rest from institutional investors and investment banking firm [[First Boston]] Corp.\n\nWithin a year, he turned the company around by freeing up capital tied in fixed assets such as building and machinery, and finding a new use for machinery during downtime by manufacturing greeting cards. He then started to recruit managers from rival companies. He further strengthened McCall by containing costs, improving quality, beginning to export to China, and emphasizing new product introductions. This new combination led to the company's most profitable year in its history. With the addition of McCall real estate worth an estimated $6 million that the company retained ownership of, he later sold McCall at a 90-1 return, resulting in a tremendous profit for investors. Lewis's share was 81.7 percent of the $90 million.\n\nIn 1987, Lewis bought [[Beatrice Foods|Beatrice International Foods]] from Beatrice Companies for $985 million, renaming it TLC Beatrice International Holdings Inc.<ref>https://www.nytimes.com/1987/08/10/business/beatrice-unit-brings-985-million.html</ref>, a snack food, beverage, and grocery store conglomerate that was the largest African-American owned and managed business in the U.S. The deal was partly financed through Michael Milken of the maverick investment bank [[Drexel Burnham Lambert]]. In order to reduce the amount needed to finance the [[leveraged buyout]], Lewis came up with a plan to sell off some of the division's assets simultaneous with the takeover.\n\nWhen TLC Beatrice reported revenue of $1.8 billion in 1987, it became the first black-owned company to have more than $1 billion in annual sales. At its peak in 1996, TLC Beatrice International Holdings Inc. had sales of $2.2 billion and was number 512 on ''Fortune'' magazine's list of 1,000 largest companies.\n\n==Philanthropy==\n{{Advert|date=March 2019}}\nIn 1987 Lewis established the Reginald F. Lewis Foundation, which funded grants of approximately $10 million to various non-profit programs and organizations while he was alive. His first major grant was an unsolicited $1 million to [[Howard University]] in 1988; the federal government matched the grant, making the gift $2 million, which was used to fund an endowment for scholarships, fellowships, and faculty sabbaticals.<ref>[http://www.reginaldflewis.com/beachglamour/legacy.html \"Reginald F. Lewis as Philanthropist\"]</ref>\n\nIn 1992, Lewis donated $3 million to [[Harvard Law School]], the largest grant at the time in the school's history.<ref>[http://www.law.harvard.edu/academics/fellowships/the-reginald-f.-lewis-fellowships-for-law-teaching.html \"The Reginald F. Lewis Fellowships for Law Teaching\"]</ref> The school renamed its International Law Center the Reginald F. Lewis International Law Center, the first major facility at Harvard named in honor of an African-American.<ref>[http://www.law.harvard.edu/about/administration/facilities/buildings/lewis.html \"Building Overview: Lewis International Law Center\"]</ref>\n\nWhile alive, Lewis made known his desire to support a museum of African American culture. In 2005, the [[Reginald F. Lewis Museum of Maryland African American History & Culture]] opened in [[Baltimore]] with the support of a $5 million grant from his foundation.<ref>[http://www.reginaldflewis.com/biography-4.php \"Reginald F. Lewis\"] {{webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20140305110929/http://www.reginaldflewis.com/biography-4.php |date=2014-03-05 }}</ref> It is the East Coast's largest African American museum occupying an 82,000 square-foot facility with permanent and special exhibition space, interactive learning environments, auditorium, resource center, oral history recording studio, museum shop, caf\u00e9, classrooms, meeting rooms, outside terrace and reception areas.<ref>[http://www.rflewismuseum.org/about/facilities \"Reginald F. Lewis Museum Facilities\"] {{webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20150422065753/http://www.rflewismuseum.org/about/facilities |date=2015-04-22 }}</ref> It highlights the history and accomplishments of African Americans with a special focus on [[Maryland]]'s African American community. The museum is also a [[Smithsonian Affiliations|Smithsonian affiliate]].\n\n==Personal life==\nBorn in [[Baltimore, Maryland]], Lewis grew up in a middle-class neighborhood. He won a football scholarship to [[Virginia State University|Virginia State University (VSU)]] and joined the Alpha Phi Chapter of [[Kappa Alpha Psi]] while an undergraduate student.<ref name=\"reginaldflewis\">http://reginaldflewis.com/reginaldflewis.com/legacy-scholarship-fund.html</ref> After graduating from VSU with a degree in political science in 1965, he immediately attended [[Harvard Law School]] and completed his [[Juris Doctorate]] degree in 1968.<ref name=\"reginaldflewis\"/>\n\nHe was married to [[Loida Nicolas-Lewis]]. They had two daughters, Leslie and Christina.<ref>http://www.baltimoresun.com/entertainment/arts/bs-ae-lewis-memoir-20120210-story.html</ref>\n\nLewis died at age 50, from [[brain cancer]]. Nicolas-Lewis took over the company a year after his death.<ref>{{cite news|author=Jonathan P. Hicks|url=https://www.nytimes.com/1993/01/20/us/reginald-f-lewis-50-is-dead-financier-led-beatrice-takeover.html|title=Reginald F. Lewis, 50, Is Dead; Financier Led Beatrice Takeover|publisher=[[The New York Times]]  |date=January 20, 1993}}</ref>\n\n==References==\n{{reflist}}\n\n==External links==\n* [http://www.reginaldflewis.com Reginald F. Lewis official website]\n* [http://www.africanamericanculture.org/ Reginald F. Lewis Museum of African American Culture & History]\n* [https://web.archive.org/web/20101124072734/http://www.law.harvard.edu/academics/fellowships/law_teaching_lewis.php Reginald F. Lewis Fellowship - Harvard]\n* [http://thelewiscollege.com/ The Lewis College]\n* [http://www.baltimorecityschools.org/419/site/default.asp Reginald F. Lewis High School - Baltimore]\n* [https://web.archive.org/web/20110715171143/http://www.reginaldflewisfanclub.com/ Reginald F. Lewis Fan Club]\n\n===Articles===\n* [http://www.mikemilken.com/fincareer.taf?page=lewis Reg Lewis, TLC Beatrice international]\n* [http://www.mikemilken.com/biography.taf?page=oftensaid Often Said]\n* [http://www.afrocentricnews.com/html/beatrice_liquidate.html Afrocentricnews - TLC Beatrice to Liquidate]\n* [http://www.vsu.edu/students/organization/kapsi/alphaphi.htm]\n* [http://www.fundinguniverse.com/company-histories/TLC-Beatrice-International-Holdings-Inc-Company-History.html] http://articles.latimes.com/1989-09-13/business/fi-2062_1_mccall-pattern\n\n===Books===\n* [https://www.amazon.com/dp/0471042277/ Amazon.com: Books: \"Why Should White Guys Have All the Fun?\": How Reginald Lewis Created a Billion-Dollar Business Empire]\n* https://www.amazon.com/America-Wrong-Donald-L-Barlett/dp/0836270010/ref=sr_1_1?s=books&ie=UTF8&qid=1347210532&sr=1-1&keywords=america+what+went+wrong\n* Amazon.com: Books: Reginald F. Lewis Before TLC Beatrice: The Young Man Before The Billion-Dollar Empire, by Lin Hart https://www.amazon.com/Reginald-Lewis-Before-Beatrice-Billion-Dollar/dp/0985347929/ref=sr_1_1?ie=UTF8&qid=1452631776&sr=8-1&keywords=Reginald+F.+Lewis+Before+TLC+Beatrice\n\n{{Authority control}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Lewis, Reginald}}\n[[Category:1942 births]]\n[[Category:1993 deaths]]\n[[Category:African-American businesspeople]]\n[[Category:American chief executives of food industry companies]]\n[[Category:African-American lawyers]]\n[[Category:African-American non-fiction writers]]\n[[Category:American businesspeople in retailing]]\n[[Category:American business writers]]\n[[Category:American financiers]]\n[[Category:American grocers]]\n[[Category:American manufacturing businesspeople]]\n[[Category:American real estate businesspeople]]\n[[Category:Businesspeople from Maryland]]\n[[Category:Businesspeople in the drink industry]]\n[[Category:Deaths from brain tumor]]\n[[Category:Harvard Law School alumni]]\n[[Category:Maryland lawyers]]\n[[Category:Businesspeople from Baltimore]]\n[[Category:Virginia State University alumni]]\n[[Category:Virginia State Trojans football players]]\n[[Category:20th-century American non-fiction writers]]\n[[Category:20th-century American businesspeople]]\n[[Category:Paul, Weiss, Rifkind, Wharton & Garrison people]]\n", "text_old": "{{other people}}\n{{Infobox person\n| name = Reginald Lewis\n| image = Reginald-lewis.jpg\n| imagesize = 300px\n| caption = \n| birth_name = Reginald F. Lewis\n| birth_date = December 7, 1942\n| birth_place = [[Baltimore]], [[Maryland]], U.S\n| death_date = {{Death date and age|1993|1|19|1942|12|7}}\n| death_place = [[New York City]], [[New York (state)|New York]], U.S\n| parents =\n| children = Leslie Lewis, [[Christina Lewis]]\n| occupation =\n| relations = [[Loida Nicolas-Lewis]] (wife)\n| alma_mater = [[Virginia State University]]<br>[[Harvard Law School]]\n}}\n'''Reginald F. Lewis''' (December 7, 1942 \u2013 January 19, 1993), was an [[United States|American]] businessman. He was one of the richest [[African-American]] men in the 1980s, and the first [[African American]] to build a billion-dollar company, TLC Beatrice International Holdings Inc.<ref>https://www.theroot.com/billion-dollar-legacy-reginald-f-lewis-incredible-li-1823041385</ref>\n\nIn 1993, ''[[Forbes]]'' listed Lewis among the 400 richest Americans, with a [[net worth]] estimated at $400 million.<ref>https://www.sfgate.com/entertainment/article/A-Black-Man-s-Journey-to-the-Forbes-400-List-3045896.php</ref><ref>https://articles.latimes.com/1993-01-20/business/fi-1542_1_leveraged-buyout</ref>\n\n==Career==\n{{unreferenced|date=April 2018|section}}\nRecruited to top New York law firm [[Paul, Weiss, Rifkind, Wharton & Garrison LLP]] immediately after law school, Lewis left to start his own firm two years later. After 15 years as a corporate lawyer with his own practice, he moved to the other side of the table by creating TLC Group L.P., a [[private equity ]] firm, in 1983.\n\nHis first major deal was the purchase of the McCall Pattern Company, a home sewing pattern business, for $22.5 million. Lewis had learned from a [[Fortune (magazine)|''Fortune'' magazine]] article that the [[JBS USA#Esmark|Esmark]] holding company, which had recently purchased [[Norton Simon]], planned to divest from the [[McCall Corporation|McCall]] Pattern Company, a maker of home sewing patterns founded in 1870. With fewer and fewer people sewing at home, McCall was seemingly on the decline\u2014though it had posted profits of $6 million in 1983 on sales of $51.9 million. At the time, McCall was number two in its industry, holding 29.7 percent of the market, compared to industry leader [[Simplicity Pattern]]s with 39.4 percent.\n\nHe managed to negotiate the price down, then raised $1 million himself from family and friends and borrowed the rest from institutional investors and investment banking firm [[First Boston]] Corp.\n\nWithin a year, he turned the company around by freeing up capital tied in fixed assets such as building and machinery, and finding a new use for machinery during downtime by manufacturing greeting cards. He then started to recruit managers from rival companies. He further strengthened McCall by containing costs, improving quality, beginning to export to China, and emphasizing new product introductions. This new combination led to the company's most profitable year in its history. With the addition of McCall real estate worth an estimated $6 million that the company retained ownership of, he later sold McCall at a 90-1 return, resulting in a tremendous profit for investors. Lewis's share was 81.7 percent of the $90 million.\n\nIn 1987, Lewis bought [[Beatrice Foods|Beatrice International Foods]] from Beatrice Companies for $985 million, renaming it TLC Beatrice International Holdings Inc.<ref>https://www.nytimes.com/1987/08/10/business/beatrice-unit-brings-985-million.html</ref>, a snack food, beverage, and grocery store conglomerate that was the largest African-American owned and managed business in the U.S. The deal was partly financed through Mike Milken of the maverick investment bank [[Drexel Burnham Lambert]]. In order to reduce the amount needed to finance the [[leveraged buyout]], Lewis came up with a plan to sell off some of the division's assets simultaneous with the takeover.\n\nWhen TLC Beatrice reported revenue of $1.8 billion in 1987, it became the first black-owned company to have more than $1 billion in annual sales. At its peak in 1996, TLC Beatrice International Holdings Inc. had sales of $2.2 billion and was number 512 on ''Fortune'' magazine's list of 1,000 largest companies.\n\n==Philanthropy==\n{{Advert|date=March 2019}}\nIn 1987 Lewis established the Reginald F. Lewis Foundation, which funded grants of approximately $10 million to various non-profit programs and organizations while he was alive. His first major grant was an unsolicited $1 million to [[Howard University]] in 1988; the federal government matched the grant, making the gift $2 million, which was used to fund an endowment for scholarships, fellowships, and faculty sabbaticals.<ref>[http://www.reginaldflewis.com/beachglamour/legacy.html \"Reginald F. Lewis as Philanthropist\"]</ref>\n\nIn 1992, Lewis donated $3 million to [[Harvard Law School]], the largest grant at the time in the school's history.<ref>[http://www.law.harvard.edu/academics/fellowships/the-reginald-f.-lewis-fellowships-for-law-teaching.html \"The Reginald F. Lewis Fellowships for Law Teaching\"]</ref> The school renamed its International Law Center the Reginald F. Lewis International Law Center, the first major facility at Harvard named in honor of an African-American.<ref>[http://www.law.harvard.edu/about/administration/facilities/buildings/lewis.html \"Building Overview: Lewis International Law Center\"]</ref>\n\nWhile alive, Lewis made known his desire to support a museum of African American culture. In 2005, the [[Reginald F. Lewis Museum of Maryland African American History & Culture]] opened in [[Baltimore]] with the support of a $5 million grant from his foundation.<ref>[http://www.reginaldflewis.com/biography-4.php \"Reginald F. Lewis\"] {{webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20140305110929/http://www.reginaldflewis.com/biography-4.php |date=2014-03-05 }}</ref> It is the East Coast's largest African American museum occupying an 82,000 square-foot facility with permanent and special exhibition space, interactive learning environments, auditorium, resource center, oral history recording studio, museum shop, caf\u00e9, classrooms, meeting rooms, outside terrace and reception areas.<ref>[http://www.rflewismuseum.org/about/facilities \"Reginald F. Lewis Museum Facilities\"] {{webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20150422065753/http://www.rflewismuseum.org/about/facilities |date=2015-04-22 }}</ref> It highlights the history and accomplishments of African Americans with a special focus on [[Maryland]]'s African American community. The museum is also a [[Smithsonian Affiliations|Smithsonian affiliate]].\n\n==Personal life==\nBorn in [[Baltimore, Maryland]], Lewis grew up in a middle-class neighborhood. He won a football scholarship to [[Virginia State University|Virginia State University (VSU)]] and joined the Alpha Phi Chapter of [[Kappa Alpha Psi]] while an undergraduate student.<ref name=\"reginaldflewis\">http://reginaldflewis.com/reginaldflewis.com/legacy-scholarship-fund.html</ref> After graduating from VSU with a degree in political science in 1965, he immediately attended [[Harvard Law School]] and completed his [[Juris Doctorate]] degree in 1968.<ref name=\"reginaldflewis\"/>\n\nHe was married to [[Loida Nicolas-Lewis]]. They had two daughters, Leslie and Christina.<ref>http://www.baltimoresun.com/entertainment/arts/bs-ae-lewis-memoir-20120210-story.html</ref>\n\nLewis died at age 50, from [[brain cancer]]. Nicolas-Lewis took over the company a year after his death.<ref>{{cite news|author=Jonathan P. Hicks|url=https://www.nytimes.com/1993/01/20/us/reginald-f-lewis-50-is-dead-financier-led-beatrice-takeover.html|title=Reginald F. Lewis, 50, Is Dead; Financier Led Beatrice Takeover|publisher=[[The New York Times]]  |date=January 20, 1993}}</ref>\n\n==References==\n{{reflist}}\n\n==External links==\n* [http://www.reginaldflewis.com Reginald F. Lewis official website]\n* [http://www.africanamericanculture.org/ Reginald F. Lewis Museum of African American Culture & History]\n* [https://web.archive.org/web/20101124072734/http://www.law.harvard.edu/academics/fellowships/law_teaching_lewis.php Reginald F. Lewis Fellowship - Harvard]\n* [http://thelewiscollege.com/ The Lewis College]\n* [http://www.baltimorecityschools.org/419/site/default.asp Reginald F. Lewis High School - Baltimore]\n* [https://web.archive.org/web/20110715171143/http://www.reginaldflewisfanclub.com/ Reginald F. Lewis Fan Club]\n\n===Articles===\n* [http://www.mikemilken.com/fincareer.taf?page=lewis Reg Lewis, TLC Beatrice international]\n* [http://www.mikemilken.com/biography.taf?page=oftensaid Often Said]\n* [http://www.afrocentricnews.com/html/beatrice_liquidate.html Afrocentricnews - TLC Beatrice to Liquidate]\n* [http://www.vsu.edu/students/organization/kapsi/alphaphi.htm]\n* [http://www.fundinguniverse.com/company-histories/TLC-Beatrice-International-Holdings-Inc-Company-History.html] http://articles.latimes.com/1989-09-13/business/fi-2062_1_mccall-pattern\n\n===Books===\n* [https://www.amazon.com/dp/0471042277/ Amazon.com: Books: \"Why Should White Guys Have All the Fun?\": How Reginald Lewis Created a Billion-Dollar Business Empire]\n* https://www.amazon.com/America-Wrong-Donald-L-Barlett/dp/0836270010/ref=sr_1_1?s=books&ie=UTF8&qid=1347210532&sr=1-1&keywords=america+what+went+wrong\n* Amazon.com: Books: Reginald F. Lewis Before TLC Beatrice: The Young Man Before The Billion-Dollar Empire, by Lin Hart https://www.amazon.com/Reginald-Lewis-Before-Beatrice-Billion-Dollar/dp/0985347929/ref=sr_1_1?ie=UTF8&qid=1452631776&sr=8-1&keywords=Reginald+F.+Lewis+Before+TLC+Beatrice\n\n{{Authority control}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Lewis, Reginald}}\n[[Category:1942 births]]\n[[Category:1993 deaths]]\n[[Category:African-American businesspeople]]\n[[Category:American chief executives of food industry companies]]\n[[Category:African-American lawyers]]\n[[Category:African-American non-fiction writers]]\n[[Category:American businesspeople in retailing]]\n[[Category:American business writers]]\n[[Category:American financiers]]\n[[Category:American grocers]]\n[[Category:American manufacturing businesspeople]]\n[[Category:American real estate businesspeople]]\n[[Category:Businesspeople from Maryland]]\n[[Category:Businesspeople in the drink industry]]\n[[Category:Deaths from brain tumor]]\n[[Category:Harvard Law School alumni]]\n[[Category:Maryland lawyers]]\n[[Category:Businesspeople from Baltimore]]\n[[Category:Virginia State University alumni]]\n[[Category:Virginia State Trojans football players]]\n[[Category:20th-century American non-fiction writers]]\n[[Category:20th-century American businesspeople]]\n[[Category:Paul, Weiss, Rifkind, Wharton & Garrison people]]\n", "name_user": "Burninmyleather", "label": "unsafe", "comment": "", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Reginald_Lewis"}
{"title_page": "Anthony Scaramucci", "text_new": "{{redirect2|The Mooch|Scaramucci||Mooch (disambiguation){{!}}Mooch|and|Scaramucci (disambiguation)}}\n{{short description|American financier and political figure}}\n{{Use mdy dates|date=October 2017}}\n{{Infobox officeholder\n| name                = Anthony Scaramucci\n| image               = Anthony Scaramucci at SALT Conference 2016 (cropped).jpg\n| office              = [[White House Communications Director]]\n| president           = [[Donald Trump]]\n| term_start          = July 21, 2017\n| term_end            = July 31, 2017\n| predecessor         = [[Sean Spicer]] (acting)\n| successor           = [[Hope Hicks]]\n| party               = [[Republican Party (United States)|Republican]]\n| birth_date          = {{birth date and age|1964|1|6}}\n| birth_place         = [[Long Island]], New York, U.S.\n| death_date          =\n| death_place         =\n| otherparty          =\n| spouse              = {{marriage|Lisa Miranda|1988|2014|end=divorced}}<br/>{{marriage|Deidre Ball|July 11, 2014}}\n| children            = 5\n| education           = [[Tufts University]] ([[Bachelor of Arts|BA]])<br/>[[Harvard University]] ([[Juris Doctor|JD]])\n| known_for           = founding [[SkyBridge Capital]]\n\n}}\n\n'''Anthony Scaramucci''' ({{IPAc-en|s|k|\u00e6r|\u0259|\u02c8|m|u\u02d0|t\u0283|i:}}, {{Respell|ska|r\u0259|MOOch|chee}}; born January 6, 1964), nicknamed \"'''The Mooch'''\", is an American-Italian financier, entrepreneur, and political consultant who briefly served as the [[White House Communications Director|White House Director of Communications]] from July 21 to July 31, 2017.\n\nScaramucci worked at [[Goldman Sachs]]' investment banking, equities, and private wealth management divisions between 1989 and 1996. After leaving Goldman Sachs, he founded Oscar Capital Management, and in 2005, he founded the investment firm [[SkyBridge Capital]].\n\nOn July 21, 2017, Scaramucci was appointed [[White House Communications Director]]. Days into the job, Scaramucci provoked controversy after launching a strongly-worded attack on members of the [[Trump Administration|Trump administration]] in an interview with ''[[The New Yorker]]''{{'}}s [[Ryan Lizza]], that he believed was off the record. Ten days after the announcement of his appointment, he was dismissed by the new [[White House Chief of Staff]], [[John F. Kelly]], at the recommendation of President Donald Trump.\n\n==Early life==\nScaramucci was born into an [[Italian Americans|Italian-American]]<ref name=\"New York Magazine\" /> family on January 6, 1964, on [[Long Island]], New York, where he was raised in [[Port Washington, New York|Port Washington]].<ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.nytimes.com/2017/07/21/business/dealbook/trump-media-scaramucci-wall-street.html|work= [[The New York Times]]|title=Scaramucci Has a Showman's Knack for Self-Promotion Rivaling Trump's|first= Eric |last=Owles|date=July 21, 2017|accessdate=January 13, 2019|quote=Mr. Scaramucci grew up on Long Island, in Port Washington, N.Y....}}</ref><ref name=usnews&worldreport>{{cite news|url=https://www.usnews.com/news/politics/articles/2017-07-24/10-things-you-didnt-know-about-anthony-scaramucci|title=10 Things About Anthony Scaramucci|first=Katelyn|last=Newman|date=July 24, 2017| accessdate=January 13, 2019|work=[[US News & World Report]]|archivedate=January 12, 2019|archiveurl= https://web.archive.org/web/20190112153805/https://www.usnews.com/news/politics/articles/2017-07-24/10-things-you-didnt-know-about-anthony-scaramucci|url-status=live}}</ref> He is the son of Marie DeFeo Scaramucci and Alexander Scaramucci, who was a construction worker.<ref name=\"New York Magazine\" /> His paternal grandfather Alessandro Scaramucci immigrated to the United States from [[Gualdo Tadino]], [[Umbria]].<ref>{{cite news |url=http://www.lastampa.it/2017/07/23/esteri/il-nonno-partito-da-gualdo-un-secolo-fa-viaggio-alle-radici-italiane-di-scaramucci-472cf4gMx9Vy5OZQtBnKRN/pagina.html |date=July 23, 2017 |access-date=July 26, 2017 |newspaper=[[La Stampa]] |first=Paolo |last=Festuccia |title=Il nonno partito da Gualdo un secolo fa, viaggio alle radici italiane di Scaramucci |language=Italian |url-status=live |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20170725085418/http://www.lastampa.it/2017/07/23/esteri/il-nonno-partito-da-gualdo-un-secolo-fa-viaggio-alle-radici-italiane-di-scaramucci-472cf4gMx9Vy5OZQtBnKRN/pagina.html |archivedate=July 25, 2017 |df=mdy-all }}</ref> He had a middle-class upbringing and was the first generation of his family to attend college.<ref name=\"New York Magazine\">{{cite news|last1=Pressler|first1=Jessica|title=The Mooch Is His Own Aflac Duck|url=http://nymag.com/news/business/themoney/anthony-scaramucci-2012-5/|work=[[New York (magazine)|New York]]|date=May 6, 2012|url-status=live|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20170721165946/http://nymag.com/news/business/themoney/anthony-scaramucci-2012-5/|archivedate=July 21, 2017|df=mdy-all}}</ref> He has an older brother, David, and a sister, Susan.<ref name=mcbride /><ref>{{cite web |url=https://medium.com/@Scaramucci/discussing-addiction-and-recovery-with-my-brother-3b607921ec9a |title=Discussing Addiction and Recovery with My Brother |first=Anthony |last=Scaramucci |access-date=July 28, 2017 |date=October 10, 2016 |publisher=[[Medium (website)|Medium]] |url-status=live |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20170729112517/https://medium.com/%40Scaramucci/discussing-addiction-and-recovery-with-my-brother-3b607921ec9a |archivedate=July 29, 2017 |df=mdy-all }}</ref> Scaramucci graduated in 1982 from [[Paul D. Schreiber Senior High School]] in Port Washington,<ref name=\"biz\">{{cite news |last=La Roche |first=Julia |date=August 20, 2015 |url=http://www.businessinsider.com/high-school-yearbook-photos-of-wall-street-ceos-2015-8/#heres-cohn-in-the-frosh-debate-club-117 |title=40 old high-school yearbook photos of Wall Street's titans |work=[[Business Insider]] |url-status=live |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20170206013334/http://www.businessinsider.com/high-school-yearbook-photos-of-wall-street-ceos-2015-8#heres-cohn-in-the-frosh-debate-club-117 |archivedate=February 6, 2017 |df=mdy-all }}</ref> where he served as student council president.<ref>{{cite news|title=Concerned Citizens Meet on Youth Center Issue|url=http://www2.portnet.k12.ny.us/schreibertimes/1991-1992/1992-02-14.pdf|page=8|work=The Schreiber Times|url-status=live|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20170728220838/http://www2.portnet.k12.ny.us/schreibertimes/1991-1992/1992-02-14.pdf|archivedate=July 28, 2017|df=mdy-all}}</ref> He earned a [[B.A.]] in [[economics]] at [[Tufts University]] and a [[Juris Doctor|J.D.]] at [[Harvard Law School]] where he overlapped with former President Barack Obama, former Deputy Attorney General Rod Rosenstein and Supreme Court Justice Neil Gorsuch, among others.<ref>{{cite news | url=http://www.businessinsider.com/anthony-scaramucci-goldman-sachs-2012-8 | title=The Hilarious Story Of How Anthony Scaramucci Was Hired, Fired, And Rehired At Goldman Sachs | publisher=Business Insider | date=August 14, 2012 | access-date=March 28, 2015 | last=Lopez | first=Linette | url-status=live | archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20150401015927/http://www.businessinsider.com/anthony-scaramucci-goldman-sachs-2012-8 | archivedate=April 1, 2015 | df=mdy-all }}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=https://today.law.harvard.edu/alumni-among-trumps-recent-appointees/|title=Scarramucci and other alumni among Trump's recent appointees|last=July 26|last2=2017|website=Harvard Law Today|language=en-US|access-date=2020-02-07}}</ref> Scaramucci credits his time and education at Harvard Law School as a springboard for his career in finance.<ref name=path>{{Cite web|url=https://medium.com/@Felicissimo/president-trumps-new-director-of-communications-anthony-scaramucci-the-unlikely-path-of-a-law-e7ff12492e45|title=President Trumps new Director of Communications: Anthony Scaramucci: The Unlikely Path of a Law...|last=Felicissimo|first=David|date=July 28, 2017|website=Medium|access-date=July 29, 2017|url-status=live|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20170730032546/https://medium.com/%40Felicissimo/president-trumps-new-director-of-communications-anthony-scaramucci-the-unlikely-path-of-a-law-e7ff12492e45|archivedate=July 30, 2017|df=mdy-all}}</ref> Scaramucci has never practiced law and went to work at Goldman Sachs directly after graduating.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.nytimes.com/2017/07/24/business/dealbook/anthony-scaramucci-white-house-communications-director-for-president-trump.html|title=Scaramucci on Trump: 'He's My Client'|first=Andrew Ross|last=Sorkin|date=July 24, 2017|publisher=The New York Times|via=NYTimes.com|access-date=August 4, 2017|url-status=live|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20170725070314/https://www.nytimes.com/2017/07/24/business/dealbook/anthony-scaramucci-white-house-communications-director-for-president-trump.html|archivedate=July 25, 2017|df=mdy-all}}</ref><ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.law.com/sites/almstaff/2017/07/21/trumps-man-of-the-hour-scaramucci-is-not-one-to-humble-brag-says-cravath-associate/?slreturn=20170702003400 |title=Trump's Man of the Hour Scaramucci Is Not One To 'Humble Brag,' Says Cravath Associate |date=July 21, 2017 |access-date=August 4, 2017 |website=law.com |url-access=registration |first=Leigh |last=Jones |publisher=[[ALM (company)|ALM]] |url-status=live |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20170802125755/http://www.law.com/sites/almstaff/2017/07/21/trumps-man-of-the-hour-scaramucci-is-not-one-to-humble-brag-says-cravath-associate/?slreturn=20170702003400 |archivedate=August 2, 2017 |df=mdy-all }}</ref>\n\n==Career in investment banking==\nScaramucci began his career at [[Goldman Sachs]] in 1989, in the Investment Banking division. A year later he was fired, then rehired two months later in the Equities division. In 1993, he became vice president in the bank's Private Wealth Management division.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.businessinsider.com/anthony-scaramucci-on-goldman-sachs-2015-12|title=SCARAMUCCI: What getting hired, fired, and rehired by Goldman Sachs taught me|last=Shen|first=Lucinda|website=Business Insider|access-date=2020-02-07}}</ref><ref>{{cite news | url=http://www.vanityfair.com/news/2010/01/goldman-sachs-200101 | title=The Bank Job | work=Vanity Fair | date=December 2009 | accessdate=March 28, 2015 | last=McLean | first=Bethany | url-status=live | archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20150402093328/http://www.vanityfair.com/news/2010/01/goldman-sachs-200101 | archivedate=April 2, 2015 | df=mdy-all }}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.weforum.org/people/anthony-scaramucci/|title=Anthony Scaramucci|website=World Economic Forum|access-date=2020-02-07}}</ref>\n\n===Oscar Capital Management===\nScaramucci left Goldman in 1996 to launch Oscar Capital Management with his colleague Andrew Boszhardt.<ref>{{cite news|url=http://archive.fortune.com/magazines/fortune/fortune_archive/1998/06/08/243511/index.htm |title=Everybody's Going Hedge Funds |work=Fortune |first=Bethany |last=McLean |date=June 8, 1998 |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/19990127185046/http://www.pathfinder.com/fortune/1998/980608/hed.html |archivedate=January 27, 1999 |url-status=live }}</ref> In 2001, Oscar Capital was sold to [[Neuberger Berman]], and upon Neuberger Berman's sale to [[Lehman Brothers]] in 2003, Scaramucci served as a managing director in the firm's Investment Management division.<ref name=\"finalternatives.com\">{{cite news|url=http://www.finalternatives.com/node/12537|title=FINalternatives Sky's the Limit for Skybridge After Citi Deal|date=March 17, 2010|work=Final Alternatives|access-date=July 31, 2017|url-status=live|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20170728035012/http://www.finalternatives.com/node/12537|archivedate=July 28, 2017|df=mdy-all}}</ref><ref>{{cite web | url=http://www.mmexecutive.com/issues/20011028/63571-1.html | title=Neuberger Acquires High-Net-Worth Assets | publisher=Money Management Executive | date=October 29, 2001 | accessdate=March 28, 2015 | url-status=live | archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20150402114424/http://www.mmexecutive.com/issues/20011028/63571-1.html | archivedate=April 2, 2015 | df=mdy-all }}</ref>\n\n===SkyBridge Capital===\nIn 2005, Scaramucci founded [[SkyBridge Capital]], a global alternative investment firm.<ref>{{cite news | url=https://www.cnbc.com/id/102372713 | title=Here are the best hedge funds for 2015: Experts | publisher=CNBC | date=January 27, 2015 | accessdate=March 28, 2015 | last=Delevingne | first=Lawrence | url-status=live | archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20150402115552/http://www.cnbc.com/id/102372713 | archivedate=April 2, 2015 | df=mdy-all }}</ref> Scaramucci is the chairman of the SkyBridge Alternatives Conference, or \"SALT\" Conference, launched in 2009. SALT hosts its annual flagship event in Las Vegas and an international event in the Fall/Winter. SALT has hosted large conferences in Singapore, Tokyo and, most recently, Abu Dhabi.<ref>{{cite news|url=https://dealbook.nytimes.com/2011/05/13/skybridge-comes-out-a-winner-in-las-vegas/|title=DealBook \"SkyBridge Comes Out a Winner in Las Vegas|work=The New York Times|first=Azam|last=Ahmed|date=May 13, 2011|url-status=live|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20170728121128/https://dealbook.nytimes.com/2011/05/13/skybridge-comes-out-a-winner-in-las-vegas/|archivedate=July 28, 2017|df=mdy-all}}</ref>\n\nIn 2011, Scaramucci received the [[Ernst & Young Entrepreneur of the Year Award]] New York Award in the Financial Services category,<ref name=\"waynes\">{{cite news|url=http://www.waynesvilledailyguide.com/article/20110805/News/308059864|title=The Readers' Writers: Entrepreneur and author Anthony Scaramucci|date=August 5, 2011|publisher=Waynesville Daily Guide|accessdate=March 28, 2015|last=Kentner|first=DA|url-status=live|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20150402015046/http://www.waynesvilledailyguide.com/article/20110805/News/308059864|archivedate=April 2, 2015|df=mdy-all}}</ref> and in 2016 was ranked #85 in ''[[Worth (magazine)|Worth]]'' magazine's \"Power 100: The 100 Most Powerful People in Global Finance\".<ref>{{cite magazine |url=http://www.worth.com/power-100-2016/ |magazine=[[Worth (magazine)|Worth]] |title=The Power 100 |date=October 17, 2016 |access-date=February 18, 2017 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20161021195630/http://www.worth.com/power-100-2016/ |archivedate=October 21, 2016 |df=mdy-all }}</ref>\n\nIn May 2014, SkyBridge licensed the rights to ''[[Wall Street Week]]'', a financial television news program formerly hosted by [[Louis Rukeyser]] on [[PBS]]. Scaramucci hosted the show. Broadcast rights were transferred to [[Fox Broadcasting Company]] in 2016.<ref>{{cite news |url=https://variety.com/2016/tv/news/wall-street-week-fox-business-network-1201729591/ |title=Fox Business Network Picks Up 'Wall Street Week' |work=Variety |date=March 14, 2016 |last=Steinberg |first=Brian |url-status=live |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20170728130416/http://variety.com/2016/tv/news/wall-street-week-fox-business-network-1201729591/ |archivedate=July 28, 2017 | df=mdy-all }}</ref>\n\nOn January 17, 2017, SkyBridge announced a majority stake sale to RON Transatlantic EG and HNA Capital (U.S.) Holding, a Chinese conglomerate with close ties to [[China]]'s Communist Party. With the announcement, Scaramucci stepped down from his co-management role and ended his affiliation with SkyBridge and SALT.<ref>{{cite news |url=https://www.cnbc.com/2017/02/02/anthony-scaramucci-wont-get-announced-white-house-role-official-says.html |title=Anthony Scaramucci won't get announced White House role, official says |work=CNBC |date=February 2, 2017 |accessdate=February 2, 2017 |url-status=live |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20170202121621/http://www.cnbc.com/2017/02/02/anthony-scaramucci-wont-get-announced-white-house-role-official-says.html |archivedate=February 2, 2017 |df=mdy-all }}</ref><ref name=SBsale>{{Cite press release|url=http://www.prnewswire.com/news-releases/skybridge-capital-announces-definitive-purchase-agreement-to-sell-majority-stake-in-firm-300391910.html|title=SkyBridge Capital Announces Definitive Purchase Agreement To Sell Majority Stake in Firm|agency=PR Newswire|publisher=SkyBridge Capital|date=January 17, 2017|access-date=January 20, 2017|url-status=live|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20170119033509/http://www.prnewswire.com/news-releases/skybridge-capital-announces-definitive-purchase-agreement-to-sell-majority-stake-in-firm-300391910.html|archivedate=January 19, 2017|df=mdy-all}}</ref> In April 2018, it was announced that Scaramucci would be returning to SkyBridge after the deal with HNA Group had collapsed due to the lack of approval of the Committee on Foreign Investment in the United States, an inter-agency government committee.<ref>{{cite news |url=https://money.cnn.com/2018/04/30/investing/anthony-scaramucci-skybridge-hna/index.html |title=Anthony Scaramucci is rejoining hedge fund after sale collapses |date=April 30, 2018 |first=Matt |last=Egan |publisher=CNN Money |department=Business |access-date=November 2, 2018 }}</ref>\n\n==Career in politics==\n[[File:Anthony Scaramucci by Gage Skidmore.jpg|thumb|Scaramucci at 2016 [[FreedomFest]]]]\nScaramucci supported the presidential campaigns of [[Hillary Clinton]] and [[Barack Obama]].<ref name=\"collins\"/> In 2008, Scaramucci also served as a fundraiser for President [[Barack Obama]].<ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.bloomberg.com/news/2011-09-27/romney-lures-obama-wall-street-donors-in-race-for-campaign-cash.html|title=Bloomberg \"Romney Lures Away Obama's Wall Street Supporters in Race for Campaign Cash|url-status=live|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20140814023433/http://www.bloomberg.com/news/2011-09-27/romney-lures-obama-wall-street-donors-in-race-for-campaign-cash.html|archivedate=August 14, 2014|df=mdy-all}}</ref> In September 2010, however, Scaramucci asked Obama at a CNBC Town Hall meeting when he was going to \"stop whacking [[Wall Street]] like a [[pi\u00f1ata]].\"<ref name=\"Sanati\">{{cite news|url=https://dealbook.nytimes.com/2010/10/06/a-fund-managers-message-beyond-the-pinata/|title=The New York Times \"A Fund Manager's Message Beyond the 'Pinata'|first=Cyrus|last=Sanati|date=October 6, 2010|url-status=live|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20170728085434/https://dealbook.nytimes.com/2010/10/06/a-fund-managers-message-beyond-the-pinata/|archivedate=July 28, 2017|df=mdy-all}}</ref>\n\nScaramucci has [[Twitter|tweeted]] at various times that he has \"always been for strong gun control laws\", and that \"Republicans should support gay marriage\".<ref>{{cite news|url=http://www.washingtonexaminer.com/anthony-scaramuccis-old-tweets-reveal-liberal-views-on-climate-abortion-gay-rights-border-wall/article/2629415|title=Anthony Scaramucci's old tweets reveal liberal views on climate, abortion, gay rights, border wall|first=Anna|last=Giaritelli|publisher=[[The Washington Examiner]]|date=July 22, 2017|url-status=live|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20170723051054/http://www.washingtonexaminer.com/anthony-scaramuccis-old-tweets-reveal-liberal-views-on-climate-abortion-gay-rights-border-wall/article/2629415|archivedate=July 23, 2017|df=mdy-all}}</ref>\n\nHe served as the national finance co-chair for Mitt Romney's 2012 presidential campaign.<ref name=\"collins\"/>\n\nIn 2015, on a [[Fox Business Network]] television appearance, Scaramucci called Trump a \"hack politician\" whose rhetoric is \"anti-American and very, very divisive.\" He further warned Trump to \"cut it out now\", and \"stop all this crazy rhetoric.\" In December 2015, Scaramucci criticized Trump's call for a border wall between Mexico and the U.S. He also criticized Trump for \"making a fundamental mistake of trying to blame all of Islam and all Muslims for what is the ideology and the actions of a minority.\"<ref name=\"collins\">{{cite web|last1=Collins|first1=Ben|title=Anthony Scaramucci Loved Hillary, Gave to Obama, and Deleted Anti-Trump Tweets|url=http://www.thedailybeast.com/new-trump-hire-anthony-scaramucci-deletes-old-tweets-bashing-trump|work=Daily Beast|access-date=July 28, 2017|url-status=live|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20170724032738/http://www.thedailybeast.com/new-trump-hire-anthony-scaramucci-deletes-old-tweets-bashing-trump|archivedate=July 24, 2017|df=mdy-all}}</ref>\n\nAhead of the 2016 election, Scaramucci tweeted that he hoped Hillary Clinton would be the next president.<ref name=\"collins\"/> During the [[2016 United States presidential election|2016 presidential election]], Scaramucci first endorsed [[Scott Walker (politician)|Scott Walker]] and later [[Jeb Bush]]. In May 2016, after both Walker and Bush had withdrawn from the race, Scaramucci signed on to [[Donald Trump]]'s political campaign by joining the Trump Finance Committee.<ref>{{cite news|last1=Rucker|first1=Philip|title=Anthony Scaramucci, a top Republican fundraiser, signs on with Trump campaign|url=https://www.washingtonpost.com/news/post-politics/wp/2016/05/09/anthony-scaramucci-a-top-republican-fundraiser-signs-on-with-trump-campaign/|work=The Washington Post|date=May 9, 2016|url-status=live|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20170728061355/https://www.washingtonpost.com/news/post-politics/wp/2016/05/09/anthony-scaramucci-a-top-republican-fundraiser-signs-on-with-trump-campaign/|archivedate=July 28, 2017|df=mdy-all}}</ref> In November 2016, he was appointed to President-elect Trump's Presidential Transition Team Executive Committee.<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.wsj.com/articles/donald-trump-shuffles-transition-team-making-mike-pence-chairman-1478890592|title=Donald Trump Shuffles Transition Team, Making Mike Pence Chairman|last=Bender|first=Michael C.|date=November 12, 2016|newspaper=The Wall Street Journal|issn=0099-9660|access-date=November 14, 2016|url-status=live|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20161114041652/http://www.wsj.com/articles/donald-trump-shuffles-transition-team-making-mike-pence-chairman-1478890592|archivedate=November 14, 2016|df=mdy-all}}</ref>\n\nIn August 2019, Scaramucci said that he no longer supported the reelection of Donald Trump as US president. He was critical of Trump's divisive rhetoric.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.cnn.com/2019/08/12/politics/anthony-scaramucci-donald-trump-reelection-cnntv/index.html|title=Scaramucci no longer backs Trump's reelection, says change may be needed at top of ticket|author=Devan Cole|website=CNN|access-date=2019-08-13|date=August 12, 2019}}</ref>\n\n===Nomination to Office of Public Liaison===\nOn January 12, 2017, Scaramucci was named Assistant to President Trump and director of the [[White House Office of Public Engagement and Intergovernmental Affairs|White House Office of Public Liaison and Intergovernmental Affairs]].<ref name=\"auto1\">{{cite magazine |url=http://nymag.com/daily/intelligencer/2017/01/trump-wall-street-supporters.html |title=Long on Trump: Wall Streeters like Anthony Scaramucci bet heavy on the would-be president back when that seemed like a pretty dumb investment. Bonus time! |magazine=[[New York (magazine)|New York]] |date=January 23, 2017 |access-date=March 6, 2017 |first=Jessica |last=Pressler |url-status=live |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20170307130923/http://nymag.com/daily/intelligencer/2017/01/trump-wall-street-supporters.html |archivedate=March 7, 2017 |df=mdy-all }}</ref> On January 23, he told [[New York (magazine)|''New York'' magazine]]: the \"thing I have learned about these people in Washington is they have no money. So what happens when they have no fucking money is they write about what seat they are in and what the title is. Fucking congressmen act like that. They are fucking jackasses\".<ref name=\"auto1\"/> On the topic of working in Washington DC, he said: \"[\u2026] that\u2019s Washington. That\u2019s how they operate. They try to caricaturise you, and dehumanise you, so that you lose your voice. They wanted to get me by grinding out a public image of me that is dramatically different from the reality.\"<ref>{{Cite news|last=Aitkenhead|first=Decca|url=https://www.theguardian.com/us-news/2018/jun/09/anthony-scaramucci-life-after-11-days-in-white-house-trump-decca-aitkenhead|title=Anthony Scaramucci: 'I\u2019m in the game for a fight. I love the fight'|date=2018-06-09|work=The Guardian|access-date=2020-02-14|language=en-GB|issn=0261-3077}}</ref>\n\nScaramucci attended the [[World Economic Forum]] in [[Davos]] January 16\u201317 as the representative for the [[Trump transition]] team.<ref name=TrumpsTranslatorBuzzfeed20170117 /> Part of his mission was to reassure attendees about the incoming [[Trump administration]].<ref name=TrumpsTranslatorBuzzfeed20170117 /> Following Chinese President [[Xi Jinping]], he gave a talk warning against protectionism and championing free trade.<ref name=TrumpsTranslatorBuzzfeed20170117>{{cite web|title=Trump's Translator Wants The Global Elite To Understand Him|url=https://www.buzzfeed.com/miriamelder/trumps-translator-wants-the-global-elite-to-understand-him|website=[[Buzzfeed News]]|date=January 17, 2017|access-date=June 20, 2018|last=Elder|first=Miriam}}</ref>\n\n[[Fox Business]] reported on January 31, 2017, that \"Scaramucci's delayed appointment underscores some of the tensions building inside the Trump White House, as various aides and advisers continue to jockey for his attention and to retain and expand their power\".<ref>{{cite news |url=http://www.foxbusiness.com/politics/2017/01/31/story-behind-scaramucci-s-delayed-appointment-amid-trump-white-house-bickering.html |title=The story behind Scaramucci's delayed appointment amid Trump White House bickering |publisher=Fox Business |date=January 31, 2017 |access-date=March 9, 2017 |first1=Charles |last1=Gasparino |first2=Brian |last2=Schwartz |url-status=live |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20170204085001/http://www.foxbusiness.com/politics/2017/01/31/story-behind-scaramucci-s-delayed-appointment-amid-trump-white-house-bickering.html |archivedate=February 4, 2017 |df=mdy-all }}</ref> According to ''[[Politico]]'', on January 31, 2017, with Scaramucci's appointment still pending approval by the [[United States Office of Government Ethics]] (OGE), Trump's chief of staff [[Reince Priebus]] called Scaramucci \"to tell him he should pull out of consideration\". They reported that Priebus opposed Scaramucci's appointment because of Scaramucci's stake in SkyBridge Capital.<ref name=\"politico\" /> Several senior White House officials questioned the significance of any internal feuding in Scaramucci's appointment delay, however, officials have cited the lengthy process to conclude his sale of SkyBridge as the reason of the delay in his appointment.<ref>{{cite news |url=http://www.foxbusiness.com/politics/2017/02/01/trump-team-reconsiders-scaramucci-s-white-house-role.html |title=Trump Team Reconsiders Scaramucci's White House Role |newspaper=Fox Business |first1=Charlie |last1=Gasparino |department=Charlie Breaks It |first2=Brian |last2=Schwartz |date=February 1, 2017 |access-date=February 2, 2017 |url-status=live |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20170201210200/http://www.foxbusiness.com/politics/2017/02/01/trump-team-reconsiders-scaramucci-s-white-house-role.html |archivedate=February 1, 2017 |df=mdy-all }}</ref> [[Reuters]] reported on February 1 that Scaramucci would not get the director role.<ref>{{cite news |agency=Reuters |url=http://in.reuters.com/article/usa-trump-scaramucci-idINL4N1FN0RK |title=Anthony Scaramucci will not get White House role \u2013 NYT |date=February 1, 2017 |access-date=February 2, 2017 |url-status=live |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20170202034248/http://in.reuters.com/article/usa-trump-scaramucci-idINL4N1FN0RK |archivedate=February 2, 2017 |df=mdy-all }}</ref> In a February 2017 ''New York'' magazine article, Priebus was quoted as saying rumors that he interfered with the hiring were \"not true\".<ref>{{cite news |url=http://nymag.com/daily/intelligencer/2017/02/bannon-and-priebus-want-you-to-know-they-are-friends.html |title=Steve Bannon and Reince Priebus Want You to Know They Are Friends |work=[[New York (magazine)|New York]] |date=February 9, 2017 |access-date=February 10, 2017 |first=Olivia |last=Nuzzi |quote='It's not true,' Priebus said of the rumors that he nixed the hire. 'The person closest to Anthony in the entire West Wing is me,' he said. |url-status=live |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20170209184812/http://nymag.com/daily/intelligencer/2017/02/bannon-and-priebus-want-you-to-know-they-are-friends.html |archivedate=February 9, 2017 |df=mdy-all }}</ref>\n\nOn March 6, 2017, the White House announced the appointment of Ideagen founder and former CEO [[George Sifakis]] as director for the Office of Public Liaison,<ref name=Sifakis>{{cite press release |title=President Donald J. Trump Announces White House Staff Appointments |date=March 6, 2017 |access-date=March 7, 2017 |url=https://www.whitehouse.gov/the-press-office/2017/03/06/president-donald-j-trump-announces-white-house-staff-appointments |publisher=The White House |url-status=live |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20170307004613/https://www.whitehouse.gov/the-press-office/2017/03/06/president-donald-j-trump-announces-white-house-staff-appointments |archivedate=March 7, 2017 |df=mdy-all }}</ref> instead of Scaramucci. The next day, Politico reported that \"White House Chief of Staff Reince Priebus is still considering offering financier Anthony Scaramucci a role\" in the administration.<ref name=politico>{{cite news |url=http://www.politico.com/story/2017/03/anthony-scaramucci-white-house-role-235804 |title=Scaramucci still in consideration for White House role, official says |newspaper=Politico |date=March 7, 2016 |access-date=March 9, 2017 |first=Tara |last=Palmeri |url-status=live |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20170308024205/http://www.politico.com/story/2017/03/anthony-scaramucci-white-house-role-235804 |archivedate=March 8, 2017 |df=mdy-all }}</ref>\n\nOn June 26, 2017, three network investigative journalists\u2014Thomas Frank, [[Eric Lichtblau]], and Lex Haris\u2014resigned from [[CNN]] after the network retracted a story that connected Scaramucci to a $10 billion Russian investment fund. CNN issued an apology to Scaramucci (who accepted the apology), with the network saying the online story (which appeared on CNN's website and was not aired on television) did not meet its [[Journalism ethics and standards|editorial standards]].<ref name=\"Battaglio\">{{cite news|last=Battaglio|first=Stephen|url=http://www.latimes.com/business/hollywood/la-fi-ct-cnn-resignation-20170626-story.html|title=Three CNN journalists resign over retracted Trump-Russia story|date=June 27, 2017|work=[[Los Angeles Times]]|access-date=June 27, 2017|url-status=live|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20170627032249/http://www.latimes.com/business/hollywood/la-fi-ct-cnn-resignation-20170626-story.html|archivedate=June 27, 2017|df=mdy-all}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=http://politi.co/2hcrEJB|title=3 CNN staffers resign over retracted Scaramucci-Russia story|last=Gold|first=Hadas|website=POLITICO|language=en|access-date=2020-03-11}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.telegraph.co.uk/news/2017/06/27/trump-attacks-cnn-resignations-three-journalists-retracted-russia/|title=Trump attacks CNN after resignations of three journalists over retracted Russia-related story|date=June 27, 2017|work=The Telegraph|url-status=live|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20170628023103/http://www.telegraph.co.uk/news/2017/06/27/trump-attacks-cnn-resignations-three-journalists-retracted-russia/|archivedate=June 28, 2017|access-date=June 28, 2017|df=mdy-all}}</ref> Scaramucci said the original story was not true; CNN did not say the story was false, but said that it \"wasn't solid enough\" to be published.<ref name=\"Battaglio\" />\n\n===Export\u2013Import Bank of the United States===\nEffective June 19, 2017, Scaramucci was named senior vice president and chief strategy officer for the [[U.S. Export-Import Bank]]. He was also still under consideration for a post as ambassador to the [[Organisation for Economic Co-operation and Development]].<ref>{{cite news |url=http://www.businessinsider.com/scaramucci-gets-trump-job-at-us-export-import-bank-2017-6 |title=The hedge funder who had long hoped to work for Trump finally got a job |date=June 27, 2017 |agency=Reuters |newspaper=[[Business Insider]] |access-date=June 28, 2017 |url-status=live |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20170711080606/http://www.businessinsider.com/scaramucci-gets-trump-job-at-us-export-import-bank-2017-6 |archivedate=July 11, 2017 |df=mdy-all }}</ref><ref>{{cite news |url=http://www.foxnews.com/politics/2017/06/27/trump-adviser-scaramucci-joins-export-import-bank.html |title=Trump adviser Scaramucci joins Export-Import Bank |date=June 27, 2017 |publisher=Fox News Channel |access-date=June 28, 2017 |first=Serafin |last=G\u00f3mez |department=Politics |url-status=live |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20170628024002/http://www.foxnews.com/politics/2017/06/27/trump-adviser-scaramucci-joins-export-import-bank.html |archivedate=June 28, 2017 |df=mdy-all }}</ref>\n\n===White House Communications Director===\nOn July 21, 2017, President [[Donald Trump]] appointed Scaramucci [[White House Communications Director]].<ref name = record/> The White House announcement of Scaramucci said he would \"report directly to the President\" rather than to the [[White House chief of staff]], as White House Press Secretary [[Sean Spicer]] had.<ref>{{Cite news|url=http://thehill.com/homenews/administration/343253-white-house-scaramucci-will-report-directly-to-trump|title=White House: Scaramucci will report directly to Trump|last=Bowden|first=John|date=July 21, 2017|work=The Hill|access-date=July 27, 2017|url-status=live|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20170723051706/http://thehill.com/homenews/administration/343253-white-house-scaramucci-will-report-directly-to-trump|archivedate=July 23, 2017|df=mdy-all}}</ref><ref name=\"ny-27jul2017\">{{Cite news|url=http://www.newyorker.com/news/ryan-lizza/anthony-scaramucci-called-me-to-unload-about-white-house-leakers-reince-priebus-and-steve-bannon|title=Anthony Scaramucci Called Me to Unload About White House Leakers, Reince Priebus, and Steve Bannon|last=Lizza|first=Ryan|date=July 27, 2017|newspaper=The New Yorker|access-date=July 27, 2017|url-status=live|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20170727210016/https://www.newyorker.com/news/ryan-lizza/anthony-scaramucci-called-me-to-unload-about-white-house-leakers-reince-priebus-and-steve-bannon|archivedate=July 27, 2017|df=mdy-all}}</ref> On the day that Scaramucci's appointment was announced, Spicer resigned.<ref name=\"nytimes1\">{{cite news|last1=Thrush|first1=Glenn|title=Sean Spicer Resigns as White House Press Secretary|url=https://www.nytimes.com/2017/07/21/us/politics/sean-spicer-resigns-as-white-house-press-secretary.html|accessdate=July 21, 2017|work=The New York Times|date=July 21, 2017|url-status=live|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20170721160008/https://www.nytimes.com/2017/07/21/us/politics/sean-spicer-resigns-as-white-house-press-secretary.html|archivedate=July 21, 2017|df=mdy-all}}</ref> ''[[The New York Times]]'' reported that he had done so after advising Trump that he \"vehemently disagreed\" with the appointment of Scaramucci.<ref name=\"nytimes1\"/><ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.bloomberg.com/news/articles/2017-07-21/scaramucci-said-to-join-white-house-as-spicer-reported-to-resign |title=Trump Hires Scaramucci as Communications Director, Spicer Resigns |publisher=Bloomberg |date=May 30, 2017 |access-date=July 21, 2017 |url-status=live |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20170721170216/https://www.bloomberg.com/news/articles/2017-07-21/scaramucci-said-to-join-white-house-as-spicer-reported-to-resign |archivedate=July 21, 2017 |df=mdy-all }}</ref> Trump's chief of staff [[Reince Priebus]] also had \"vehement objections\" to his hiring.<ref name=\"ny-27jul2017\"/> At this time, Scaramucci was taunted by \"email prankster\" [[James Linton (hacker)|James Linton]] masquerading as Reince Priebus.<ref>{{cite news |last1=Booth |first1=Robert |title=Prankster says he targeted Scaramucci over mental health insult |url=https://www.theguardian.com/technology/2017/aug/01/prankster-says-he-targeted-scaramucci-over-mental-health-insult |accessdate=10 April 2020 |date=1 August 2017}}</ref>\n\nIn July 26, 2017, journalist Ryan Lizza reported that Scaramucci called him to identify who leaked information to ''The New Yorker'', revealing some disagreements with Chief of Staff Reince Priebus and White House advisor Steve Bannon. Scaramucci believed the conversation to be off the record.<ref>{{Cite news|last=Crilly|first=Rob|url=https://www.telegraph.co.uk/news/2017/08/13/anthony-scaramucci-says-white-house-plotters-working-against/|title=Anthony Scaramucci says White House leakers are working against Donald Trump, in first interview since he was fired|date=2017-08-13|work=The Telegraph|access-date=2020-02-07|language=en-GB|issn=0307-1235}}</ref>\n\nDuring the interview and in a tweet immediately afterward, Scaramucci said that he had contacted or would be contacting the [[FBI]] and the [[U.S. Department of Justice|Department of Justice]], asking them to investigate Priebus for allegedly \"leaking\" his financial-disclosure form to a ''[[Politico]]'' reporter. Scaramucci later deleted the tweet. Lizza said the form was obtained from publicly available data at the [[Export\u2013Import Bank of the United States|U.S. Export-Import Bank]].<ref>{{cite news | last = Blake | first = Aaron | title = Anthony Scaramucci's vulgarity is one thing. The bigger story is his deception. | newspaper = The Washington Post | date = July 28, 2017 | url = https://www.washingtonpost.com/pb/news/the-fix/wp/2017/07/28/anthony-scaramuccis-vulgarity-is-one-thing-the-bigger-story-is-his-deception/?outputType=accessibility&nid=menu_nav_accessibilityforscreenreader | access-date = August 1, 2017 | url-status=live | archiveurl = https://web.archive.org/web/20170801202120/https://www.washingtonpost.com/pb/news/the-fix/wp/2017/07/28/anthony-scaramuccis-vulgarity-is-one-thing-the-bigger-story-is-his-deception/?outputType=accessibility&nid=menu_nav_accessibilityforscreenreader | archivedate = August 1, 2017 | df = mdy-all }}</ref>\n\nOn July 28, Priebus's resignation as chief of staff was announced; Priebus said that he had resigned on July 27. Also on July 28, Trump announced that he had named retired general [[John F. Kelly]] as his new chief of staff.<ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.nytimes.com/2017/07/28/us/politics/reince-priebus-white-house-trump.html|title=Reince Priebus Pushed Out After Rocky Tenure as Trump Chief of Staff|first1=Peter|last1=Baker|first2=Maggie|last2=Haberman|date=July 28, 2017|work=New York Times|url-status=live|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20170729021432/https://www.nytimes.com/2017/07/28/us/politics/reince-priebus-white-house-trump.html|archivedate=July 29, 2017|df=mdy-all}}</ref>\n\nOn July 31, 2017, Trump dismissed Scaramucci from his role as communications director on the recommendation of Kelly, who wanted him removed because he did not think Scaramucci was disciplined and believed Scaramucci had lost his credibility.<ref name=nytimes731>{{cite news|url=https://www.nytimes.com/2017/07/31/us/politics/anthony-scaramucci-white-house.html|title=Trump Removes Anthony Scaramucci From Communications Director Role|date=July 31, 2017|accessdate=July 31, 2017|work=The New York Times|url-status=live|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20170731183613/https://www.nytimes.com/2017/07/31/us/politics/anthony-scaramucci-white-house.html|archivedate=July 31, 2017|df=mdy-all}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.cnbc.com/2017/07/31/trump-removes-anthony-scaramucci-from-communications-director-role-ny-times.html|title=Trump removes Anthony Scaramucci from communications director role|work=[[CNBC]]|last=Pramuk|first=Jacob|date=July 31, 2017|access-date=July 31, 2017|url-status=live|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20170731185528/https://www.cnbc.com/2017/07/31/trump-removes-anthony-scaramucci-from-communications-director-role-ny-times.html|archivedate=July 31, 2017|df=mdy-all}}</ref><ref>{{cite news | last = Jackson | first = Hallie | title = What Really Happened to Anthony Scaramucci | newspaper = NBC News | date = August 1, 2017 | url = http://www.nbcnews.com/politics/white-house/what-really-happened-scaramucci-n788356 | access-date = August 1, 2017 | url-status=live | archiveurl = https://web.archive.org/web/20170801045143/http://www.nbcnews.com/politics/white-house/what-really-happened-scaramucci-n788356 | archivedate = August 1, 2017 | df = mdy-all }}</ref><ref name=\":0\" /> As one of his first acts after being sworn in as Chief of Staff, Kelly reportedly invited Scaramucci to his office and told him he was being let go.<ref name=\":0\">{{cite news|url=http://www.cnn.com/2017/07/31/politics/anthony-scaramucci/index.html|title=Anthony Scaramucci out as White House communications director|last1=Merica|first1=Dan|last2=Zeleny|first2=Jeff|last3=Acosta|first3=Jim|date=July 31, 2017|work=CNN|accessdate=August 1, 2017|url-status=live|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20170801001920/http://www.cnn.com/2017/07/31/politics/anthony-scaramucci/index.html|archivedate=August 1, 2017|df=mdy-all}}</ref> An official White House statement indicated that Scaramucci \"will be leaving\" his post \"to give Chief of Staff John Kelly a clean slate and the ability to build his own team.\"<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.whitehouse.gov/the-press-office/2017/07/31/statement-press-secretary|title=Statement from the Press Secretary|date=July 31, 2017|work=The White House, Office of the Press Secretary|access-date=July 31, 2017|url-status=dead|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20170731192205/https://www.whitehouse.gov/the-press-office/2017/07/31/statement-press-secretary|archivedate=July 31, 2017|df=mdy-all}}</ref> Scaramucci's tenure of eleven days is tied for shortest in history for that position with [[Jack Koehler]] in the [[Presidency of Ronald Reagan|Reagan administration]].<ref name=record>{{cite news|url=http://www.nbcnews.com/politics/politics-news/scaramucci-sets-new-record-shortest-term-communications-director-n788281|title=Scaramucci Sets New Record for Shortest Term as Communications Director|last=Santos|first=Amanda Proen\u00e7a|date=July 31, 2017|work=NBC News|accessdate=July 31, 2017|url-status=live|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20170801002231/http://www.nbcnews.com/politics/politics-news/scaramucci-sets-new-record-shortest-term-communications-director-n788281|archivedate=August 1, 2017|df=mdy-all}}</ref>\n\n==Other activities==\nScaramucci paid $100,000 to have SkyBridge's logo in the film ''[[Wall Street: Money Never Sleeps]]'' (2010), along with two cameo appearances.<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.telegraph.co.uk/news/2017/07/31/gucci-scaramucci-paid-100000-appear-wall-street-sequel-according/|title='Gucci Scaramucci' reportedly spent $100,000 on 15-second cameo in Wall Street film sequel|last=Nianias|first=Helen|date=2017-07-31|work=The Telegraph|access-date=2020-02-04|language=en-GB|issn=0307-1235}}</ref><ref name=schuster>{{cite web|last1=Schuster|first1=Dana|title=Scaramucci's fed-up wife filed for divorce while nine months pregnant|url=http://pagesix.com/2017/07/29/scaramuccis-fed-up-wife-filed-for-divorce-while-nine-months-pregnant/|work=New York Post|accessdate=July 30, 2017|url-status=live|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20170730014413/http://pagesix.com/2017/07/29/scaramuccis-fed-up-wife-filed-for-divorce-while-nine-months-pregnant/|archivedate=July 30, 2017|df=mdy-all}}</ref>\n\nHe is the author of four books:\n* ''Goodbye [[Gordon Gekko]]: How to Find Your Fortune Without Losing Your Soul'' (2010)<ref name=\"The Economist\">{{cite news |url=http://www.economist.com/node/18681778 |newspaper=[[The Economist]] |date=May 12, 2011 |title=Power and pi\u00f1atas: Anthony Scaramucci, hedge-fund ambassador |access-date=March 9, 2017 |url-status=live |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20170622165701/http://www.economist.com/node/18681778 |archivedate=June 22, 2017 |df=mdy-all }}</ref><ref>{{cite web | url=https://www.nytimes.com/2010/10/02/business/02nocera.html | title=Still Stuck in Denial on Wall St. | work=The New York Times | date=October 1, 2010 | accessdate=March 28, 2015 | last=Nocera | first=Joe | url-status=live | archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20150403170204/http://www.nytimes.com/2010/10/02/business/02nocera.html | archivedate=April 3, 2015 | df=mdy-all }}</ref>\n* ''The Little Book of Hedge Funds: What You Need to Know About Hedge Funds but the Managers Won't Tell You'' (2012)<ref>{{cite news |url=http://www.cbsnews.com/video/watch/?id=7411762n |publisher=CBS News |title='The Little Book of Hedge Funds' by Anthony Scaramucci |date=June 15, 2012 |access-date=March 9, 2017 |first=Jeff |last=Glor |url-status=live |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20120619060135/http://www.cbsnews.com/video/watch/?id=7411762n |archivedate=June 19, 2012 |df=mdy-all }}</ref>\n* ''Hopping Over the Rabbit Hole: How Entrepreneurs Turn Failure Into Success'' (2016)<ref>{{cite news|last1=Taub|first1=Rob|title=Hopping Over The Rabbit Hole: How Entrepreneurs Turn Failure Into Success|url=http://www.huffingtonpost.com/rob-taub/book-review-hopping-over_b_12588720.html|accessdate=July 31, 2017|work=Huffington Post|date=October 24, 2016|url-status=live|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20170819054216/http://www.huffingtonpost.com/rob-taub/book-review-hopping-over_b_12588720.html|archivedate=August 19, 2017|df=mdy-all}}</ref>\n* ''Trump, the Blue-Collar President'' (2018)<ref>{{cite news|last1=Schuster|first1=Dana|title=Now it\u2019s Scaramucci\u2019s turn to give inside look at Trump White House in new book|url=https://www.marketwatch.com/story/scaramucci-gives-his-inside-look-at-trump-white-house-in-new-book-2018-10-21|accessdate=October 23, 2018|work=The New York Post|date=October 21, 2018|url-status=live|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20181023180153/https://www.marketwatch.com/story/scaramucci-gives-his-inside-look-at-trump-white-house-in-new-book-2018-10-21|archivedate=October 23, 2018|df=mdy-all}}</ref>\n\nHe joined [[Fox Business Network]] as a contributor in 2014, and in March 2016 served as host of the financial television show ''[[Wall Street Week]]''.<ref>{{cite web | url=https://nypost.com/2014/09/10/scaramucci-inks-deal-with-fox-business/ | title=Scaramucci inks deal with Fox Business | work=New York Post | date=September 10, 2014 | accessdate=March 28, 2015 | author=Celarier, Michelle | url-status=live | archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20150324072643/http://nypost.com/2014/09/10/scaramucci-inks-deal-with-fox-business/ | archivedate=March 24, 2015 | df=mdy-all }}</ref><ref name=\"Fox Business Network\">{{cite web | url=http://www.foxbusiness.com/features/2016/03/14/fox-business-network-welcomes-iconic-wall-street-week-program.html/ | title=FOX Business Network Welcomes Iconic 'Wall Street Week' Program | publisher=Fox Business Network | date=March 14, 2016 | url-status=live | archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20160406111620/http://www.foxbusiness.com/features/2016/03/14/fox-business-network-welcomes-iconic-wall-street-week-program.html | archivedate=April 6, 2016 | df=mdy-all }}</ref>\n\nScaramucci, along with restaurateur Eytan Sugarman and financier Nelson Braff, founded the [[Hunt & Fish Club]] steakhouse and seafood restaurant in [[Midtown Manhattan]] in New York City, which opened in 2015.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.nydailynews.com/life-style/eats/eats-beat-hunt-fish-club-opens-w-44th-st-article-1.2067642|title=Eats Beat: Steak-seafood spot Hunt & Fish Club opens on W. 44th St.|first=Gina|last=Pace|work=New York Daily News|date=January 11, 2015}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.townandcountrymag.com/leisure/dining/news/g1278/how-to-find-a-rich-husband-on-your-lunchbreak/|title=How To Find A Rich Husband On Your Lunchbreak|first=Tucker|last=Westbrook|date=May 6, 2015|work=Town & Country}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.businessinsider.com/inside-new-yorks-hunt-and-fish-club-2015-1|title=Inside Hunt & Fish Club, Wall Street\u2019s New Favorite Steakhouse|first=Megan|last=Willett|website=Business Insider|date=January 29, 2015}}</ref><ref name=\"auto2\">{{Cite web|url=https://www.wsj.com/articles/hunt-fish-club-a-homage-to-old-new-york-1424224351|title=Hunt & Fish Club, a Homage to Old New York; A swanky new Midtown steakhouse|work=The Wall Street Journal|date=February 17, 2015}}</ref><ref name=\"auto\">{{Cite web|url=https://nypost.com/2015/01/28/inside-hunt-fish-where-beauties-trawl-for-sugar-daddies/|title=Inside Hunt & Fish, where beauties trawl for sugar daddies|first=Dana|last=Schuster|date=January 29, 2015|work=The New York Post}}</ref>\n\nHe is the vice chair of the Kennedy Center Corporate Fund Board, and a trustee of the United States Olympic & Paralympic Foundation.<ref>{{cite web | url=http://www.saltconference.com/speakers/scaramucci_photo.html | title=Conference Speakers: Anthony Scaramucci | publisher=SALT Conference | access-date=March 28, 2015 | url-status=dead | archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20150331221645/http://www.saltconference.com/speakers/scaramucci_photo.html | archivedate=March 31, 2015 | df=mdy-all }}</ref> He is also a member of the [[Council on Foreign Relations]]. Scaramucci was a member of the New York City Financial Services Advisory Committee from 2007 to 2012.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.nyssa.org/programs/mastercalendar/ctl/viewdetail/mid/512/itemid/2318/d/20150415.aspx|title=Generating Alpha in Volatile Markets|publisher=New York Society of Security Analysts|accessdate=March 28, 2015|url-status=dead|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20170731190655/http://www.independent.co.uk/news/world/americas/us-politics/anthony-scaramucci-wife-miss-birth-son-donald-trump-white-house-communications-deidre-scaramucci-a7868351.html|archivedate=July 31, 2017|df=mdy-all}}</ref>\n\nIn April 2016, Scaramucci and two other [[New York Mets]] fans bought [[Mike Piazza]]'s jersey from the September 21, 2001, game against the [[Atlanta Braves]], the first professional baseball game played in New York following the [[September 11 attacks|9/11 attacks]], in which Piazza hit a game-winning 8th-inning home run. The jersey was purchased in a private auction for $365,000, the highest price ever paid for a modern-day jersey, which Scaramucci described as having \"tremendous artistic symbolism\". The new owners wanted the jersey accessible to fans, so it will be displayed on a rotating basis among the [[9/11 Memorial Museum]], [[Citi Field]], and the [[National Baseball Hall of Fame]].<ref>{{cite news | url=https://nypost.com/2016/04/14/mets-fans-spend-big-to-rescue-piazza-911-jersey-as-museum-piece/ | title=Mets fans spend big to rescue Piazza 9/11 jersey as museum piece | newspaper=New York Post | date=April 14, 2016 | last=Kernan | first=Kevin | access-date=July 21, 2017 | url-status=live | archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20170728141940/http://nypost.com/2016/04/14/mets-fans-spend-big-to-rescue-piazza-911-jersey-as-museum-piece/ | archivedate=July 28, 2017 | df=mdy-all }}</ref><ref>{{cite news |url=https://nypost.com/2016/04/05/mike-piazza-just-cant-believe-mets-sold-his-famed-911-jersey/ |title=Frustrated Mike Piazza speaks out on Mets' 9/11 jersey shocker |newspaper=New York Post |date=April 5, 2016 |last=Kernan |first=Kevin |access-date=July 21, 2017 |url-status=live |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20170728145804/http://nypost.com/2016/04/05/mike-piazza-just-cant-believe-mets-sold-his-famed-911-jersey/ |archivedate=July 28, 2017 |df=mdy-all }}</ref>\n\nOn October 2, 2017, Scaramucci launched the online media venture '''the Scaramucci Post'''. At a press conference, Scaramucci said that \"we have no idea what the Scaramucci Post is and neither do you. But, we launched it today and we launched with great fanfare and so we'll have to see how the whole thing unfolds.\"<ref>{{Cite news|url=http://fortune.com/2017/10/03/the-mooch-launches-the-scaramucci-post/|title='We Have No Idea What the Scaramucci Post Is and Neither Do You': The Mooch Launches His New Venture|work=Fortune|date=October 3, 2017|access-date=October 23, 2017|language=en|url-status=live|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20171024091645/http://fortune.com/2017/10/03/the-mooch-launches-the-scaramucci-post/|archivedate=October 24, 2017|df=mdy-all}}</ref> Later that month, the Post was criticized for posting a Twitter poll asking \"How many Jews were killed in the Holocaust?\". The tweet was posted by Scaramucci's business partner Lance Laifer without the approval of Scaramucci, who was in London at the time; when he found out about the tweet, Scaramucci was reportedly furious at Laifer.<ref>{{Cite news|url=http://www.newsweek.com/anthony-scaramucci-scaramucci-post-holocaust-jews-twitter-poll-686629|title=Anthony Scaramucci's new media venture offends Twitter with poll about Jewish Holocaust deaths|date=October 17, 2017|work=Newsweek|access-date=October 23, 2017|language=en|url-status=live|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20171024043129/http://www.newsweek.com/anthony-scaramucci-scaramucci-post-holocaust-jews-twitter-poll-686629|archivedate=October 24, 2017|df=mdy-all}}</ref> The tweet was soon taken down, and Scaramucci subsequently wrote that \"If anyone was offended by this act, you have both my sincere personal apology and commitment that it will never happen again\", and pledged to donate $25,000 to the [[Simon Wiesenthal Center]]. Subsequently, however, the Post tweeted that they had changed their mind on the poll, defending their decision to post it and accusing their critics of \"laziness and mob-mentality\", claiming that the poll was designed to illustrate that memory was fading about the death of 6 million Jews.<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.vanityfair.com/news/2017/10/scaramucci-post-tries-fails-to-quell-its-sick-holocaust-curiosity|date=October 20, 2017|title=Scaramucci Post Tries, Fails to Quell Its Sick Holocaust Curiosity|last=Levin|first=Bess|work=The Hive|access-date=October 23, 2017|language=en|url-status=live|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20180208172722/https://www.vanityfair.com/news/2017/10/scaramucci-post-tries-fails-to-quell-its-sick-holocaust-curiosity|archivedate=December 24, 2017|df=mdy-all}}</ref>\n\nOn January 13, 2019, it was announced Scaramucci would be a participant in the [[Celebrity Big Brother 2 (U.S.)|second American season]] of the reality show competition ''[[Celebrity Big Brother (U.S. TV series)|Celebrity Big Brother]];''<ref name=\":4\">{{cite web|url=https://www.hollywoodreporter.com/live-feed/celebrity-big-brother-cast-revealed-ryan-lochte-anthony-scaramucci-dina-lohan-more-1175684|title='Celebrity Big Brother' Cast Includes Anthony Scaramucci, Dina Lohan and Ryan Lochte|last=Porreca|first=Brian|date=13 January 2019|website=www.hollywoodreporter.com/|publisher=[[The Hollywood Reporter]]|access-date=13 January 2019}}</ref><ref name=\":5\">{{cite web|url=https://ew.com/tv/2019/01/13/celebrity-big-brother-cast-anthony-scaramucci/|title=Anthony Scaramucci among 12 new Celebrity Big Brother houseguests|last=Ross|first=Dalton|date=13 January 2019|website=www.ew.com/|publisher=[[Entertainment Weekly]]|access-date=13 January 2019}}</ref> though, in a twist, it was revealed he was a Fake HouseGuest on the show.\n\n=== Tufts controversy ===\nIn June 2016, Scaramucci joined the Board of Advisors of the [[Fletcher School of Law and Diplomacy]], located at his alma mater of Tufts University.<ref name=\":2\">{{Cite news|url=https://www.bostonglobe.com/metro/2017/11/06/some-students-alums-say-the-mooch-doesn-belong-tufts-board/cmnOWHgNo02d496sbMcKFP/story.html|title=Some students, alums say 'The Mooch' doesn't belong on Tufts board|last=Fernandes|first=Deirdre|date=7 November 2017|work=Boston Globe|access-date=2017-11-28|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20171201033908/https://www.bostonglobe.com/metro/2017/11/06/some-students-alums-say-the-mooch-doesn-belong-tufts-board/cmnOWHgNo02d496sbMcKFP/story.html|archive-date=December 1, 2017|url-status=live|df=mdy-all}}</ref> In early November 2017, 240 Tufts students, faculty, and alumni signed an online petition calling for Scaramucci's removal from the position.<ref name=\":2\" /> One Fletcher graduate student, Camilo Caballero, wrote a pair of op-eds in Tufts' independent student newspaper, ''[[The Tufts Daily]]'', on November 6 and 13.<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://tuftsdaily.com/opinion/2017/11/06/op-ed-seeking-power-values-power-money/|title=Op-Ed: Seeking power of values over power of money|last=Caballero|first=Camilo|date=2017-11-06|work=The Tufts Daily|access-date=2017-11-28|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20171127182942/https://tuftsdaily.com/opinion/2017/11/06/op-ed-seeking-power-values-power-money/|archive-date=November 27, 2017|url-status=live|language=en-US|df=mdy-all}}</ref><ref>{{Cite news|url=https://tuftsdaily.com/opinion/2017/11/13/op-ed-tuftsfletcher-administration-fell-scaramuccis-trap-students-faculty-smarter/|title=Op-Ed: Tufts/Fletcher administration fell into Scaramucci's trap: Students and faculty are smarter|last=Caballero|first=Camilo|date=2017-11-13|work=The Tufts Daily|access-date=2017-11-28|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20171128161943/https://tuftsdaily.com/opinion/2017/11/13/op-ed-tuftsfletcher-administration-fell-scaramuccis-trap-students-faculty-smarter/|archive-date=November 28, 2017|url-status=live|language=en-US|df=mdy-all}}</ref> On November 21, 2017, lawyers representing Scaramucci sent a [[Cease and desist|cease-and-desist]] letter to the ''Daily,'' alleging that the op-eds contained factual inaccuracies which attempted to defame him.<ref name=\":3\">{{Cite news|url=https://tuftsdaily.com/opinion/2017/11/27/cease-and-desist-letter/|title=Claiming defamation, lawyer for Anthony Scaramucci demands retractions from Daily op-eds|last=|first=|date=2017-11-27|work=The Tufts Daily|access-date=2017-11-28|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20171127072106/https://tuftsdaily.com/opinion/2017/11/27/cease-and-desist-letter/|archive-date=November 27, 2017|url-status=live|language=en-US|df=mdy-all}}</ref> The letter demanded that Caballero and the ''Daily'' issue a retraction and an apology for its allegedly \"defamatory\" statements, threatening a lawsuit if the paper did not comply within five business days.<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.bostonglobe.com/metro/2017/11/26/tufts-postpones-scaramucci-event-after-threatens-student-and-paper-with-lawsuit/uKOsaakB8dH3cyiyYcwiyL/story.html|title=Tufts postpones Scaramucci event after he threatens student and paper with lawsuit|last=Hilliard|first=John|date=27 November 2017|work=Boston Globe|access-date=2017-11-28|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20171127225034/https://www.bostonglobe.com/metro/2017/11/26/tufts-postpones-scaramucci-event-after-threatens-student-and-paper-with-lawsuit/uKOsaakB8dH3cyiyYcwiyL/story.html|archive-date=November 27, 2017|url-status=live|df=mdy-all}}</ref><ref name=\":1\">{{Cite news|url=https://www.washingtonpost.com/news/grade-point/wp/2017/11/27/tufts-postpones-scaramucci-talk-after-he-threatens-to-sue-student/|title=Tufts postpones Scaramucci talk after he threatens to sue student|last=Svrluga|first=Susan|date=2017-11-27|work=Washington Post|access-date=2017-11-28|language=en-US|issn=0190-8286|url-status=live|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20171127195131/https://www.washingtonpost.com/news/grade-point/wp/2017/11/27/tufts-postpones-scaramucci-talk-after-he-threatens-to-sue-student/|archivedate=November 27, 2017|df=mdy-all}}</ref> The ''Daily'' opted to keep the full text of the editorials on its website while publishing publicly the cease-and-desist letter on November 27, 2017.<ref name=\":3\" /><ref name=\":1\" /> That evening, members of the [[Tufts University#Student government|Tufts Community Union (TCU) Senate]], the main student government body at Tufts University, publicly called on the university to remove Scaramucci from the Fletcher School's Board of Advisors.<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://tuftsdaily.com/news/2017/11/27/tcu-senators-call-tufts-remove-scaramucci-fletcher-board-advisors/|title=TCU Senators call on Tufts to remove Scaramucci from Fletcher Board of Advisors|last=Walsh|first=Joe|date=2017-11-27|work=The Tufts Daily|access-date=2017-11-28|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20171128082742/https://tuftsdaily.com/news/2017/11/27/tcu-senators-call-tufts-remove-scaramucci-fletcher-board-advisors/|archive-date=November 28, 2017|url-status=live|language=en-US|df=mdy-all}}</ref> On November 28, 2017, Scaramucci resigned his position.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://twitter.com/TuftsDaily/status/935535741442121729|title=BREAKING: Anthony Scaramucci has resigned from The Fletcher School's Board of Advisors effective immediately. The resignation was announced this morning in an email to the Fletcher community from Dean James Stavridis and Provost David Harris.pic.twitter.com/VGiOvHkC8K|last=Daily|first=The Tufts|date=2017-11-28|website=@TuftsDaily|language=en|access-date=2017-11-28|url-status=live|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20180210070156/https://twitter.com/TuftsDaily/status/935535741442121729|archivedate=February 10, 2018|df=mdy-all}}</ref>\n\n==Personal life==\n\nScaramucci's first marriage was to Lisa Miranda. They separated in 2011 after 23 years of marriage, and their divorce was finalized in 2014.<ref name=schuster /><ref>{{cite web|last1=McBride|first1=Jessica|title=Lisa Miranda, Anthony Scaramucci's Ex Wife: 5 Fast Facts You Need to Know|url=https://heavy.com/news/2017/07/lisa-miranda-scaramucci-ex-wife-first-photos-anthony-children-daughter-amelia-demilo-divorce/|publisher=Heavy.com|accessdate=July 31, 2017|url-status=live|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20170730121345/https://heavy.com/news/2017/07/lisa-miranda-scaramucci-ex-wife-first-photos-anthony-children-daughter-amelia-demilo-divorce/|archivedate=July 30, 2017|df=mdy-all}}</ref>\n\nHis second marriage is with Deidre Ball. Ball worked in investor relations for SkyBridge Capital until Scaramucci left the firm. The couple first dated in 2011 and married on July 11, 2014,<ref name=mcbride>{{cite web |url=http://heavy.com/news/2017/07/anthony-scaramucci-family-parents-father-children-wife-deidre-italian-manhasset-long-island/ |title=Anthony Scaramucci's Family: 5 Fast Facts You Need to Know |author=McBride, Jessica |publisher=[[Heavy.com]] |date=July 21, 2017 |accessdate=July 24, 2017 |url-status=live |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20170722062040/http://heavy.com/news/2017/07/anthony-scaramucci-family-parents-father-children-wife-deidre-italian-manhasset-long-island/ |archivedate=July 22, 2017 |df=mdy-all }}</ref> after having their first child together in early 2014. Scaramucci and Ball separated briefly in early 2017.<ref name = schuster/> Ball filed for divorce from Scaramucci in early July 2017 when she was pregnant with their second child, to whom she gave birth on July 24, 2017,<ref name=schuster /><ref name=independent>{{cite web |url=https://www.independent.co.uk/news/world/americas/us-politics/anthony-scaramucci-wife-miss-birth-son-donald-trump-white-house-communications-deidre-scaramucci-a7868351.html |title=Anthony Scaramucci 'texted \"I'll pray for our child\" to his wife after missing birth of their son' |author=Pasha-Robinson, Lucy |publisher=Independent |date=July 31, 2017 |accessdate=July 31, 2017 |url-status=live |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20170731190655/http://www.independent.co.uk/news/world/americas/us-politics/anthony-scaramucci-wife-miss-birth-son-donald-trump-white-house-communications-deidre-scaramucci-a7868351.html |archivedate=July 31, 2017 |df=mdy-all }}</ref> but she dropped the divorce case on November 29, 2017.<ref name=pagesix>{{cite web |url=https://pagesix.com/2017/11/30/scaramucci-and-his-wife-call-off-their-divorce/ |title=Scaramucci and his wife call off their divorce |author=Julia Marsh, Chris Perez |publisher=Page Six |date=November 30, 2017 |url-status=live |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20171208174857/https://pagesix.com/2017/11/30/scaramucci-and-his-wife-call-off-their-divorce/ |archivedate=December 8, 2017 |df=mdy-all }}</ref> The couple worked out their marital problems and in September 2018 began a [[Radio.com]] podcast titled \"Mooch and the Mrs.\", in which they discuss their world view from opposite political stances, while managing their relationship.<ref>{{cite news |url=https://www.foxnews.com/entertainment/anthony-scaramucci-once-estranged-wife-doing-just-fine |title=Anthony Scaramucci, wife 'managed to work it out' after marital trouble detailed in tabloids |first=Brian |last=Flood |date=September 28, 2018 |publisher=Fox News |access-date=November 2, 2018 }}</ref><ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.radio.com/blogs/anthony-scaramucci-podcast-mooch-and-mrs-streaming-radiocom |title=Radio.com Launches Anthony and Deidre Scaramucci Podcast |date=September 18, 2018 |website=Radio.com |access-date=November 2, 2018 }}</ref>\n\n==References==\n{{reflist|30em}}\n\n==External links==\n{{sisterlinks|d=Q4773428|c=category:Anthony Scaramucci|n=no|b=no|v=no|voy=no|m=no|mw=no|species=no|s=no|wikt=no}}\n*{{C-SPAN|Anthony Scaramucci}}\n\n{{s-start}}\n{{s-off}}\n{{s-bef|before=[[Sean Spicer]]<br>Acting}}\n{{s-ttl|title=[[White House Communications Director|White House Director of Communications]]|years=2017}}\n{{s-aft|after=[[Hope Hicks]]<br>}}\n{{s-end}}\n\n{{WHCD}}\n{{authority control}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Scaramucci, Anthony}}\n[[Category:1964 births]]\n[[Category:21st-century American non-fiction writers]]\n[[Category:American financial writers]]\n[[Category:American financiers]]\n[[Category:American hedge fund managers]]\n[[Category:American male non-fiction writers]]\n[[Category:American people of Italian descent]]\n[[Category:American men podcasters]]\n[[Category:American podcasters]]\n[[Category:Celebrity Big Brother]]\n[[Category:Contestants on American game shows]]\n[[Category:Goldman Sachs people]]\n[[Category:Harvard Law School alumni]]\n[[Category:Living people]]\n[[Category:New York (state) Republicans]]\n[[Category:Paul D. Schreiber High School alumni]]\n[[Category:People from Long Island]]\n[[Category:People from Manhasset, New York]]\n[[Category:People from Port Washington, New York]]\n[[Category:People of Umbrian descent]]\n[[Category:Trump administration personnel]]\n[[Category:Tufts University alumni]]\n[[Category:White House Communications Directors]]\n[[Category:Writers from New York (state)]]\n", "text_old": "{{redirect2|The Mooch|Scaramucci||Mooch (disambiguation){{!}}Mooch|and|Scaramucci (disambiguation)}}\n{{short description|American financier and political figure}}\n{{Use mdy dates|date=October 2017}}\n{{Infobox officeholder\n| name                = Anthony Scaramucci\n| image               = Anthony Scaramucci at SALT Conference 2016 (cropped).jpg\n| office              = [[White House Communications Director]]\n| president           = [[Donald Trump]]\n| term_start          = July 21, 2017\n| term_end            = July 31, 2017\n| predecessor         = [[Sean Spicer]] (acting)\n| successor           = [[Hope Hicks]]\n| party               = [[Republican Party (United States)|Republican]]\n| birth_date          = {{birth date and age|1964|1|6}}\n| birth_place         = [[Long Island]], New York, U.S.\n| death_date          =\n| death_place         =\n| otherparty          =\n| spouse              = {{marriage|Lisa Miranda|1988|2014|end=divorced}}<br/>{{marriage|Deidre Ball|July 11, 2014}}\n| children            = 5\n| education           = [[Tufts University]] ([[Bachelor of Arts|BA]])<br/>[[Harvard University]] ([[Juris Doctor|JD]])\n| known_for           = founding [[SkyBridge Capital]]\n\n}}\n\n'''Anthony Scaramucci''' ({{IPAc-en|s|k|\u00e6r|\u0259|\u02c8|m|u\u02d0|t\u0283|i:}}, {{Respell|ska|r\u0259|MOOch|chee}}; born January 6, 1964), nicknamed \"'''The Mooch'''\", is an American financier, entrepreneur, and political consultant who briefly served as the [[White House Communications Director|White House Director of Communications]] from July 21 to July 31, 2017.\n\nScaramucci worked at [[Goldman Sachs]]' investment banking, equities, and private wealth management divisions between 1989 and 1996. After leaving Goldman Sachs, he founded Oscar Capital Management, and in 2005, he founded the investment firm [[SkyBridge Capital]].\n\nOn July 21, 2017, Scaramucci was appointed [[White House Communications Director]]. Days into the job, Scaramucci provoked controversy after launching a strongly-worded attack on members of the [[Trump Administration|Trump administration]] in an interview with ''[[The New Yorker]]''{{'}}s [[Ryan Lizza]], that he believed was off the record. Ten days after the announcement of his appointment, he was dismissed by the new [[White House Chief of Staff]], [[John F. Kelly]], at the recommendation of President Donald Trump.\n\n==Early life==\nScaramucci was born into an [[Italian Americans|Italian-American]]<ref name=\"New York Magazine\" /> family on January 6, 1964, on [[Long Island]], New York, where he was raised in [[Port Washington, New York|Port Washington]].<ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.nytimes.com/2017/07/21/business/dealbook/trump-media-scaramucci-wall-street.html|work= [[The New York Times]]|title=Scaramucci Has a Showman's Knack for Self-Promotion Rivaling Trump's|first= Eric |last=Owles|date=July 21, 2017|accessdate=January 13, 2019|quote=Mr. Scaramucci grew up on Long Island, in Port Washington, N.Y....}}</ref><ref name=usnews&worldreport>{{cite news|url=https://www.usnews.com/news/politics/articles/2017-07-24/10-things-you-didnt-know-about-anthony-scaramucci|title=10 Things About Anthony Scaramucci|first=Katelyn|last=Newman|date=July 24, 2017| accessdate=January 13, 2019|work=[[US News & World Report]]|archivedate=January 12, 2019|archiveurl= https://web.archive.org/web/20190112153805/https://www.usnews.com/news/politics/articles/2017-07-24/10-things-you-didnt-know-about-anthony-scaramucci|url-status=live}}</ref> He is the son of Marie DeFeo Scaramucci and Alexander Scaramucci, who was a construction worker.<ref name=\"New York Magazine\" /> His paternal grandfather Alessandro Scaramucci immigrated to the United States from [[Gualdo Tadino]], [[Umbria]].<ref>{{cite news |url=http://www.lastampa.it/2017/07/23/esteri/il-nonno-partito-da-gualdo-un-secolo-fa-viaggio-alle-radici-italiane-di-scaramucci-472cf4gMx9Vy5OZQtBnKRN/pagina.html |date=July 23, 2017 |access-date=July 26, 2017 |newspaper=[[La Stampa]] |first=Paolo |last=Festuccia |title=Il nonno partito da Gualdo un secolo fa, viaggio alle radici italiane di Scaramucci |language=Italian |url-status=live |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20170725085418/http://www.lastampa.it/2017/07/23/esteri/il-nonno-partito-da-gualdo-un-secolo-fa-viaggio-alle-radici-italiane-di-scaramucci-472cf4gMx9Vy5OZQtBnKRN/pagina.html |archivedate=July 25, 2017 |df=mdy-all }}</ref> He had a middle-class upbringing and was the first generation of his family to attend college.<ref name=\"New York Magazine\">{{cite news|last1=Pressler|first1=Jessica|title=The Mooch Is His Own Aflac Duck|url=http://nymag.com/news/business/themoney/anthony-scaramucci-2012-5/|work=[[New York (magazine)|New York]]|date=May 6, 2012|url-status=live|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20170721165946/http://nymag.com/news/business/themoney/anthony-scaramucci-2012-5/|archivedate=July 21, 2017|df=mdy-all}}</ref> He has an older brother, David, and a sister, Susan.<ref name=mcbride /><ref>{{cite web |url=https://medium.com/@Scaramucci/discussing-addiction-and-recovery-with-my-brother-3b607921ec9a |title=Discussing Addiction and Recovery with My Brother |first=Anthony |last=Scaramucci |access-date=July 28, 2017 |date=October 10, 2016 |publisher=[[Medium (website)|Medium]] |url-status=live |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20170729112517/https://medium.com/%40Scaramucci/discussing-addiction-and-recovery-with-my-brother-3b607921ec9a |archivedate=July 29, 2017 |df=mdy-all }}</ref> Scaramucci graduated in 1982 from [[Paul D. Schreiber Senior High School]] in Port Washington,<ref name=\"biz\">{{cite news |last=La Roche |first=Julia |date=August 20, 2015 |url=http://www.businessinsider.com/high-school-yearbook-photos-of-wall-street-ceos-2015-8/#heres-cohn-in-the-frosh-debate-club-117 |title=40 old high-school yearbook photos of Wall Street's titans |work=[[Business Insider]] |url-status=live |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20170206013334/http://www.businessinsider.com/high-school-yearbook-photos-of-wall-street-ceos-2015-8#heres-cohn-in-the-frosh-debate-club-117 |archivedate=February 6, 2017 |df=mdy-all }}</ref> where he served as student council president.<ref>{{cite news|title=Concerned Citizens Meet on Youth Center Issue|url=http://www2.portnet.k12.ny.us/schreibertimes/1991-1992/1992-02-14.pdf|page=8|work=The Schreiber Times|url-status=live|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20170728220838/http://www2.portnet.k12.ny.us/schreibertimes/1991-1992/1992-02-14.pdf|archivedate=July 28, 2017|df=mdy-all}}</ref> He earned a [[B.A.]] in [[economics]] at [[Tufts University]] and a [[Juris Doctor|J.D.]] at [[Harvard Law School]] where he overlapped with former President Barack Obama, former Deputy Attorney General Rod Rosenstein and Supreme Court Justice Neil Gorsuch, among others.<ref>{{cite news | url=http://www.businessinsider.com/anthony-scaramucci-goldman-sachs-2012-8 | title=The Hilarious Story Of How Anthony Scaramucci Was Hired, Fired, And Rehired At Goldman Sachs | publisher=Business Insider | date=August 14, 2012 | access-date=March 28, 2015 | last=Lopez | first=Linette | url-status=live | archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20150401015927/http://www.businessinsider.com/anthony-scaramucci-goldman-sachs-2012-8 | archivedate=April 1, 2015 | df=mdy-all }}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=https://today.law.harvard.edu/alumni-among-trumps-recent-appointees/|title=Scarramucci and other alumni among Trump's recent appointees|last=July 26|last2=2017|website=Harvard Law Today|language=en-US|access-date=2020-02-07}}</ref> Scaramucci credits his time and education at Harvard Law School as a springboard for his career in finance.<ref name=path>{{Cite web|url=https://medium.com/@Felicissimo/president-trumps-new-director-of-communications-anthony-scaramucci-the-unlikely-path-of-a-law-e7ff12492e45|title=President Trumps new Director of Communications: Anthony Scaramucci: The Unlikely Path of a Law...|last=Felicissimo|first=David|date=July 28, 2017|website=Medium|access-date=July 29, 2017|url-status=live|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20170730032546/https://medium.com/%40Felicissimo/president-trumps-new-director-of-communications-anthony-scaramucci-the-unlikely-path-of-a-law-e7ff12492e45|archivedate=July 30, 2017|df=mdy-all}}</ref> Scaramucci has never practiced law and went to work at Goldman Sachs directly after graduating.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.nytimes.com/2017/07/24/business/dealbook/anthony-scaramucci-white-house-communications-director-for-president-trump.html|title=Scaramucci on Trump: 'He's My Client'|first=Andrew Ross|last=Sorkin|date=July 24, 2017|publisher=The New York Times|via=NYTimes.com|access-date=August 4, 2017|url-status=live|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20170725070314/https://www.nytimes.com/2017/07/24/business/dealbook/anthony-scaramucci-white-house-communications-director-for-president-trump.html|archivedate=July 25, 2017|df=mdy-all}}</ref><ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.law.com/sites/almstaff/2017/07/21/trumps-man-of-the-hour-scaramucci-is-not-one-to-humble-brag-says-cravath-associate/?slreturn=20170702003400 |title=Trump's Man of the Hour Scaramucci Is Not One To 'Humble Brag,' Says Cravath Associate |date=July 21, 2017 |access-date=August 4, 2017 |website=law.com |url-access=registration |first=Leigh |last=Jones |publisher=[[ALM (company)|ALM]] |url-status=live |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20170802125755/http://www.law.com/sites/almstaff/2017/07/21/trumps-man-of-the-hour-scaramucci-is-not-one-to-humble-brag-says-cravath-associate/?slreturn=20170702003400 |archivedate=August 2, 2017 |df=mdy-all }}</ref>\n\n==Career in investment banking==\nScaramucci began his career at [[Goldman Sachs]] in 1989, in the Investment Banking division. A year later he was fired, then rehired two months later in the Equities division. In 1993, he became vice president in the bank's Private Wealth Management division.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.businessinsider.com/anthony-scaramucci-on-goldman-sachs-2015-12|title=SCARAMUCCI: What getting hired, fired, and rehired by Goldman Sachs taught me|last=Shen|first=Lucinda|website=Business Insider|access-date=2020-02-07}}</ref><ref>{{cite news | url=http://www.vanityfair.com/news/2010/01/goldman-sachs-200101 | title=The Bank Job | work=Vanity Fair | date=December 2009 | accessdate=March 28, 2015 | last=McLean | first=Bethany | url-status=live | archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20150402093328/http://www.vanityfair.com/news/2010/01/goldman-sachs-200101 | archivedate=April 2, 2015 | df=mdy-all }}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.weforum.org/people/anthony-scaramucci/|title=Anthony Scaramucci|website=World Economic Forum|access-date=2020-02-07}}</ref>\n\n===Oscar Capital Management===\nScaramucci left Goldman in 1996 to launch Oscar Capital Management with his colleague Andrew Boszhardt.<ref>{{cite news|url=http://archive.fortune.com/magazines/fortune/fortune_archive/1998/06/08/243511/index.htm |title=Everybody's Going Hedge Funds |work=Fortune |first=Bethany |last=McLean |date=June 8, 1998 |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/19990127185046/http://www.pathfinder.com/fortune/1998/980608/hed.html |archivedate=January 27, 1999 |url-status=live }}</ref> In 2001, Oscar Capital was sold to [[Neuberger Berman]], and upon Neuberger Berman's sale to [[Lehman Brothers]] in 2003, Scaramucci served as a managing director in the firm's Investment Management division.<ref name=\"finalternatives.com\">{{cite news|url=http://www.finalternatives.com/node/12537|title=FINalternatives Sky's the Limit for Skybridge After Citi Deal|date=March 17, 2010|work=Final Alternatives|access-date=July 31, 2017|url-status=live|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20170728035012/http://www.finalternatives.com/node/12537|archivedate=July 28, 2017|df=mdy-all}}</ref><ref>{{cite web | url=http://www.mmexecutive.com/issues/20011028/63571-1.html | title=Neuberger Acquires High-Net-Worth Assets | publisher=Money Management Executive | date=October 29, 2001 | accessdate=March 28, 2015 | url-status=live | archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20150402114424/http://www.mmexecutive.com/issues/20011028/63571-1.html | archivedate=April 2, 2015 | df=mdy-all }}</ref>\n\n===SkyBridge Capital===\nIn 2005, Scaramucci founded [[SkyBridge Capital]], a global alternative investment firm.<ref>{{cite news | url=https://www.cnbc.com/id/102372713 | title=Here are the best hedge funds for 2015: Experts | publisher=CNBC | date=January 27, 2015 | accessdate=March 28, 2015 | last=Delevingne | first=Lawrence | url-status=live | archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20150402115552/http://www.cnbc.com/id/102372713 | archivedate=April 2, 2015 | df=mdy-all }}</ref> Scaramucci is the chairman of the SkyBridge Alternatives Conference, or \"SALT\" Conference, launched in 2009. SALT hosts its annual flagship event in Las Vegas and an international event in the Fall/Winter. SALT has hosted large conferences in Singapore, Tokyo and, most recently, Abu Dhabi.<ref>{{cite news|url=https://dealbook.nytimes.com/2011/05/13/skybridge-comes-out-a-winner-in-las-vegas/|title=DealBook \"SkyBridge Comes Out a Winner in Las Vegas|work=The New York Times|first=Azam|last=Ahmed|date=May 13, 2011|url-status=live|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20170728121128/https://dealbook.nytimes.com/2011/05/13/skybridge-comes-out-a-winner-in-las-vegas/|archivedate=July 28, 2017|df=mdy-all}}</ref>\n\nIn 2011, Scaramucci received the [[Ernst & Young Entrepreneur of the Year Award]] New York Award in the Financial Services category,<ref name=\"waynes\">{{cite news|url=http://www.waynesvilledailyguide.com/article/20110805/News/308059864|title=The Readers' Writers: Entrepreneur and author Anthony Scaramucci|date=August 5, 2011|publisher=Waynesville Daily Guide|accessdate=March 28, 2015|last=Kentner|first=DA|url-status=live|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20150402015046/http://www.waynesvilledailyguide.com/article/20110805/News/308059864|archivedate=April 2, 2015|df=mdy-all}}</ref> and in 2016 was ranked #85 in ''[[Worth (magazine)|Worth]]'' magazine's \"Power 100: The 100 Most Powerful People in Global Finance\".<ref>{{cite magazine |url=http://www.worth.com/power-100-2016/ |magazine=[[Worth (magazine)|Worth]] |title=The Power 100 |date=October 17, 2016 |access-date=February 18, 2017 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20161021195630/http://www.worth.com/power-100-2016/ |archivedate=October 21, 2016 |df=mdy-all }}</ref>\n\nIn May 2014, SkyBridge licensed the rights to ''[[Wall Street Week]]'', a financial television news program formerly hosted by [[Louis Rukeyser]] on [[PBS]]. Scaramucci hosted the show. Broadcast rights were transferred to [[Fox Broadcasting Company]] in 2016.<ref>{{cite news |url=https://variety.com/2016/tv/news/wall-street-week-fox-business-network-1201729591/ |title=Fox Business Network Picks Up 'Wall Street Week' |work=Variety |date=March 14, 2016 |last=Steinberg |first=Brian |url-status=live |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20170728130416/http://variety.com/2016/tv/news/wall-street-week-fox-business-network-1201729591/ |archivedate=July 28, 2017 | df=mdy-all }}</ref>\n\nOn January 17, 2017, SkyBridge announced a majority stake sale to RON Transatlantic EG and HNA Capital (U.S.) Holding, a Chinese conglomerate with close ties to [[China]]'s Communist Party. With the announcement, Scaramucci stepped down from his co-management role and ended his affiliation with SkyBridge and SALT.<ref>{{cite news |url=https://www.cnbc.com/2017/02/02/anthony-scaramucci-wont-get-announced-white-house-role-official-says.html |title=Anthony Scaramucci won't get announced White House role, official says |work=CNBC |date=February 2, 2017 |accessdate=February 2, 2017 |url-status=live |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20170202121621/http://www.cnbc.com/2017/02/02/anthony-scaramucci-wont-get-announced-white-house-role-official-says.html |archivedate=February 2, 2017 |df=mdy-all }}</ref><ref name=SBsale>{{Cite press release|url=http://www.prnewswire.com/news-releases/skybridge-capital-announces-definitive-purchase-agreement-to-sell-majority-stake-in-firm-300391910.html|title=SkyBridge Capital Announces Definitive Purchase Agreement To Sell Majority Stake in Firm|agency=PR Newswire|publisher=SkyBridge Capital|date=January 17, 2017|access-date=January 20, 2017|url-status=live|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20170119033509/http://www.prnewswire.com/news-releases/skybridge-capital-announces-definitive-purchase-agreement-to-sell-majority-stake-in-firm-300391910.html|archivedate=January 19, 2017|df=mdy-all}}</ref> In April 2018, it was announced that Scaramucci would be returning to SkyBridge after the deal with HNA Group had collapsed due to the lack of approval of the Committee on Foreign Investment in the United States, an inter-agency government committee.<ref>{{cite news |url=https://money.cnn.com/2018/04/30/investing/anthony-scaramucci-skybridge-hna/index.html |title=Anthony Scaramucci is rejoining hedge fund after sale collapses |date=April 30, 2018 |first=Matt |last=Egan |publisher=CNN Money |department=Business |access-date=November 2, 2018 }}</ref>\n\n==Career in politics==\n[[File:Anthony Scaramucci by Gage Skidmore.jpg|thumb|Scaramucci at 2016 [[FreedomFest]]]]\nScaramucci supported the presidential campaigns of [[Hillary Clinton]] and [[Barack Obama]].<ref name=\"collins\"/> In 2008, Scaramucci also served as a fundraiser for President [[Barack Obama]].<ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.bloomberg.com/news/2011-09-27/romney-lures-obama-wall-street-donors-in-race-for-campaign-cash.html|title=Bloomberg \"Romney Lures Away Obama's Wall Street Supporters in Race for Campaign Cash|url-status=live|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20140814023433/http://www.bloomberg.com/news/2011-09-27/romney-lures-obama-wall-street-donors-in-race-for-campaign-cash.html|archivedate=August 14, 2014|df=mdy-all}}</ref> In September 2010, however, Scaramucci asked Obama at a CNBC Town Hall meeting when he was going to \"stop whacking [[Wall Street]] like a [[pi\u00f1ata]].\"<ref name=\"Sanati\">{{cite news|url=https://dealbook.nytimes.com/2010/10/06/a-fund-managers-message-beyond-the-pinata/|title=The New York Times \"A Fund Manager's Message Beyond the 'Pinata'|first=Cyrus|last=Sanati|date=October 6, 2010|url-status=live|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20170728085434/https://dealbook.nytimes.com/2010/10/06/a-fund-managers-message-beyond-the-pinata/|archivedate=July 28, 2017|df=mdy-all}}</ref>\n\nScaramucci has [[Twitter|tweeted]] at various times that he has \"always been for strong gun control laws\", and that \"Republicans should support gay marriage\".<ref>{{cite news|url=http://www.washingtonexaminer.com/anthony-scaramuccis-old-tweets-reveal-liberal-views-on-climate-abortion-gay-rights-border-wall/article/2629415|title=Anthony Scaramucci's old tweets reveal liberal views on climate, abortion, gay rights, border wall|first=Anna|last=Giaritelli|publisher=[[The Washington Examiner]]|date=July 22, 2017|url-status=live|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20170723051054/http://www.washingtonexaminer.com/anthony-scaramuccis-old-tweets-reveal-liberal-views-on-climate-abortion-gay-rights-border-wall/article/2629415|archivedate=July 23, 2017|df=mdy-all}}</ref>\n\nHe served as the national finance co-chair for Mitt Romney's 2012 presidential campaign.<ref name=\"collins\"/>\n\nIn 2015, on a [[Fox Business Network]] television appearance, Scaramucci called Trump a \"hack politician\" whose rhetoric is \"anti-American and very, very divisive.\" He further warned Trump to \"cut it out now\", and \"stop all this crazy rhetoric.\" In December 2015, Scaramucci criticized Trump's call for a border wall between Mexico and the U.S. He also criticized Trump for \"making a fundamental mistake of trying to blame all of Islam and all Muslims for what is the ideology and the actions of a minority.\"<ref name=\"collins\">{{cite web|last1=Collins|first1=Ben|title=Anthony Scaramucci Loved Hillary, Gave to Obama, and Deleted Anti-Trump Tweets|url=http://www.thedailybeast.com/new-trump-hire-anthony-scaramucci-deletes-old-tweets-bashing-trump|work=Daily Beast|access-date=July 28, 2017|url-status=live|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20170724032738/http://www.thedailybeast.com/new-trump-hire-anthony-scaramucci-deletes-old-tweets-bashing-trump|archivedate=July 24, 2017|df=mdy-all}}</ref>\n\nAhead of the 2016 election, Scaramucci tweeted that he hoped Hillary Clinton would be the next president.<ref name=\"collins\"/> During the [[2016 United States presidential election|2016 presidential election]], Scaramucci first endorsed [[Scott Walker (politician)|Scott Walker]] and later [[Jeb Bush]]. In May 2016, after both Walker and Bush had withdrawn from the race, Scaramucci signed on to [[Donald Trump]]'s political campaign by joining the Trump Finance Committee.<ref>{{cite news|last1=Rucker|first1=Philip|title=Anthony Scaramucci, a top Republican fundraiser, signs on with Trump campaign|url=https://www.washingtonpost.com/news/post-politics/wp/2016/05/09/anthony-scaramucci-a-top-republican-fundraiser-signs-on-with-trump-campaign/|work=The Washington Post|date=May 9, 2016|url-status=live|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20170728061355/https://www.washingtonpost.com/news/post-politics/wp/2016/05/09/anthony-scaramucci-a-top-republican-fundraiser-signs-on-with-trump-campaign/|archivedate=July 28, 2017|df=mdy-all}}</ref> In November 2016, he was appointed to President-elect Trump's Presidential Transition Team Executive Committee.<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.wsj.com/articles/donald-trump-shuffles-transition-team-making-mike-pence-chairman-1478890592|title=Donald Trump Shuffles Transition Team, Making Mike Pence Chairman|last=Bender|first=Michael C.|date=November 12, 2016|newspaper=The Wall Street Journal|issn=0099-9660|access-date=November 14, 2016|url-status=live|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20161114041652/http://www.wsj.com/articles/donald-trump-shuffles-transition-team-making-mike-pence-chairman-1478890592|archivedate=November 14, 2016|df=mdy-all}}</ref>\n\nIn August 2019, Scaramucci said that he no longer supported the reelection of Donald Trump as US president. He was critical of Trump's divisive rhetoric.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.cnn.com/2019/08/12/politics/anthony-scaramucci-donald-trump-reelection-cnntv/index.html|title=Scaramucci no longer backs Trump's reelection, says change may be needed at top of ticket|author=Devan Cole|website=CNN|access-date=2019-08-13|date=August 12, 2019}}</ref>\n\n===Nomination to Office of Public Liaison===\nOn January 12, 2017, Scaramucci was named Assistant to President Trump and director of the [[White House Office of Public Engagement and Intergovernmental Affairs|White House Office of Public Liaison and Intergovernmental Affairs]].<ref name=\"auto1\">{{cite magazine |url=http://nymag.com/daily/intelligencer/2017/01/trump-wall-street-supporters.html |title=Long on Trump: Wall Streeters like Anthony Scaramucci bet heavy on the would-be president back when that seemed like a pretty dumb investment. Bonus time! |magazine=[[New York (magazine)|New York]] |date=January 23, 2017 |access-date=March 6, 2017 |first=Jessica |last=Pressler |url-status=live |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20170307130923/http://nymag.com/daily/intelligencer/2017/01/trump-wall-street-supporters.html |archivedate=March 7, 2017 |df=mdy-all }}</ref> On January 23, he told [[New York (magazine)|''New York'' magazine]]: the \"thing I have learned about these people in Washington is they have no money. So what happens when they have no fucking money is they write about what seat they are in and what the title is. Fucking congressmen act like that. They are fucking jackasses\".<ref name=\"auto1\"/> On the topic of working in Washington DC, he said: \"[\u2026] that\u2019s Washington. That\u2019s how they operate. They try to caricaturise you, and dehumanise you, so that you lose your voice. They wanted to get me by grinding out a public image of me that is dramatically different from the reality.\"<ref>{{Cite news|last=Aitkenhead|first=Decca|url=https://www.theguardian.com/us-news/2018/jun/09/anthony-scaramucci-life-after-11-days-in-white-house-trump-decca-aitkenhead|title=Anthony Scaramucci: 'I\u2019m in the game for a fight. I love the fight'|date=2018-06-09|work=The Guardian|access-date=2020-02-14|language=en-GB|issn=0261-3077}}</ref>\n\nScaramucci attended the [[World Economic Forum]] in [[Davos]] January 16\u201317 as the representative for the [[Trump transition]] team.<ref name=TrumpsTranslatorBuzzfeed20170117 /> Part of his mission was to reassure attendees about the incoming [[Trump administration]].<ref name=TrumpsTranslatorBuzzfeed20170117 /> Following Chinese President [[Xi Jinping]], he gave a talk warning against protectionism and championing free trade.<ref name=TrumpsTranslatorBuzzfeed20170117>{{cite web|title=Trump's Translator Wants The Global Elite To Understand Him|url=https://www.buzzfeed.com/miriamelder/trumps-translator-wants-the-global-elite-to-understand-him|website=[[Buzzfeed News]]|date=January 17, 2017|access-date=June 20, 2018|last=Elder|first=Miriam}}</ref>\n\n[[Fox Business]] reported on January 31, 2017, that \"Scaramucci's delayed appointment underscores some of the tensions building inside the Trump White House, as various aides and advisers continue to jockey for his attention and to retain and expand their power\".<ref>{{cite news |url=http://www.foxbusiness.com/politics/2017/01/31/story-behind-scaramucci-s-delayed-appointment-amid-trump-white-house-bickering.html |title=The story behind Scaramucci's delayed appointment amid Trump White House bickering |publisher=Fox Business |date=January 31, 2017 |access-date=March 9, 2017 |first1=Charles |last1=Gasparino |first2=Brian |last2=Schwartz |url-status=live |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20170204085001/http://www.foxbusiness.com/politics/2017/01/31/story-behind-scaramucci-s-delayed-appointment-amid-trump-white-house-bickering.html |archivedate=February 4, 2017 |df=mdy-all }}</ref> According to ''[[Politico]]'', on January 31, 2017, with Scaramucci's appointment still pending approval by the [[United States Office of Government Ethics]] (OGE), Trump's chief of staff [[Reince Priebus]] called Scaramucci \"to tell him he should pull out of consideration\". They reported that Priebus opposed Scaramucci's appointment because of Scaramucci's stake in SkyBridge Capital.<ref name=\"politico\" /> Several senior White House officials questioned the significance of any internal feuding in Scaramucci's appointment delay, however, officials have cited the lengthy process to conclude his sale of SkyBridge as the reason of the delay in his appointment.<ref>{{cite news |url=http://www.foxbusiness.com/politics/2017/02/01/trump-team-reconsiders-scaramucci-s-white-house-role.html |title=Trump Team Reconsiders Scaramucci's White House Role |newspaper=Fox Business |first1=Charlie |last1=Gasparino |department=Charlie Breaks It |first2=Brian |last2=Schwartz |date=February 1, 2017 |access-date=February 2, 2017 |url-status=live |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20170201210200/http://www.foxbusiness.com/politics/2017/02/01/trump-team-reconsiders-scaramucci-s-white-house-role.html |archivedate=February 1, 2017 |df=mdy-all }}</ref> [[Reuters]] reported on February 1 that Scaramucci would not get the director role.<ref>{{cite news |agency=Reuters |url=http://in.reuters.com/article/usa-trump-scaramucci-idINL4N1FN0RK |title=Anthony Scaramucci will not get White House role \u2013 NYT |date=February 1, 2017 |access-date=February 2, 2017 |url-status=live |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20170202034248/http://in.reuters.com/article/usa-trump-scaramucci-idINL4N1FN0RK |archivedate=February 2, 2017 |df=mdy-all }}</ref> In a February 2017 ''New York'' magazine article, Priebus was quoted as saying rumors that he interfered with the hiring were \"not true\".<ref>{{cite news |url=http://nymag.com/daily/intelligencer/2017/02/bannon-and-priebus-want-you-to-know-they-are-friends.html |title=Steve Bannon and Reince Priebus Want You to Know They Are Friends |work=[[New York (magazine)|New York]] |date=February 9, 2017 |access-date=February 10, 2017 |first=Olivia |last=Nuzzi |quote='It's not true,' Priebus said of the rumors that he nixed the hire. 'The person closest to Anthony in the entire West Wing is me,' he said. |url-status=live |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20170209184812/http://nymag.com/daily/intelligencer/2017/02/bannon-and-priebus-want-you-to-know-they-are-friends.html |archivedate=February 9, 2017 |df=mdy-all }}</ref>\n\nOn March 6, 2017, the White House announced the appointment of Ideagen founder and former CEO [[George Sifakis]] as director for the Office of Public Liaison,<ref name=Sifakis>{{cite press release |title=President Donald J. Trump Announces White House Staff Appointments |date=March 6, 2017 |access-date=March 7, 2017 |url=https://www.whitehouse.gov/the-press-office/2017/03/06/president-donald-j-trump-announces-white-house-staff-appointments |publisher=The White House |url-status=live |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20170307004613/https://www.whitehouse.gov/the-press-office/2017/03/06/president-donald-j-trump-announces-white-house-staff-appointments |archivedate=March 7, 2017 |df=mdy-all }}</ref> instead of Scaramucci. The next day, Politico reported that \"White House Chief of Staff Reince Priebus is still considering offering financier Anthony Scaramucci a role\" in the administration.<ref name=politico>{{cite news |url=http://www.politico.com/story/2017/03/anthony-scaramucci-white-house-role-235804 |title=Scaramucci still in consideration for White House role, official says |newspaper=Politico |date=March 7, 2016 |access-date=March 9, 2017 |first=Tara |last=Palmeri |url-status=live |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20170308024205/http://www.politico.com/story/2017/03/anthony-scaramucci-white-house-role-235804 |archivedate=March 8, 2017 |df=mdy-all }}</ref>\n\nOn June 26, 2017, three network investigative journalists\u2014Thomas Frank, [[Eric Lichtblau]], and Lex Haris\u2014resigned from [[CNN]] after the network retracted a story that connected Scaramucci to a $10 billion Russian investment fund. CNN issued an apology to Scaramucci (who accepted the apology), with the network saying the online story (which appeared on CNN's website and was not aired on television) did not meet its [[Journalism ethics and standards|editorial standards]].<ref name=\"Battaglio\">{{cite news|last=Battaglio|first=Stephen|url=http://www.latimes.com/business/hollywood/la-fi-ct-cnn-resignation-20170626-story.html|title=Three CNN journalists resign over retracted Trump-Russia story|date=June 27, 2017|work=[[Los Angeles Times]]|access-date=June 27, 2017|url-status=live|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20170627032249/http://www.latimes.com/business/hollywood/la-fi-ct-cnn-resignation-20170626-story.html|archivedate=June 27, 2017|df=mdy-all}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=http://politi.co/2hcrEJB|title=3 CNN staffers resign over retracted Scaramucci-Russia story|last=Gold|first=Hadas|website=POLITICO|language=en|access-date=2020-03-11}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.telegraph.co.uk/news/2017/06/27/trump-attacks-cnn-resignations-three-journalists-retracted-russia/|title=Trump attacks CNN after resignations of three journalists over retracted Russia-related story|date=June 27, 2017|work=The Telegraph|url-status=live|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20170628023103/http://www.telegraph.co.uk/news/2017/06/27/trump-attacks-cnn-resignations-three-journalists-retracted-russia/|archivedate=June 28, 2017|access-date=June 28, 2017|df=mdy-all}}</ref> Scaramucci said the original story was not true; CNN did not say the story was false, but said that it \"wasn't solid enough\" to be published.<ref name=\"Battaglio\" />\n\n===Export\u2013Import Bank of the United States===\nEffective June 19, 2017, Scaramucci was named senior vice president and chief strategy officer for the [[U.S. Export-Import Bank]]. He was also still under consideration for a post as ambassador to the [[Organisation for Economic Co-operation and Development]].<ref>{{cite news |url=http://www.businessinsider.com/scaramucci-gets-trump-job-at-us-export-import-bank-2017-6 |title=The hedge funder who had long hoped to work for Trump finally got a job |date=June 27, 2017 |agency=Reuters |newspaper=[[Business Insider]] |access-date=June 28, 2017 |url-status=live |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20170711080606/http://www.businessinsider.com/scaramucci-gets-trump-job-at-us-export-import-bank-2017-6 |archivedate=July 11, 2017 |df=mdy-all }}</ref><ref>{{cite news |url=http://www.foxnews.com/politics/2017/06/27/trump-adviser-scaramucci-joins-export-import-bank.html |title=Trump adviser Scaramucci joins Export-Import Bank |date=June 27, 2017 |publisher=Fox News Channel |access-date=June 28, 2017 |first=Serafin |last=G\u00f3mez |department=Politics |url-status=live |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20170628024002/http://www.foxnews.com/politics/2017/06/27/trump-adviser-scaramucci-joins-export-import-bank.html |archivedate=June 28, 2017 |df=mdy-all }}</ref>\n\n===White House Communications Director===\nOn July 21, 2017, President [[Donald Trump]] appointed Scaramucci [[White House Communications Director]].<ref name = record/> The White House announcement of Scaramucci said he would \"report directly to the President\" rather than to the [[White House chief of staff]], as White House Press Secretary [[Sean Spicer]] had.<ref>{{Cite news|url=http://thehill.com/homenews/administration/343253-white-house-scaramucci-will-report-directly-to-trump|title=White House: Scaramucci will report directly to Trump|last=Bowden|first=John|date=July 21, 2017|work=The Hill|access-date=July 27, 2017|url-status=live|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20170723051706/http://thehill.com/homenews/administration/343253-white-house-scaramucci-will-report-directly-to-trump|archivedate=July 23, 2017|df=mdy-all}}</ref><ref name=\"ny-27jul2017\">{{Cite news|url=http://www.newyorker.com/news/ryan-lizza/anthony-scaramucci-called-me-to-unload-about-white-house-leakers-reince-priebus-and-steve-bannon|title=Anthony Scaramucci Called Me to Unload About White House Leakers, Reince Priebus, and Steve Bannon|last=Lizza|first=Ryan|date=July 27, 2017|newspaper=The New Yorker|access-date=July 27, 2017|url-status=live|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20170727210016/https://www.newyorker.com/news/ryan-lizza/anthony-scaramucci-called-me-to-unload-about-white-house-leakers-reince-priebus-and-steve-bannon|archivedate=July 27, 2017|df=mdy-all}}</ref> On the day that Scaramucci's appointment was announced, Spicer resigned.<ref name=\"nytimes1\">{{cite news|last1=Thrush|first1=Glenn|title=Sean Spicer Resigns as White House Press Secretary|url=https://www.nytimes.com/2017/07/21/us/politics/sean-spicer-resigns-as-white-house-press-secretary.html|accessdate=July 21, 2017|work=The New York Times|date=July 21, 2017|url-status=live|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20170721160008/https://www.nytimes.com/2017/07/21/us/politics/sean-spicer-resigns-as-white-house-press-secretary.html|archivedate=July 21, 2017|df=mdy-all}}</ref> ''[[The New York Times]]'' reported that he had done so after advising Trump that he \"vehemently disagreed\" with the appointment of Scaramucci.<ref name=\"nytimes1\"/><ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.bloomberg.com/news/articles/2017-07-21/scaramucci-said-to-join-white-house-as-spicer-reported-to-resign |title=Trump Hires Scaramucci as Communications Director, Spicer Resigns |publisher=Bloomberg |date=May 30, 2017 |access-date=July 21, 2017 |url-status=live |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20170721170216/https://www.bloomberg.com/news/articles/2017-07-21/scaramucci-said-to-join-white-house-as-spicer-reported-to-resign |archivedate=July 21, 2017 |df=mdy-all }}</ref> Trump's chief of staff [[Reince Priebus]] also had \"vehement objections\" to his hiring.<ref name=\"ny-27jul2017\"/> At this time, Scaramucci was taunted by \"email prankster\" [[James Linton (hacker)|James Linton]] masquerading as Reince Priebus.<ref>{{cite news |last1=Booth |first1=Robert |title=Prankster says he targeted Scaramucci over mental health insult |url=https://www.theguardian.com/technology/2017/aug/01/prankster-says-he-targeted-scaramucci-over-mental-health-insult |accessdate=10 April 2020 |date=1 August 2017}}</ref>\n\nIn July 26, 2017, journalist Ryan Lizza reported that Scaramucci called him to identify who leaked information to ''The New Yorker'', revealing some disagreements with Chief of Staff Reince Priebus and White House advisor Steve Bannon. Scaramucci believed the conversation to be off the record.<ref>{{Cite news|last=Crilly|first=Rob|url=https://www.telegraph.co.uk/news/2017/08/13/anthony-scaramucci-says-white-house-plotters-working-against/|title=Anthony Scaramucci says White House leakers are working against Donald Trump, in first interview since he was fired|date=2017-08-13|work=The Telegraph|access-date=2020-02-07|language=en-GB|issn=0307-1235}}</ref>\n\nDuring the interview and in a tweet immediately afterward, Scaramucci said that he had contacted or would be contacting the [[FBI]] and the [[U.S. Department of Justice|Department of Justice]], asking them to investigate Priebus for allegedly \"leaking\" his financial-disclosure form to a ''[[Politico]]'' reporter. Scaramucci later deleted the tweet. Lizza said the form was obtained from publicly available data at the [[Export\u2013Import Bank of the United States|U.S. Export-Import Bank]].<ref>{{cite news | last = Blake | first = Aaron | title = Anthony Scaramucci's vulgarity is one thing. The bigger story is his deception. | newspaper = The Washington Post | date = July 28, 2017 | url = https://www.washingtonpost.com/pb/news/the-fix/wp/2017/07/28/anthony-scaramuccis-vulgarity-is-one-thing-the-bigger-story-is-his-deception/?outputType=accessibility&nid=menu_nav_accessibilityforscreenreader | access-date = August 1, 2017 | url-status=live | archiveurl = https://web.archive.org/web/20170801202120/https://www.washingtonpost.com/pb/news/the-fix/wp/2017/07/28/anthony-scaramuccis-vulgarity-is-one-thing-the-bigger-story-is-his-deception/?outputType=accessibility&nid=menu_nav_accessibilityforscreenreader | archivedate = August 1, 2017 | df = mdy-all }}</ref>\n\nOn July 28, Priebus's resignation as chief of staff was announced; Priebus said that he had resigned on July 27. Also on July 28, Trump announced that he had named retired general [[John F. Kelly]] as his new chief of staff.<ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.nytimes.com/2017/07/28/us/politics/reince-priebus-white-house-trump.html|title=Reince Priebus Pushed Out After Rocky Tenure as Trump Chief of Staff|first1=Peter|last1=Baker|first2=Maggie|last2=Haberman|date=July 28, 2017|work=New York Times|url-status=live|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20170729021432/https://www.nytimes.com/2017/07/28/us/politics/reince-priebus-white-house-trump.html|archivedate=July 29, 2017|df=mdy-all}}</ref>\n\nOn July 31, 2017, Trump dismissed Scaramucci from his role as communications director on the recommendation of Kelly, who wanted him removed because he did not think Scaramucci was disciplined and believed Scaramucci had lost his credibility.<ref name=nytimes731>{{cite news|url=https://www.nytimes.com/2017/07/31/us/politics/anthony-scaramucci-white-house.html|title=Trump Removes Anthony Scaramucci From Communications Director Role|date=July 31, 2017|accessdate=July 31, 2017|work=The New York Times|url-status=live|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20170731183613/https://www.nytimes.com/2017/07/31/us/politics/anthony-scaramucci-white-house.html|archivedate=July 31, 2017|df=mdy-all}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.cnbc.com/2017/07/31/trump-removes-anthony-scaramucci-from-communications-director-role-ny-times.html|title=Trump removes Anthony Scaramucci from communications director role|work=[[CNBC]]|last=Pramuk|first=Jacob|date=July 31, 2017|access-date=July 31, 2017|url-status=live|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20170731185528/https://www.cnbc.com/2017/07/31/trump-removes-anthony-scaramucci-from-communications-director-role-ny-times.html|archivedate=July 31, 2017|df=mdy-all}}</ref><ref>{{cite news | last = Jackson | first = Hallie | title = What Really Happened to Anthony Scaramucci | newspaper = NBC News | date = August 1, 2017 | url = http://www.nbcnews.com/politics/white-house/what-really-happened-scaramucci-n788356 | access-date = August 1, 2017 | url-status=live | archiveurl = https://web.archive.org/web/20170801045143/http://www.nbcnews.com/politics/white-house/what-really-happened-scaramucci-n788356 | archivedate = August 1, 2017 | df = mdy-all }}</ref><ref name=\":0\" /> As one of his first acts after being sworn in as Chief of Staff, Kelly reportedly invited Scaramucci to his office and told him he was being let go.<ref name=\":0\">{{cite news|url=http://www.cnn.com/2017/07/31/politics/anthony-scaramucci/index.html|title=Anthony Scaramucci out as White House communications director|last1=Merica|first1=Dan|last2=Zeleny|first2=Jeff|last3=Acosta|first3=Jim|date=July 31, 2017|work=CNN|accessdate=August 1, 2017|url-status=live|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20170801001920/http://www.cnn.com/2017/07/31/politics/anthony-scaramucci/index.html|archivedate=August 1, 2017|df=mdy-all}}</ref> An official White House statement indicated that Scaramucci \"will be leaving\" his post \"to give Chief of Staff John Kelly a clean slate and the ability to build his own team.\"<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.whitehouse.gov/the-press-office/2017/07/31/statement-press-secretary|title=Statement from the Press Secretary|date=July 31, 2017|work=The White House, Office of the Press Secretary|access-date=July 31, 2017|url-status=dead|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20170731192205/https://www.whitehouse.gov/the-press-office/2017/07/31/statement-press-secretary|archivedate=July 31, 2017|df=mdy-all}}</ref> Scaramucci's tenure of eleven days is tied for shortest in history for that position with [[Jack Koehler]] in the [[Presidency of Ronald Reagan|Reagan administration]].<ref name=record>{{cite news|url=http://www.nbcnews.com/politics/politics-news/scaramucci-sets-new-record-shortest-term-communications-director-n788281|title=Scaramucci Sets New Record for Shortest Term as Communications Director|last=Santos|first=Amanda Proen\u00e7a|date=July 31, 2017|work=NBC News|accessdate=July 31, 2017|url-status=live|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20170801002231/http://www.nbcnews.com/politics/politics-news/scaramucci-sets-new-record-shortest-term-communications-director-n788281|archivedate=August 1, 2017|df=mdy-all}}</ref>\n\n==Other activities==\nScaramucci paid $100,000 to have SkyBridge's logo in the film ''[[Wall Street: Money Never Sleeps]]'' (2010), along with two cameo appearances.<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.telegraph.co.uk/news/2017/07/31/gucci-scaramucci-paid-100000-appear-wall-street-sequel-according/|title='Gucci Scaramucci' reportedly spent $100,000 on 15-second cameo in Wall Street film sequel|last=Nianias|first=Helen|date=2017-07-31|work=The Telegraph|access-date=2020-02-04|language=en-GB|issn=0307-1235}}</ref><ref name=schuster>{{cite web|last1=Schuster|first1=Dana|title=Scaramucci's fed-up wife filed for divorce while nine months pregnant|url=http://pagesix.com/2017/07/29/scaramuccis-fed-up-wife-filed-for-divorce-while-nine-months-pregnant/|work=New York Post|accessdate=July 30, 2017|url-status=live|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20170730014413/http://pagesix.com/2017/07/29/scaramuccis-fed-up-wife-filed-for-divorce-while-nine-months-pregnant/|archivedate=July 30, 2017|df=mdy-all}}</ref>\n\nHe is the author of four books:\n* ''Goodbye [[Gordon Gekko]]: How to Find Your Fortune Without Losing Your Soul'' (2010)<ref name=\"The Economist\">{{cite news |url=http://www.economist.com/node/18681778 |newspaper=[[The Economist]] |date=May 12, 2011 |title=Power and pi\u00f1atas: Anthony Scaramucci, hedge-fund ambassador |access-date=March 9, 2017 |url-status=live |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20170622165701/http://www.economist.com/node/18681778 |archivedate=June 22, 2017 |df=mdy-all }}</ref><ref>{{cite web | url=https://www.nytimes.com/2010/10/02/business/02nocera.html | title=Still Stuck in Denial on Wall St. | work=The New York Times | date=October 1, 2010 | accessdate=March 28, 2015 | last=Nocera | first=Joe | url-status=live | archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20150403170204/http://www.nytimes.com/2010/10/02/business/02nocera.html | archivedate=April 3, 2015 | df=mdy-all }}</ref>\n* ''The Little Book of Hedge Funds: What You Need to Know About Hedge Funds but the Managers Won't Tell You'' (2012)<ref>{{cite news |url=http://www.cbsnews.com/video/watch/?id=7411762n |publisher=CBS News |title='The Little Book of Hedge Funds' by Anthony Scaramucci |date=June 15, 2012 |access-date=March 9, 2017 |first=Jeff |last=Glor |url-status=live |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20120619060135/http://www.cbsnews.com/video/watch/?id=7411762n |archivedate=June 19, 2012 |df=mdy-all }}</ref>\n* ''Hopping Over the Rabbit Hole: How Entrepreneurs Turn Failure Into Success'' (2016)<ref>{{cite news|last1=Taub|first1=Rob|title=Hopping Over The Rabbit Hole: How Entrepreneurs Turn Failure Into Success|url=http://www.huffingtonpost.com/rob-taub/book-review-hopping-over_b_12588720.html|accessdate=July 31, 2017|work=Huffington Post|date=October 24, 2016|url-status=live|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20170819054216/http://www.huffingtonpost.com/rob-taub/book-review-hopping-over_b_12588720.html|archivedate=August 19, 2017|df=mdy-all}}</ref>\n* ''Trump, the Blue-Collar President'' (2018)<ref>{{cite news|last1=Schuster|first1=Dana|title=Now it\u2019s Scaramucci\u2019s turn to give inside look at Trump White House in new book|url=https://www.marketwatch.com/story/scaramucci-gives-his-inside-look-at-trump-white-house-in-new-book-2018-10-21|accessdate=October 23, 2018|work=The New York Post|date=October 21, 2018|url-status=live|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20181023180153/https://www.marketwatch.com/story/scaramucci-gives-his-inside-look-at-trump-white-house-in-new-book-2018-10-21|archivedate=October 23, 2018|df=mdy-all}}</ref>\n\nHe joined [[Fox Business Network]] as a contributor in 2014, and in March 2016 served as host of the financial television show ''[[Wall Street Week]]''.<ref>{{cite web | url=https://nypost.com/2014/09/10/scaramucci-inks-deal-with-fox-business/ | title=Scaramucci inks deal with Fox Business | work=New York Post | date=September 10, 2014 | accessdate=March 28, 2015 | author=Celarier, Michelle | url-status=live | archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20150324072643/http://nypost.com/2014/09/10/scaramucci-inks-deal-with-fox-business/ | archivedate=March 24, 2015 | df=mdy-all }}</ref><ref name=\"Fox Business Network\">{{cite web | url=http://www.foxbusiness.com/features/2016/03/14/fox-business-network-welcomes-iconic-wall-street-week-program.html/ | title=FOX Business Network Welcomes Iconic 'Wall Street Week' Program | publisher=Fox Business Network | date=March 14, 2016 | url-status=live | archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20160406111620/http://www.foxbusiness.com/features/2016/03/14/fox-business-network-welcomes-iconic-wall-street-week-program.html | archivedate=April 6, 2016 | df=mdy-all }}</ref>\n\nScaramucci, along with restaurateur Eytan Sugarman and financier Nelson Braff, founded the [[Hunt & Fish Club]] steakhouse and seafood restaurant in [[Midtown Manhattan]] in New York City, which opened in 2015.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.nydailynews.com/life-style/eats/eats-beat-hunt-fish-club-opens-w-44th-st-article-1.2067642|title=Eats Beat: Steak-seafood spot Hunt & Fish Club opens on W. 44th St.|first=Gina|last=Pace|work=New York Daily News|date=January 11, 2015}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.townandcountrymag.com/leisure/dining/news/g1278/how-to-find-a-rich-husband-on-your-lunchbreak/|title=How To Find A Rich Husband On Your Lunchbreak|first=Tucker|last=Westbrook|date=May 6, 2015|work=Town & Country}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.businessinsider.com/inside-new-yorks-hunt-and-fish-club-2015-1|title=Inside Hunt & Fish Club, Wall Street\u2019s New Favorite Steakhouse|first=Megan|last=Willett|website=Business Insider|date=January 29, 2015}}</ref><ref name=\"auto2\">{{Cite web|url=https://www.wsj.com/articles/hunt-fish-club-a-homage-to-old-new-york-1424224351|title=Hunt & Fish Club, a Homage to Old New York; A swanky new Midtown steakhouse|work=The Wall Street Journal|date=February 17, 2015}}</ref><ref name=\"auto\">{{Cite web|url=https://nypost.com/2015/01/28/inside-hunt-fish-where-beauties-trawl-for-sugar-daddies/|title=Inside Hunt & Fish, where beauties trawl for sugar daddies|first=Dana|last=Schuster|date=January 29, 2015|work=The New York Post}}</ref>\n\nHe is the vice chair of the Kennedy Center Corporate Fund Board, and a trustee of the United States Olympic & Paralympic Foundation.<ref>{{cite web | url=http://www.saltconference.com/speakers/scaramucci_photo.html | title=Conference Speakers: Anthony Scaramucci | publisher=SALT Conference | access-date=March 28, 2015 | url-status=dead | archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20150331221645/http://www.saltconference.com/speakers/scaramucci_photo.html | archivedate=March 31, 2015 | df=mdy-all }}</ref> He is also a member of the [[Council on Foreign Relations]]. Scaramucci was a member of the New York City Financial Services Advisory Committee from 2007 to 2012.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.nyssa.org/programs/mastercalendar/ctl/viewdetail/mid/512/itemid/2318/d/20150415.aspx|title=Generating Alpha in Volatile Markets|publisher=New York Society of Security Analysts|accessdate=March 28, 2015|url-status=dead|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20170731190655/http://www.independent.co.uk/news/world/americas/us-politics/anthony-scaramucci-wife-miss-birth-son-donald-trump-white-house-communications-deidre-scaramucci-a7868351.html|archivedate=July 31, 2017|df=mdy-all}}</ref>\n\nIn April 2016, Scaramucci and two other [[New York Mets]] fans bought [[Mike Piazza]]'s jersey from the September 21, 2001, game against the [[Atlanta Braves]], the first professional baseball game played in New York following the [[September 11 attacks|9/11 attacks]], in which Piazza hit a game-winning 8th-inning home run. The jersey was purchased in a private auction for $365,000, the highest price ever paid for a modern-day jersey, which Scaramucci described as having \"tremendous artistic symbolism\". The new owners wanted the jersey accessible to fans, so it will be displayed on a rotating basis among the [[9/11 Memorial Museum]], [[Citi Field]], and the [[National Baseball Hall of Fame]].<ref>{{cite news | url=https://nypost.com/2016/04/14/mets-fans-spend-big-to-rescue-piazza-911-jersey-as-museum-piece/ | title=Mets fans spend big to rescue Piazza 9/11 jersey as museum piece | newspaper=New York Post | date=April 14, 2016 | last=Kernan | first=Kevin | access-date=July 21, 2017 | url-status=live | archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20170728141940/http://nypost.com/2016/04/14/mets-fans-spend-big-to-rescue-piazza-911-jersey-as-museum-piece/ | archivedate=July 28, 2017 | df=mdy-all }}</ref><ref>{{cite news |url=https://nypost.com/2016/04/05/mike-piazza-just-cant-believe-mets-sold-his-famed-911-jersey/ |title=Frustrated Mike Piazza speaks out on Mets' 9/11 jersey shocker |newspaper=New York Post |date=April 5, 2016 |last=Kernan |first=Kevin |access-date=July 21, 2017 |url-status=live |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20170728145804/http://nypost.com/2016/04/05/mike-piazza-just-cant-believe-mets-sold-his-famed-911-jersey/ |archivedate=July 28, 2017 |df=mdy-all }}</ref>\n\nOn October 2, 2017, Scaramucci launched the online media venture '''the Scaramucci Post'''. At a press conference, Scaramucci said that \"we have no idea what the Scaramucci Post is and neither do you. But, we launched it today and we launched with great fanfare and so we'll have to see how the whole thing unfolds.\"<ref>{{Cite news|url=http://fortune.com/2017/10/03/the-mooch-launches-the-scaramucci-post/|title='We Have No Idea What the Scaramucci Post Is and Neither Do You': The Mooch Launches His New Venture|work=Fortune|date=October 3, 2017|access-date=October 23, 2017|language=en|url-status=live|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20171024091645/http://fortune.com/2017/10/03/the-mooch-launches-the-scaramucci-post/|archivedate=October 24, 2017|df=mdy-all}}</ref> Later that month, the Post was criticized for posting a Twitter poll asking \"How many Jews were killed in the Holocaust?\". The tweet was posted by Scaramucci's business partner Lance Laifer without the approval of Scaramucci, who was in London at the time; when he found out about the tweet, Scaramucci was reportedly furious at Laifer.<ref>{{Cite news|url=http://www.newsweek.com/anthony-scaramucci-scaramucci-post-holocaust-jews-twitter-poll-686629|title=Anthony Scaramucci's new media venture offends Twitter with poll about Jewish Holocaust deaths|date=October 17, 2017|work=Newsweek|access-date=October 23, 2017|language=en|url-status=live|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20171024043129/http://www.newsweek.com/anthony-scaramucci-scaramucci-post-holocaust-jews-twitter-poll-686629|archivedate=October 24, 2017|df=mdy-all}}</ref> The tweet was soon taken down, and Scaramucci subsequently wrote that \"If anyone was offended by this act, you have both my sincere personal apology and commitment that it will never happen again\", and pledged to donate $25,000 to the [[Simon Wiesenthal Center]]. Subsequently, however, the Post tweeted that they had changed their mind on the poll, defending their decision to post it and accusing their critics of \"laziness and mob-mentality\", claiming that the poll was designed to illustrate that memory was fading about the death of 6 million Jews.<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.vanityfair.com/news/2017/10/scaramucci-post-tries-fails-to-quell-its-sick-holocaust-curiosity|date=October 20, 2017|title=Scaramucci Post Tries, Fails to Quell Its Sick Holocaust Curiosity|last=Levin|first=Bess|work=The Hive|access-date=October 23, 2017|language=en|url-status=live|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20180208172722/https://www.vanityfair.com/news/2017/10/scaramucci-post-tries-fails-to-quell-its-sick-holocaust-curiosity|archivedate=December 24, 2017|df=mdy-all}}</ref>\n\nOn January 13, 2019, it was announced Scaramucci would be a participant in the [[Celebrity Big Brother 2 (U.S.)|second American season]] of the reality show competition ''[[Celebrity Big Brother (U.S. TV series)|Celebrity Big Brother]];''<ref name=\":4\">{{cite web|url=https://www.hollywoodreporter.com/live-feed/celebrity-big-brother-cast-revealed-ryan-lochte-anthony-scaramucci-dina-lohan-more-1175684|title='Celebrity Big Brother' Cast Includes Anthony Scaramucci, Dina Lohan and Ryan Lochte|last=Porreca|first=Brian|date=13 January 2019|website=www.hollywoodreporter.com/|publisher=[[The Hollywood Reporter]]|access-date=13 January 2019}}</ref><ref name=\":5\">{{cite web|url=https://ew.com/tv/2019/01/13/celebrity-big-brother-cast-anthony-scaramucci/|title=Anthony Scaramucci among 12 new Celebrity Big Brother houseguests|last=Ross|first=Dalton|date=13 January 2019|website=www.ew.com/|publisher=[[Entertainment Weekly]]|access-date=13 January 2019}}</ref> though, in a twist, it was revealed he was a Fake HouseGuest on the show.\n\n=== Tufts controversy ===\nIn June 2016, Scaramucci joined the Board of Advisors of the [[Fletcher School of Law and Diplomacy]], located at his alma mater of Tufts University.<ref name=\":2\">{{Cite news|url=https://www.bostonglobe.com/metro/2017/11/06/some-students-alums-say-the-mooch-doesn-belong-tufts-board/cmnOWHgNo02d496sbMcKFP/story.html|title=Some students, alums say 'The Mooch' doesn't belong on Tufts board|last=Fernandes|first=Deirdre|date=7 November 2017|work=Boston Globe|access-date=2017-11-28|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20171201033908/https://www.bostonglobe.com/metro/2017/11/06/some-students-alums-say-the-mooch-doesn-belong-tufts-board/cmnOWHgNo02d496sbMcKFP/story.html|archive-date=December 1, 2017|url-status=live|df=mdy-all}}</ref> In early November 2017, 240 Tufts students, faculty, and alumni signed an online petition calling for Scaramucci's removal from the position.<ref name=\":2\" /> One Fletcher graduate student, Camilo Caballero, wrote a pair of op-eds in Tufts' independent student newspaper, ''[[The Tufts Daily]]'', on November 6 and 13.<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://tuftsdaily.com/opinion/2017/11/06/op-ed-seeking-power-values-power-money/|title=Op-Ed: Seeking power of values over power of money|last=Caballero|first=Camilo|date=2017-11-06|work=The Tufts Daily|access-date=2017-11-28|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20171127182942/https://tuftsdaily.com/opinion/2017/11/06/op-ed-seeking-power-values-power-money/|archive-date=November 27, 2017|url-status=live|language=en-US|df=mdy-all}}</ref><ref>{{Cite news|url=https://tuftsdaily.com/opinion/2017/11/13/op-ed-tuftsfletcher-administration-fell-scaramuccis-trap-students-faculty-smarter/|title=Op-Ed: Tufts/Fletcher administration fell into Scaramucci's trap: Students and faculty are smarter|last=Caballero|first=Camilo|date=2017-11-13|work=The Tufts Daily|access-date=2017-11-28|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20171128161943/https://tuftsdaily.com/opinion/2017/11/13/op-ed-tuftsfletcher-administration-fell-scaramuccis-trap-students-faculty-smarter/|archive-date=November 28, 2017|url-status=live|language=en-US|df=mdy-all}}</ref> On November 21, 2017, lawyers representing Scaramucci sent a [[Cease and desist|cease-and-desist]] letter to the ''Daily,'' alleging that the op-eds contained factual inaccuracies which attempted to defame him.<ref name=\":3\">{{Cite news|url=https://tuftsdaily.com/opinion/2017/11/27/cease-and-desist-letter/|title=Claiming defamation, lawyer for Anthony Scaramucci demands retractions from Daily op-eds|last=|first=|date=2017-11-27|work=The Tufts Daily|access-date=2017-11-28|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20171127072106/https://tuftsdaily.com/opinion/2017/11/27/cease-and-desist-letter/|archive-date=November 27, 2017|url-status=live|language=en-US|df=mdy-all}}</ref> The letter demanded that Caballero and the ''Daily'' issue a retraction and an apology for its allegedly \"defamatory\" statements, threatening a lawsuit if the paper did not comply within five business days.<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.bostonglobe.com/metro/2017/11/26/tufts-postpones-scaramucci-event-after-threatens-student-and-paper-with-lawsuit/uKOsaakB8dH3cyiyYcwiyL/story.html|title=Tufts postpones Scaramucci event after he threatens student and paper with lawsuit|last=Hilliard|first=John|date=27 November 2017|work=Boston Globe|access-date=2017-11-28|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20171127225034/https://www.bostonglobe.com/metro/2017/11/26/tufts-postpones-scaramucci-event-after-threatens-student-and-paper-with-lawsuit/uKOsaakB8dH3cyiyYcwiyL/story.html|archive-date=November 27, 2017|url-status=live|df=mdy-all}}</ref><ref name=\":1\">{{Cite news|url=https://www.washingtonpost.com/news/grade-point/wp/2017/11/27/tufts-postpones-scaramucci-talk-after-he-threatens-to-sue-student/|title=Tufts postpones Scaramucci talk after he threatens to sue student|last=Svrluga|first=Susan|date=2017-11-27|work=Washington Post|access-date=2017-11-28|language=en-US|issn=0190-8286|url-status=live|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20171127195131/https://www.washingtonpost.com/news/grade-point/wp/2017/11/27/tufts-postpones-scaramucci-talk-after-he-threatens-to-sue-student/|archivedate=November 27, 2017|df=mdy-all}}</ref> The ''Daily'' opted to keep the full text of the editorials on its website while publishing publicly the cease-and-desist letter on November 27, 2017.<ref name=\":3\" /><ref name=\":1\" /> That evening, members of the [[Tufts University#Student government|Tufts Community Union (TCU) Senate]], the main student government body at Tufts University, publicly called on the university to remove Scaramucci from the Fletcher School's Board of Advisors.<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://tuftsdaily.com/news/2017/11/27/tcu-senators-call-tufts-remove-scaramucci-fletcher-board-advisors/|title=TCU Senators call on Tufts to remove Scaramucci from Fletcher Board of Advisors|last=Walsh|first=Joe|date=2017-11-27|work=The Tufts Daily|access-date=2017-11-28|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20171128082742/https://tuftsdaily.com/news/2017/11/27/tcu-senators-call-tufts-remove-scaramucci-fletcher-board-advisors/|archive-date=November 28, 2017|url-status=live|language=en-US|df=mdy-all}}</ref> On November 28, 2017, Scaramucci resigned his position.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://twitter.com/TuftsDaily/status/935535741442121729|title=BREAKING: Anthony Scaramucci has resigned from The Fletcher School's Board of Advisors effective immediately. The resignation was announced this morning in an email to the Fletcher community from Dean James Stavridis and Provost David Harris.pic.twitter.com/VGiOvHkC8K|last=Daily|first=The Tufts|date=2017-11-28|website=@TuftsDaily|language=en|access-date=2017-11-28|url-status=live|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20180210070156/https://twitter.com/TuftsDaily/status/935535741442121729|archivedate=February 10, 2018|df=mdy-all}}</ref>\n\n==Personal life==\n\nScaramucci's first marriage was to Lisa Miranda. They separated in 2011 after 23 years of marriage, and their divorce was finalized in 2014.<ref name=schuster /><ref>{{cite web|last1=McBride|first1=Jessica|title=Lisa Miranda, Anthony Scaramucci's Ex Wife: 5 Fast Facts You Need to Know|url=https://heavy.com/news/2017/07/lisa-miranda-scaramucci-ex-wife-first-photos-anthony-children-daughter-amelia-demilo-divorce/|publisher=Heavy.com|accessdate=July 31, 2017|url-status=live|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20170730121345/https://heavy.com/news/2017/07/lisa-miranda-scaramucci-ex-wife-first-photos-anthony-children-daughter-amelia-demilo-divorce/|archivedate=July 30, 2017|df=mdy-all}}</ref>\n\nHis second marriage is with Deidre Ball. Ball worked in investor relations for SkyBridge Capital until Scaramucci left the firm. The couple first dated in 2011 and married on July 11, 2014,<ref name=mcbride>{{cite web |url=http://heavy.com/news/2017/07/anthony-scaramucci-family-parents-father-children-wife-deidre-italian-manhasset-long-island/ |title=Anthony Scaramucci's Family: 5 Fast Facts You Need to Know |author=McBride, Jessica |publisher=[[Heavy.com]] |date=July 21, 2017 |accessdate=July 24, 2017 |url-status=live |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20170722062040/http://heavy.com/news/2017/07/anthony-scaramucci-family-parents-father-children-wife-deidre-italian-manhasset-long-island/ |archivedate=July 22, 2017 |df=mdy-all }}</ref> after having their first child together in early 2014. Scaramucci and Ball separated briefly in early 2017.<ref name = schuster/> Ball filed for divorce from Scaramucci in early July 2017 when she was pregnant with their second child, to whom she gave birth on July 24, 2017,<ref name=schuster /><ref name=independent>{{cite web |url=https://www.independent.co.uk/news/world/americas/us-politics/anthony-scaramucci-wife-miss-birth-son-donald-trump-white-house-communications-deidre-scaramucci-a7868351.html |title=Anthony Scaramucci 'texted \"I'll pray for our child\" to his wife after missing birth of their son' |author=Pasha-Robinson, Lucy |publisher=Independent |date=July 31, 2017 |accessdate=July 31, 2017 |url-status=live |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20170731190655/http://www.independent.co.uk/news/world/americas/us-politics/anthony-scaramucci-wife-miss-birth-son-donald-trump-white-house-communications-deidre-scaramucci-a7868351.html |archivedate=July 31, 2017 |df=mdy-all }}</ref> but she dropped the divorce case on November 29, 2017.<ref name=pagesix>{{cite web |url=https://pagesix.com/2017/11/30/scaramucci-and-his-wife-call-off-their-divorce/ |title=Scaramucci and his wife call off their divorce |author=Julia Marsh, Chris Perez |publisher=Page Six |date=November 30, 2017 |url-status=live |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20171208174857/https://pagesix.com/2017/11/30/scaramucci-and-his-wife-call-off-their-divorce/ |archivedate=December 8, 2017 |df=mdy-all }}</ref> The couple worked out their marital problems and in September 2018 began a [[Radio.com]] podcast titled \"Mooch and the Mrs.\", in which they discuss their world view from opposite political stances, while managing their relationship.<ref>{{cite news |url=https://www.foxnews.com/entertainment/anthony-scaramucci-once-estranged-wife-doing-just-fine |title=Anthony Scaramucci, wife 'managed to work it out' after marital trouble detailed in tabloids |first=Brian |last=Flood |date=September 28, 2018 |publisher=Fox News |access-date=November 2, 2018 }}</ref><ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.radio.com/blogs/anthony-scaramucci-podcast-mooch-and-mrs-streaming-radiocom |title=Radio.com Launches Anthony and Deidre Scaramucci Podcast |date=September 18, 2018 |website=Radio.com |access-date=November 2, 2018 }}</ref>\n\n==References==\n{{reflist|30em}}\n\n==External links==\n{{sisterlinks|d=Q4773428|c=category:Anthony Scaramucci|n=no|b=no|v=no|voy=no|m=no|mw=no|species=no|s=no|wikt=no}}\n*{{C-SPAN|Anthony Scaramucci}}\n\n{{s-start}}\n{{s-off}}\n{{s-bef|before=[[Sean Spicer]]<br>Acting}}\n{{s-ttl|title=[[White House Communications Director|White House Director of Communications]]|years=2017}}\n{{s-aft|after=[[Hope Hicks]]<br>}}\n{{s-end}}\n\n{{WHCD}}\n{{authority control}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Scaramucci, Anthony}}\n[[Category:1964 births]]\n[[Category:21st-century American non-fiction writers]]\n[[Category:American financial writers]]\n[[Category:American financiers]]\n[[Category:American hedge fund managers]]\n[[Category:American male non-fiction writers]]\n[[Category:American people of Italian descent]]\n[[Category:American men podcasters]]\n[[Category:American podcasters]]\n[[Category:Celebrity Big Brother]]\n[[Category:Contestants on American game shows]]\n[[Category:Goldman Sachs people]]\n[[Category:Harvard Law School alumni]]\n[[Category:Living people]]\n[[Category:New York (state) Republicans]]\n[[Category:Paul D. Schreiber High School alumni]]\n[[Category:People from Long Island]]\n[[Category:People from Manhasset, New York]]\n[[Category:People from Port Washington, New York]]\n[[Category:People of Umbrian descent]]\n[[Category:Trump administration personnel]]\n[[Category:Tufts University alumni]]\n[[Category:White House Communications Directors]]\n[[Category:Writers from New York (state)]]\n", "name_user": "Burninmyleather", "label": "unsafe", "comment": "", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Anthony_Scaramucci"}
{"title_page": "Transplant surgeon", "text_new": "{{short description|Surgeon specializing in organ transplantation}}\n{{more citations needed|date=November 2018}}\nA '''transplant surgeon''' is a [[surgeon]] who performs [[organ transplant]]s. Among the many [[Organ (anatomy)|organs]] that can be transplanted are: [[kidney]]s. [[liver]]s, [[heart]]s, [[lung]]s, the [[pancreas]], the intestine (especially the [[small intestine]]), and recently, [[face]]s, tracheal (windpipe) tissue, and [[penis]]es. \n\n==Medical training==\n\nTraining in the U.S. involves the four years of the undergraduate education, four years of medical school, five years of general surgery residency, followed by a two year fellowship in transplant surgery. <ref>{{Cite web|url=https://residency.wustl.edu/choosing-a-specialty/specialty-descriptions/general-surgery/|title=General Surgery {{!}} Residency Roadmap|website=residency.wustl.edu|access-date=2019-12-23}}</ref>\n\n== Notable Surgeons ==\n\n* [[Thomas Starzl]] - first human liver transplants. Often quoted as the \u201cfather of modern transplantation\u201d\n* [[Theodor Kocher]] - first modern transplant\n* [[James Hardy (surgeon)|James D. Hardy]] - first successful lung transplant \n* [[Bruce Reitz]] - first successful heart transplant\n*[[Patrick Soon-Shiong|Patrick Soon Shiong]] - first pancreatic islet cell transplant\n\n==See also==\n* [[Transplant surgery]]\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist}}\n\n[[Category:Transplant surgeons| ]]\n[[Category:Health care occupations]]\n", "text_old": "{{short description|Surgeon specializing in organ transplantation}}\n{{more citations needed|date=November 2018}}\nA '''transplant surgeon''' is a [[surgeon]] who performs [[organ transplant]]s. Among the many [[Organ (anatomy)|organs]] that can be transplanted are: [[kidney]]s. [[liver]]s, [[heart]]s, [[lung]]s, the [[pancreas]], the intestine (especially the [[small intestine]]), and recently, [[face]]s, tracheal (windpipe) tissue, and [[penis]]es. \n\n==Medical training==\n\nTraining in the U.S. involves the four years of the undergraduate education, four years of medical school, five years of general surgery residency, followed by a two year fellowship in transplant surgery. <ref>{{Cite web|url=https://residency.wustl.edu/choosing-a-specialty/specialty-descriptions/general-surgery/|title=General Surgery {{!}} Residency Roadmap|website=residency.wustl.edu|access-date=2019-12-23}}</ref>\n\n== Notable Surgeons ==\n\n* [[Thomas Starzl]] - first human liver transplants. Often quoted as the \u201cfather of modern transplantation\u201d\n* [[Theodor Kocher]] - first modern transplant\n* [[James Hardy (surgeon)|James D. Hardy]] - first successful lung transplant \n* [[Bruce Reitz]] - first successful heart transplant\n\n==See also==\n* [[Transplant surgery]]\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist}}\n\n[[Category:Transplant surgeons| ]]\n[[Category:Health care occupations]]\n", "name_user": "Jojo1478", "label": "safe", "comment": "Added Patrick soon shiong", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Transplant_surgeon"}
{"title_page": "Chamath Palihapitiya", "text_new": "{{Infobox person\n| name        =Chamath Palihapitiya\n| image       = Chamath Palihapitiya Portrait.jpg\n| caption     = Palihapitiya in 2018\n| birth_date   =\n| birth_place  = [[Sri Lanka]]\n| citizenship = Canada, United States\n| education = [[University of Waterloo]]\n| known_for   = Software development, venture capital\n| years active = 2007\u2013present\n| net worth = \n}}\n\n'''Chamath Palihapitiya''' is a South Asian-Canadian [[venture capital]]ist and the founder and [[CEO]] of [[Social Capital (venture capital)|Social Capital]]. Palihapitiya was an early senior executive at [[Facebook]], joining the company in 2007 and leaving in 2011. He is a minority stakeholder and board member of the [[Golden State Warriors]].<ref name=\"newyorkmag\">Roose, Kevin (October 16, 2013) [http://nymag.com/daily/intelligencer/2013/10/silicon-valleys-dysfunction-fetish.html \"The Government Shutdown Has Revealed Silicon Valley\u2019s Dysfunction Fetish.\"] ''New York Magazine.'' (Retrieved 5-14-2014.)</ref>\n\n==Life and career==\n===Early life and education===\n\nPalihapitiya was born in [[Sri Lanka]] and, at the age of six, moved with his family to [[Canada]] as refugees. Throughout his childhood, Palihapitiya's father was constantly unemployed and his mother was a housekeeper, and later a nurses' aid. Living on [[welfare]], Palihapitiya recalls sleeping on a mattress in the living room.<ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.cnbc.com/2017/10/15/social-capitals-chamath-palihapitiya-explains-the-beauty-of-a-calculated-risk.html|title = Social Capital's Chamath Palihapitiya explains the beauty of a calculated risk |last = Fortt |first= Jon|date = 2017-10-15|accessdate = 2017-05-22|work = CNBC}}</ref> He attended [[Lisgar Collegiate Institute]] while working part time to assist his family, and graduated at the age of 17.<ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.nytimes.com/2017/10/20/business/corner-office-chamath-palihapitiya-social-capital.html|title=Chamath Palihapitiya of Social Capital on the Paradox of Ego and Humility |last=Bryant|first=Adam|date=2017-10-20|accessdate = 2017-05-22|work= The New York}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=https://heritageottawa.org/news/lisgar-collegiate-graduates-celebrate-venerable-building|title=Lisgar Collegiate graduates to celebrate venerable building | publisher= Heritage Ottawa |accessdate= 2018-05-22}}</ref>\n\nAfter graduating from the [[University of Waterloo]] in 1999 with a degree in [[electrical engineering]], Palihapitiya worked for a year as a [[derivative (finance)|derivatives]] trader at the [[investment bank]] [[BMO Nesbitt Burns]]. He moved to [[California]] to be with his then-girlfriend, Brigette Lau, and they later married.<ref name=nytimes-profile>{{cite news|url=https://dealbook.nytimes.com/2011/10/06/in-flip-flops-and-jeans-the-unconventional-venture-capitalist/|title = In Flip-Flops and Jeans, An Unconventional Venture Capitalist|last = Rusli|first = Evelyn|date = 2011-10-06|accessdate = 2013-04-23|work=The New York Times}}</ref> In 2018 Palihapitiya filed for divorce.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://unicourt.com/case/ca-sm-chamath-palihapitiya-vs-brigette-lau-382244|title=San Mateo County Court Proceedings|date = 2019-02-20|accessdate = 2019-03-08}}</ref>\n\n===Career as a software engineer and manager===\n\nPalihapitiya joined [[AOL]], becoming the company's youngest vice president ever, heading its instant messaging division in 2004.<ref name=nytimes-profile/><ref>{{cite news|url=http://www.businessinsider.com/the-fabulous-life-of-facebook-millionaire-chamath-palihapitiya-2015-6| title=Meet Facebook's most successful alum, a borderline billionaire who owns the Golden State Warriors|last = Stone |first= Madeline|date=2015-06-01|accessdate=2018-05-22|work=Business Insider}}</ref> In 2005, he left AOL and joined [[Mayfield Fund]]; a few months later he left that job and joined [[Facebook]], which was then a little more than a year old.<ref name=nytimes-profile/> Palihapitiya's work at Facebook involved trying to increase its userbase.<ref name=businessweek/>\n\n===Career as a venture capitalist===\n{{see also|Social Capital (venture capital)}}\nPalihapitiya made investments on the side while still employed at Facebook, including investments in [[Palantir Technologies|Palantir]], [[Pure Storage]] (NYSE:PSTG), [[Playdom]] (bought by [[The Walt Disney Company]]), and [[Bumptop]] (bought by [[Google]]).\n\nIn 2011, he left Facebook<ref>https://techcrunch.com/2011/06/03/facebook-vp-chamath-venture-socialcapital/</ref> and started his own fund, [[The Social+Capital Partnership]], with his wife. The firm changed its name to Social Capital in 2015.<ref name=nytimes-profile/><ref name=social-capital-crunchbase>{{cite web|url=http://www.crunchbase.com/financial-organization/the-social-capital-partnership|title = The Social+Capital Partnership |accessdate = 2013-04-23}}</ref><ref>{{cite news|url=https://techcrunch.com/2011/06/03/facebook-vp-chamath-venture-socialcapital/|title = Facebook VP Chamath Palihapitiya Forms New Venture Fund, The Social+Capital Partnership|last = Arrington|first = Michael|work = [[TechCrunch]]|date = 2011-06-03|accessdate = 2013-04-23}}</ref> It has stood out strategically, with a focus on technology in healthcare, financial services, and education, as well as on software as a service. Social Capital started investing in health and education when those fields were largely neglected by other venture capitalists.<ref name=techcrunch>{{cite news|url=https://techcrunch.com/2011/09/27/former-facebook-vp-chamath-palihapitiya-leads-17m-round-in-enterprise-social-networking-platform-yammer/|title = Former Facebook VP Chamath Palihapitiya Leads $17M Round In Enterprise Social Networking Platform Yammer|last = Rao|first = Leena|date = 2011-09-27|accessdate = 2013-04-23|work = [[TechCrunch]]}}</ref>\n\nThe fund was praised by [[Peter Thiel]], who invested in it and expressed enthusiasm for Palihapitiya's approach.<ref name=businessweek>{{cite web|url=http://www.businessweek.com/articles/2012-07-26/social-plus-capital-the-league-of-extraordinarily-rich-gentlemen|title = Social+Capital, the League of Extraordinarily Rich Gentlemen|last = Bennett|first = Drake|date = 2012-07-26|accessdate = 2013-04-23}}</ref>\n\nThrough the fund, Palihapitiya has invested in a number of companies, including [[Glooko, Inc]], [[Yammer]], [[SecondMarket]], [[Slack (software)|Slack]], [[Box (company)|Box]], and [[Premise (company)|Premise]].<ref name=\"techcrunch\"/><ref name=wsj>{{cite web|url=https://blogs.wsj.com/venturecapital/2015/03/17/the-daily-startup-paper-drawing-app-aims-for-enterprise-with-new-funding/|title = The Daily Startup: Paper Drawing App Aims for Enterprise With New Funding|last = Billings|first = Mike|date = 2015-03-17|accessdate = 2015-04-22|publisher = Wall Street Journal Blog}}</ref><ref>{{cite news|url=https://venturebeat.com/2011/11/02/secondmarket-raises-15m-at-200m-valuation-from-former-facebook-exec-palihapitiya/|title = SecondMarket raises $15M at $200M valuation from former Facebook exec|last = Marshall|first = Matt|work = [[VentureBeat]]|date = 2011-11-02|accessdate = 2013-04-23}}</ref> In 2017 he became a member of the [[board of directors]] of [[Slack (software)|Slack]].<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.businesswire.com/news/home/20191204005852/en/Slack-Appoints-Flex-CEO-Mike-McNamara-Board|title=Slack Appoints Former Flex CEO Mike McNamara to Its Board of Directors}}</ref>\n\nIn March 2013, Palihapitiya confirmed that his venture fund had raised more than $275 million in its second round of fundraising.<ref>{{cite news|url=https://techcrunch.com/2013/03/04/social-capital-partnership-new-fund/|title = Chamath Palihapitiya Confirms That His Social+Capital Partnership Has Raised A New Fund Of $275M+|date = 2013-03-04|accessdate = 2013-04-23|last = Ha|first = Anthony|work = [[TechCrunch]]}}</ref><ref>{{cite news|url=https://venturebeat.com/2013/03/04/making-money-and-a-difference-socialcapital-partnership-confirms-new-fund/|title = Making money and a difference, Social+Capital Partnership confirms new fund|work = [[VentureBeat]]|accessdate = 2013-04-23|date = 2013-03-04|last = Grant|first = Rebecca}}</ref>  As of 2015, the fund had more than $1.1 billion in total assets.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://fortune.com/2015/05/18/is-socialcapitals-chamath-palihapitiya-the-future-of-venture-capital/|title = Is Social+Capital's Chamath Palihapitiya the future of venture capital?|publisher = FORTUNE|accessdate = 2016-02-23|date = 2016-03-23|last = Rao|first = Leena}}</ref>\n\nIn October 2015, Palihapitiya and Social Capital worked with the technology industry publication ''The Information'' to publish a report on diversity in venture capital. The study found that 92% of senior investment teams at top-tier venture firms are male and 78% are white.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.theinformation.com/introducing-the-informations-future-list|title = Introducing The Information's Future List|publisher = The Information|accessdate = 2016-02-23|date = 2016-03-23|last = Schulz|first = Peter}}</ref> Based on the report, Palihapitiya wrote an op-ed calling for a \"wake-up call\" among venture capital firms that would \"recapture our potential and open doors\" in order to \"surround ourselves with a more diverse set of experiences and\u2026prioritize a diverse set of things.\"<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.theinformation.com/bros-funding-bros-whats-wrong-with-venture-capital|title = IBros Funding Bros: What's Wrong with Venture Capital|publisher = The Information|accessdate = 2016-02-23|date = 2016-03-23|last = Palihapitiya|first = Chamath}}</ref>\n\nIn 2019 Palihapitiya stepped down as a member of the board of directors of [[Slack (software)|Slack]].<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.businesswire.com/news/home/20191204005852/en/Slack-Appoints-Flex-CEO-Mike-McNamara-Board|title=Slack Appoints Former Flex CEO Mike McNamara to Its Board of Directors}}</ref>\n\n===Career as a poker player===\n\nPalihapitiya has three [[World Series of Poker|World Series of Poker (WSOP)]] and two [[World Poker Tour|World Poker Tour (WPT)]] cashes for a total of $175,801.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.cardplayer.com/poker-players/214938-chamath-palihapitiya|title=Chamath Palihapitiya: Cash Out|accessdate=22 Feb 2016}}</ref> In 2011, he finished 101st out of 6,865 entries in the World Series of Poker's Main Event.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://pokerdb.thehendonmob.com/event.php?a=r&n=51923|title=42nd World Series of Poker (WSOP) 2011 United States|accessdate=22 Feb 2016}}</ref>\n\n==Politics==\n\n===Immigration reform and policy advocacy===\n\nPalihapitiya was listed as one of the \"Founders\" of the lobbying group [[FWD.us]].<ref name=fwd-us-supporters>{{cite web|url = http://www.fwd.us/our_supporters|title = Our Supporters|publisher = FWD.us|accessdate = 2013-04-23|archive-url = https://web.archive.org/web/20130413230948/http://www.fwd.us/our_supporters|archive-date = 2013-04-13|url-status = dead}}</ref> The group launched on April 11, 2013, and its goals include immigration reform, improving education, and enabling technological innovation, all in a United States context.<ref name=fwd-us-about-us>{{cite web|url=http://www.fwd.us/about_us|title = About Us|publisher = FWD.us|accessdate = 2013-04-23}}</ref><ref name=zuck-op-ed>{{cite news|url=https://www.washingtonpost.com/opinions/mark-zuckerberg-immigrants-are-the-key-to-a-knowledge-economy/2013/04/10/aba05554-a20b-11e2-82bc-511538ae90a4_story.html|title = Facebook's Mark Zuckerberg: Immigration and the knowledge economy|last = Zuckerberg|first = Mark|date = 2013-04-11|accessdate = 2013-04-17|newspaper = [[Washington Post]]}}</ref> An article in ''[[The New Republic]]'' stated that Palihapitiya received a weekly report about FWD.us and also quoted him as saying, in response to controversy around the FWD.us political lobbying strategy: \"The folks that are actually people that run that day to day are sophisticated and understand the nuances of how to affect it... It's a really gnarly, gnarly thing having to deal with Washington. And to be honest with you, my perspective was, it's a really good investment because it's a good way to pay it forward, and I'm really glad there are other people other than me who are dealing with it who have the patience and resolve to figure it out.\"<ref>{{cite magazine|url=https://newrepublic.com/article/113117/mark-zuckerbergs-immigration-reform-strategy-necessary-cynicism|title = Mark Zuckerberg's Cynical, Necessary Washington Strategy|last = DePillis|first = Lydia|accessdate = 2013-05-07|date = 2013-05-06|magazine = [[The New Republic]]}}</ref>\n\n===San Francisco inequality and housing controversy===\nAt [[Bloomberg L.P.|Bloomberg]]'s ''Next Big Thing'' conference in [[Sausalito, California]], Palihapitiya made remarks critical of San Francisco's then mayor, [[Ed Lee (politician)|Ed Lee]], and proposed that the city provide subsidized housing to low-income residents funded by an equity tax on startups, with the tax-and-subsidy schemes potentially restricted to particular zones of the city. This led to a heated debate between Palihapitiya and [[super angel]] [[Ron Conway]]. Conway, a supporter of Lee, defended the city's policies, argued that things would get better for all residents, and noted that Palihapitiya lives in [[Palo Alto]] rather than in the city.<ref>{{cite magazine|url=http://www.slate.com/blogs/future_tense/2014/06/09/ron_conway_chamath_palihapitiya_get_into_shouting_match_at_sausalito_tech.html|title = Tech Conference Turns Into Shouting Match About Inequality in Silicon Valley|last = Oremus|first = Will|date = June 9, 2014|accessdate = July 9, 2015|magazine = [[Slate (magazine)|Slate]]}}</ref><ref>{{cite news|url = http://blog.sfgate.com/techchron/2014/06/09/ron-conway-mocks-fellow-venture-capitalist-uses-phrase-palo-alto-resident-as-insult/|title = Ron Conway mocks fellow venture capitalist, uses phrase 'Palo Alto resident' as insult|last = Garofoli|first = Joe|date = June 9, 2014|accessdate = July 9, 2015|newspaper = [[San Francisco Chronicle]]}}</ref> In a later clarification to ''[[TechCrunch]]'', Palihapitiya outlined his vision in more detail and described how his views on inequality and social mobility were shaped by his experience growing up with relatively poor immigrant parents in [[Canada]].<ref>{{cite news|url=https://techcrunch.com/2014/06/09/eruption-over-sf-housing-and-google-breaks-out-at-next-big-thing-conference/|title = Ron Conway And Chamath Palihapitiya Debate SF Housing And Google At Next Big Thing Conference|last = Buhr|first = Sarah|date = June 9, 2014|accessdate = July 9, 2015|work = [[TechCrunch]]}}</ref>\n\n===Criticism of Facebook and social media===\nIn November 2017, Palihapitiya revealed that, for ethical reasons, he regrets having helped Facebook to become the largest social media platform.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.businessinsider.com/former-facebook-exec-chamath-palihapitiya-social-media-damaging-society-2017-12|title=Former Facebook exec feels 'tremendous guilt' for what he helped make|publisher=}}</ref> He said, \"[t]he short-term, dopamine-driven feedback loops that we have created are destroying how society works: no civil discourse, no cooperation, misinformation, mistruth and it's not an American problem. This is not about Russian ads. This is a global problem. It is eroding the core foundations of how people behave by and between each other. I can't control them. I can control my decision, which is that I don't use that shit. I can control my kids' decisions, which is that they're not allowed to use that shit\".<ref>{{cite web |first=Julia Carrie |last=Wong |title=Former Facebook executive: social media is ripping society apart |url=https://www.theguardian.com/technology/2017/dec/11/facebook-former-executive-ripping-society-apart |work=[[The Guardian]] |date=December 12, 2017 |accessdate=December 12, 2017}}</ref><ref>{{Citation|last=Stanford Graduate School of Business|title=Chamath Palihapitiya, Founder and CEO Social Capital, on Money as an Instrument of Change|date=2017-11-13|url=https://www.youtube.com/watch?time_continue=1281&v=PMotykw0SIk|accessdate=2017-12-13}}</ref> Following criticism from Facebook for his remarks, Palihapitiya subsequently clarified, \"I genuinely believe that Facebook is a force for good in the world, so I'd like to expand on my comments...My comments were meant to start an important conversation, not to criticize one company \u2014 particularly one I love. In 2017, many of us have grappled with the unintended consequences of the products we've built. Social media platforms in particular have been used and abused in ways that we, their architects, never imagined. Much blame has been thrown and guilt felt, but the important thing is what we as an industry do now to ensure that our impact on society continues to be a positive one.\"<ref>Gilbert, Ben (December 15, 2017). [http://www.businessinsider.com/former-facebook-exec-adds-context-to-social-media-criticism-2017-12 \"Former Facebook exec: I take back what I said about Facebook 'destroying how society works' \u2014 kinda\"]. ''Business Insider''.</ref><ref>Palihapitiya, Chamath (December 15, 2017). [https://www.facebook.com/chamath/posts/10159808356105644 (Untitled)]. [[Facebook]]. (Account confirmed by ''Business Insider'' article.)</ref>\n\n==References==\n{{reflist|2}}\n\n==External links==\n{{wikiquote}}\n* [http://www.crunchbase.com/person/chamath-palihapitiya Chamath Palihapitiya] on ''[[CrunchBase]]''\n* {{Twitter}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Palihapitiya, Chamath}}\n[[Category:American venture capitalists]]\n[[Category:Living people]]\n[[Category:University of Waterloo alumni]]\n[[Category:Sri Lankan emigrants to Canada]]\n[[Category:Bank of Montreal people]]\n[[Category:Canadian expatriates in the United States]]\n[[Category:Silicon Valley people]]\n[[Category:American people of Sri Lankan descent]]\n[[Category:Lisgar Collegiate Institute]]\n[[Category:American billionaires]]\n", "text_old": "{{Infobox person\n| name        =Chamath Palihapitiya\n| image       = Chamath Palihapitiya Portrait.jpg\n| caption     = Palihapitiya in 2018\n| birth_date   =\n| birth_place  = [[Sri Lanka]]\n| citizenship = Canada, United States\n| education = [[University of Waterloo]]\n| known_for   = Software development, venture capital\n| years active = 2007\u2013present\n| net worth = \n}}\n\n'''Chamath Palihapitiya''' is a Canadian [[venture capital]]ist and the founder and [[CEO]] of [[Social Capital (venture capital)|Social Capital]]. Palihapitiya was an early senior executive at [[Facebook]], joining the company in 2007 and leaving in 2011. He is a minority stakeholder and board member of the [[Golden State Warriors]].<ref name=\"newyorkmag\">Roose, Kevin (October 16, 2013) [http://nymag.com/daily/intelligencer/2013/10/silicon-valleys-dysfunction-fetish.html \"The Government Shutdown Has Revealed Silicon Valley\u2019s Dysfunction Fetish.\"] ''New York Magazine.'' (Retrieved 5-14-2014.)</ref>\n\n==Life and career==\n===Early life and education===\n\nPalihapitiya was born in [[Sri Lanka]] and, at the age of six, moved with his family to [[Canada]] as refugees. Throughout his childhood, Palihapitiya's father was constantly unemployed and his mother was a housekeeper, and later a nurses' aid. Living on [[welfare]], Palihapitiya recalls sleeping on a mattress in the living room.<ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.cnbc.com/2017/10/15/social-capitals-chamath-palihapitiya-explains-the-beauty-of-a-calculated-risk.html|title = Social Capital's Chamath Palihapitiya explains the beauty of a calculated risk |last = Fortt |first= Jon|date = 2017-10-15|accessdate = 2017-05-22|work = CNBC}}</ref> He attended [[Lisgar Collegiate Institute]] while working part time to assist his family, and graduated at the age of 17.<ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.nytimes.com/2017/10/20/business/corner-office-chamath-palihapitiya-social-capital.html|title=Chamath Palihapitiya of Social Capital on the Paradox of Ego and Humility |last=Bryant|first=Adam|date=2017-10-20|accessdate = 2017-05-22|work= The New York}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=https://heritageottawa.org/news/lisgar-collegiate-graduates-celebrate-venerable-building|title=Lisgar Collegiate graduates to celebrate venerable building | publisher= Heritage Ottawa |accessdate= 2018-05-22}}</ref>\n\nAfter graduating from the [[University of Waterloo]] in 1999 with a degree in [[electrical engineering]], Palihapitiya worked for a year as a [[derivative (finance)|derivatives]] trader at the [[investment bank]] [[BMO Nesbitt Burns]]. He moved to [[California]] to be with his then-girlfriend, Brigette Lau, and they later married.<ref name=nytimes-profile>{{cite news|url=https://dealbook.nytimes.com/2011/10/06/in-flip-flops-and-jeans-the-unconventional-venture-capitalist/|title = In Flip-Flops and Jeans, An Unconventional Venture Capitalist|last = Rusli|first = Evelyn|date = 2011-10-06|accessdate = 2013-04-23|work=The New York Times}}</ref> In 2018 Palihapitiya filed for divorce.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://unicourt.com/case/ca-sm-chamath-palihapitiya-vs-brigette-lau-382244|title=San Mateo County Court Proceedings|date = 2019-02-20|accessdate = 2019-03-08}}</ref>\n\n===Career as a software engineer and manager===\n\nPalihapitiya joined [[AOL]], becoming the company's youngest vice president ever, heading its instant messaging division in 2004.<ref name=nytimes-profile/><ref>{{cite news|url=http://www.businessinsider.com/the-fabulous-life-of-facebook-millionaire-chamath-palihapitiya-2015-6| title=Meet Facebook's most successful alum, a borderline billionaire who owns the Golden State Warriors|last = Stone |first= Madeline|date=2015-06-01|accessdate=2018-05-22|work=Business Insider}}</ref> In 2005, he left AOL and joined [[Mayfield Fund]]; a few months later he left that job and joined [[Facebook]], which was then a little more than a year old.<ref name=nytimes-profile/> Palihapitiya's work at Facebook involved trying to increase its userbase.<ref name=businessweek/>\n\n===Career as a venture capitalist===\n{{see also|Social Capital (venture capital)}}\nPalihapitiya made investments on the side while still employed at Facebook, including investments in [[Palantir Technologies|Palantir]], [[Pure Storage]] (NYSE:PSTG), [[Playdom]] (bought by [[The Walt Disney Company]]), and [[Bumptop]] (bought by [[Google]]).\n\nIn 2011, he left Facebook<ref>https://techcrunch.com/2011/06/03/facebook-vp-chamath-venture-socialcapital/</ref> and started his own fund, [[The Social+Capital Partnership]], with his wife. The firm changed its name to Social Capital in 2015.<ref name=nytimes-profile/><ref name=social-capital-crunchbase>{{cite web|url=http://www.crunchbase.com/financial-organization/the-social-capital-partnership|title = The Social+Capital Partnership |accessdate = 2013-04-23}}</ref><ref>{{cite news|url=https://techcrunch.com/2011/06/03/facebook-vp-chamath-venture-socialcapital/|title = Facebook VP Chamath Palihapitiya Forms New Venture Fund, The Social+Capital Partnership|last = Arrington|first = Michael|work = [[TechCrunch]]|date = 2011-06-03|accessdate = 2013-04-23}}</ref> It has stood out strategically, with a focus on technology in healthcare, financial services, and education, as well as on software as a service. Social Capital started investing in health and education when those fields were largely neglected by other venture capitalists.<ref name=techcrunch>{{cite news|url=https://techcrunch.com/2011/09/27/former-facebook-vp-chamath-palihapitiya-leads-17m-round-in-enterprise-social-networking-platform-yammer/|title = Former Facebook VP Chamath Palihapitiya Leads $17M Round In Enterprise Social Networking Platform Yammer|last = Rao|first = Leena|date = 2011-09-27|accessdate = 2013-04-23|work = [[TechCrunch]]}}</ref>\n\nThe fund was praised by [[Peter Thiel]], who invested in it and expressed enthusiasm for Palihapitiya's approach.<ref name=businessweek>{{cite web|url=http://www.businessweek.com/articles/2012-07-26/social-plus-capital-the-league-of-extraordinarily-rich-gentlemen|title = Social+Capital, the League of Extraordinarily Rich Gentlemen|last = Bennett|first = Drake|date = 2012-07-26|accessdate = 2013-04-23}}</ref>\n\nThrough the fund, Palihapitiya has invested in a number of companies, including [[Glooko, Inc]], [[Yammer]], [[SecondMarket]], [[Slack (software)|Slack]], [[Box (company)|Box]], and [[Premise (company)|Premise]].<ref name=\"techcrunch\"/><ref name=wsj>{{cite web|url=https://blogs.wsj.com/venturecapital/2015/03/17/the-daily-startup-paper-drawing-app-aims-for-enterprise-with-new-funding/|title = The Daily Startup: Paper Drawing App Aims for Enterprise With New Funding|last = Billings|first = Mike|date = 2015-03-17|accessdate = 2015-04-22|publisher = Wall Street Journal Blog}}</ref><ref>{{cite news|url=https://venturebeat.com/2011/11/02/secondmarket-raises-15m-at-200m-valuation-from-former-facebook-exec-palihapitiya/|title = SecondMarket raises $15M at $200M valuation from former Facebook exec|last = Marshall|first = Matt|work = [[VentureBeat]]|date = 2011-11-02|accessdate = 2013-04-23}}</ref> In 2017 he became a member of the [[board of directors]] of [[Slack (software)|Slack]].<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.businesswire.com/news/home/20191204005852/en/Slack-Appoints-Flex-CEO-Mike-McNamara-Board|title=Slack Appoints Former Flex CEO Mike McNamara to Its Board of Directors}}</ref>\n\nIn March 2013, Palihapitiya confirmed that his venture fund had raised more than $275 million in its second round of fundraising.<ref>{{cite news|url=https://techcrunch.com/2013/03/04/social-capital-partnership-new-fund/|title = Chamath Palihapitiya Confirms That His Social+Capital Partnership Has Raised A New Fund Of $275M+|date = 2013-03-04|accessdate = 2013-04-23|last = Ha|first = Anthony|work = [[TechCrunch]]}}</ref><ref>{{cite news|url=https://venturebeat.com/2013/03/04/making-money-and-a-difference-socialcapital-partnership-confirms-new-fund/|title = Making money and a difference, Social+Capital Partnership confirms new fund|work = [[VentureBeat]]|accessdate = 2013-04-23|date = 2013-03-04|last = Grant|first = Rebecca}}</ref>  As of 2015, the fund had more than $1.1 billion in total assets.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://fortune.com/2015/05/18/is-socialcapitals-chamath-palihapitiya-the-future-of-venture-capital/|title = Is Social+Capital's Chamath Palihapitiya the future of venture capital?|publisher = FORTUNE|accessdate = 2016-02-23|date = 2016-03-23|last = Rao|first = Leena}}</ref>\n\nIn October 2015, Palihapitiya and Social Capital worked with the technology industry publication ''The Information'' to publish a report on diversity in venture capital. The study found that 92% of senior investment teams at top-tier venture firms are male and 78% are white.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.theinformation.com/introducing-the-informations-future-list|title = Introducing The Information's Future List|publisher = The Information|accessdate = 2016-02-23|date = 2016-03-23|last = Schulz|first = Peter}}</ref> Based on the report, Palihapitiya wrote an op-ed calling for a \"wake-up call\" among venture capital firms that would \"recapture our potential and open doors\" in order to \"surround ourselves with a more diverse set of experiences and\u2026prioritize a diverse set of things.\"<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.theinformation.com/bros-funding-bros-whats-wrong-with-venture-capital|title = IBros Funding Bros: What's Wrong with Venture Capital|publisher = The Information|accessdate = 2016-02-23|date = 2016-03-23|last = Palihapitiya|first = Chamath}}</ref>\n\nIn 2019 Palihapitiya stepped down as a member of the board of directors of [[Slack (software)|Slack]].<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.businesswire.com/news/home/20191204005852/en/Slack-Appoints-Flex-CEO-Mike-McNamara-Board|title=Slack Appoints Former Flex CEO Mike McNamara to Its Board of Directors}}</ref>\n\n===Career as a poker player===\n\nPalihapitiya has three [[World Series of Poker|World Series of Poker (WSOP)]] and two [[World Poker Tour|World Poker Tour (WPT)]] cashes for a total of $175,801.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.cardplayer.com/poker-players/214938-chamath-palihapitiya|title=Chamath Palihapitiya: Cash Out|accessdate=22 Feb 2016}}</ref> In 2011, he finished 101st out of 6,865 entries in the World Series of Poker's Main Event.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://pokerdb.thehendonmob.com/event.php?a=r&n=51923|title=42nd World Series of Poker (WSOP) 2011 United States|accessdate=22 Feb 2016}}</ref>\n\n==Politics==\n\n===Immigration reform and policy advocacy===\n\nPalihapitiya was listed as one of the \"Founders\" of the lobbying group [[FWD.us]].<ref name=fwd-us-supporters>{{cite web|url = http://www.fwd.us/our_supporters|title = Our Supporters|publisher = FWD.us|accessdate = 2013-04-23|archive-url = https://web.archive.org/web/20130413230948/http://www.fwd.us/our_supporters|archive-date = 2013-04-13|url-status = dead}}</ref> The group launched on April 11, 2013, and its goals include immigration reform, improving education, and enabling technological innovation, all in a United States context.<ref name=fwd-us-about-us>{{cite web|url=http://www.fwd.us/about_us|title = About Us|publisher = FWD.us|accessdate = 2013-04-23}}</ref><ref name=zuck-op-ed>{{cite news|url=https://www.washingtonpost.com/opinions/mark-zuckerberg-immigrants-are-the-key-to-a-knowledge-economy/2013/04/10/aba05554-a20b-11e2-82bc-511538ae90a4_story.html|title = Facebook's Mark Zuckerberg: Immigration and the knowledge economy|last = Zuckerberg|first = Mark|date = 2013-04-11|accessdate = 2013-04-17|newspaper = [[Washington Post]]}}</ref> An article in ''[[The New Republic]]'' stated that Palihapitiya received a weekly report about FWD.us and also quoted him as saying, in response to controversy around the FWD.us political lobbying strategy: \"The folks that are actually people that run that day to day are sophisticated and understand the nuances of how to affect it... It's a really gnarly, gnarly thing having to deal with Washington. And to be honest with you, my perspective was, it's a really good investment because it's a good way to pay it forward, and I'm really glad there are other people other than me who are dealing with it who have the patience and resolve to figure it out.\"<ref>{{cite magazine|url=https://newrepublic.com/article/113117/mark-zuckerbergs-immigration-reform-strategy-necessary-cynicism|title = Mark Zuckerberg's Cynical, Necessary Washington Strategy|last = DePillis|first = Lydia|accessdate = 2013-05-07|date = 2013-05-06|magazine = [[The New Republic]]}}</ref>\n\n===San Francisco inequality and housing controversy===\nAt [[Bloomberg L.P.|Bloomberg]]'s ''Next Big Thing'' conference in [[Sausalito, California]], Palihapitiya made remarks critical of San Francisco's then mayor, [[Ed Lee (politician)|Ed Lee]], and proposed that the city provide subsidized housing to low-income residents funded by an equity tax on startups, with the tax-and-subsidy schemes potentially restricted to particular zones of the city. This led to a heated debate between Palihapitiya and [[super angel]] [[Ron Conway]]. Conway, a supporter of Lee, defended the city's policies, argued that things would get better for all residents, and noted that Palihapitiya lives in [[Palo Alto]] rather than in the city.<ref>{{cite magazine|url=http://www.slate.com/blogs/future_tense/2014/06/09/ron_conway_chamath_palihapitiya_get_into_shouting_match_at_sausalito_tech.html|title = Tech Conference Turns Into Shouting Match About Inequality in Silicon Valley|last = Oremus|first = Will|date = June 9, 2014|accessdate = July 9, 2015|magazine = [[Slate (magazine)|Slate]]}}</ref><ref>{{cite news|url = http://blog.sfgate.com/techchron/2014/06/09/ron-conway-mocks-fellow-venture-capitalist-uses-phrase-palo-alto-resident-as-insult/|title = Ron Conway mocks fellow venture capitalist, uses phrase 'Palo Alto resident' as insult|last = Garofoli|first = Joe|date = June 9, 2014|accessdate = July 9, 2015|newspaper = [[San Francisco Chronicle]]}}</ref> In a later clarification to ''[[TechCrunch]]'', Palihapitiya outlined his vision in more detail and described how his views on inequality and social mobility were shaped by his experience growing up with relatively poor immigrant parents in [[Canada]].<ref>{{cite news|url=https://techcrunch.com/2014/06/09/eruption-over-sf-housing-and-google-breaks-out-at-next-big-thing-conference/|title = Ron Conway And Chamath Palihapitiya Debate SF Housing And Google At Next Big Thing Conference|last = Buhr|first = Sarah|date = June 9, 2014|accessdate = July 9, 2015|work = [[TechCrunch]]}}</ref>\n\n===Criticism of Facebook and social media===\nIn November 2017, Palihapitiya revealed that, for ethical reasons, he regrets having helped Facebook to become the largest social media platform.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.businessinsider.com/former-facebook-exec-chamath-palihapitiya-social-media-damaging-society-2017-12|title=Former Facebook exec feels 'tremendous guilt' for what he helped make|publisher=}}</ref> He said, \"[t]he short-term, dopamine-driven feedback loops that we have created are destroying how society works: no civil discourse, no cooperation, misinformation, mistruth and it's not an American problem. This is not about Russian ads. This is a global problem. It is eroding the core foundations of how people behave by and between each other. I can't control them. I can control my decision, which is that I don't use that shit. I can control my kids' decisions, which is that they're not allowed to use that shit\".<ref>{{cite web |first=Julia Carrie |last=Wong |title=Former Facebook executive: social media is ripping society apart |url=https://www.theguardian.com/technology/2017/dec/11/facebook-former-executive-ripping-society-apart |work=[[The Guardian]] |date=December 12, 2017 |accessdate=December 12, 2017}}</ref><ref>{{Citation|last=Stanford Graduate School of Business|title=Chamath Palihapitiya, Founder and CEO Social Capital, on Money as an Instrument of Change|date=2017-11-13|url=https://www.youtube.com/watch?time_continue=1281&v=PMotykw0SIk|accessdate=2017-12-13}}</ref> Following criticism from Facebook for his remarks, Palihapitiya subsequently clarified, \"I genuinely believe that Facebook is a force for good in the world, so I'd like to expand on my comments...My comments were meant to start an important conversation, not to criticize one company \u2014 particularly one I love. In 2017, many of us have grappled with the unintended consequences of the products we've built. Social media platforms in particular have been used and abused in ways that we, their architects, never imagined. Much blame has been thrown and guilt felt, but the important thing is what we as an industry do now to ensure that our impact on society continues to be a positive one.\"<ref>Gilbert, Ben (December 15, 2017). [http://www.businessinsider.com/former-facebook-exec-adds-context-to-social-media-criticism-2017-12 \"Former Facebook exec: I take back what I said about Facebook 'destroying how society works' \u2014 kinda\"]. ''Business Insider''.</ref><ref>Palihapitiya, Chamath (December 15, 2017). [https://www.facebook.com/chamath/posts/10159808356105644 (Untitled)]. [[Facebook]]. (Account confirmed by ''Business Insider'' article.)</ref>\n\n==References==\n{{reflist|2}}\n\n==External links==\n{{wikiquote}}\n* [http://www.crunchbase.com/person/chamath-palihapitiya Chamath Palihapitiya] on ''[[CrunchBase]]''\n* {{Twitter}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Palihapitiya, Chamath}}\n[[Category:American venture capitalists]]\n[[Category:Living people]]\n[[Category:University of Waterloo alumni]]\n[[Category:Sri Lankan emigrants to Canada]]\n[[Category:Bank of Montreal people]]\n[[Category:Canadian expatriates in the United States]]\n[[Category:Silicon Valley people]]\n[[Category:American people of Sri Lankan descent]]\n[[Category:Lisgar Collegiate Institute]]\n[[Category:American billionaires]]\n", "name_user": "Burninmyleather", "label": "unsafe", "comment": "", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Chamath_Palihapitiya"}
{"title_page": "Social Capital (venture capital)", "text_new": "{{short description|Venture capital firm}}\n{{Infobox company\n| name                = Social Capital LP\n| logo                = Social Capital Logo.png\n| type                = [[Private Company|Private]]\n| industry            = [[Venture capital]]\n| foundation          = 2011\n| founder             = [[Chamath Palihapitiya]]\n| location            = [[Palo Alto, California]], [[United States]]\n| products            = [[Investments]]\n| assets              = $1.2 billion\n| num_employees       = \n| homepage            = {{Official website}}\n}}\n\n'''Social Capital''', formerly known as '''Social+Capital Partnership''', is a [[venture capital]] firm based in [[Palo Alto, California]]. The firm specializes in technology startups, providing [[seed funding]], [[venture capital]] and [[private equity]].<ref name=Fortune /><ref name=\"New York Times name\">{{cite web|last1=de la MERCED|first1=MICHAEL J.|title=Silicon Valley Investment Funds Still Lack Diversity, Study Shows|url=https://www.nytimes.com/2015/10/07/business/dealbook/silicon-valley-still-lacks-diversity-study-shows.html|website=New York Times|publisher=New York Times|accessdate=23 October 2015}}</ref>\n\nThe firm has \"stood out strategically\", according to ''Fortune'', \"with a focus on...healthcare, financial services and education...when those fields were...neglected by the VC community.\"<ref name=Fortune />\n\n==History==\nSocial Capital was founded in 2011 by [[Chamath Palihapitiya]], who had previously worked at [[Facebook]].<ref name=\"Fortune\" /> [[Mamoon Hamid]] and Ted Maidenberg also joined the firm that year as General Partners.<ref>{{cite news|url=https://techcrunch.com/2011/06/03/facebook-vp-chamath-venture-socialcapital/|title = Facebook VP Chamath Palihapitiya Forms New Venture Fund, The Social+Capital Partnership|last = Arrington|first = Michael|work = [[TechCrunch]]|date = 2011-06-03|accessdate = 2013-04-23}}</ref><ref name=\"Business Insider\">{{cite web|last1=Kim|first1=Eugene|title=These Two Charts Explain Why Kleiner Perkins Wanted To Buy This Four-Year-Old VC Firm|url=http://www.businessinsider.com/kleiner-perkins-social-capital-deal-why-2015-1|website=Business Insider|publisher=Business Insider|accessdate=9 October 2015}}</ref>\n\nIn January 2015, ''[[Fortune (magazine)|Fortune]]'' reported that [[Kleiner Perkins]] was in acquisition talks with Social Capital,<ref name=\"Fortune2\">{{cite magazine|url = http://fortune.com/2015/01/26/exclusive-kleiner-perkins-tried-to-acquire-socialcapital-partnership/|title = Exclusive: Kleiner Perkins tried to 'acquire' Social+Capital Partnership|last = Primack|first = Dan|magazine = [[Fortune (magazine)|Fortune]]|date = January 26, 2015|accessdate = July 8, 2015}}</ref> but the acquisition reportedly fell through.<ref name=\"TechCrunch\">{{cite news|url=https://techcrunch.com/2015/03/31/why-the-kleiner-social-capital-deal-fell-apart/|title = Why The Kleiner Perkins-Social+Capital Deal Fell Apart|last = Lynley|first = Matthew|date = March 31, 2015|accessdate = July 8, 2015|work = [[TechCrunch]]}}</ref> In May 2015, Social Capital raised $600 million in their third and largest venture capital fund.<ref name=Fortune>{{cite web|last1=Rao|first1=Leena|title=Is Social+Capital's Chamath Palihapitiya the future of venture capital?|url=http://fortune.com/2015/05/18/is-socialcapitals-chamath-palihapitiya-the-future-of-venture-capital/|website=Fortune|publisher=Fortune|accessdate=9 October 2015}}</ref> [[PayPal]] cofounder [[Peter Thiel]] praised Palihapitiya's approach, and as of 2015 served as a limited partner.<ref name=businessweek>{{cite web|url=http://www.businessweek.com/articles/2012-07-26/social-plus-capital-the-league-of-extraordinarily-rich-gentlemen|title = Social+Capital, the League of Extraordinarily Rich Gentlemen|last = Bennett|first = Drake|date = 2012-07-26|accessdate = 2013-04-23}}</ref><ref name=Bloomberg>{{cite web|last1=Bennett|first1=Drake|title=Social+Capital, the League of Extraordinarily Rich Gentlemen|url=https://www.bloomberg.com/bw/articles/2012-07-26/social-plus-capital-the-league-of-extraordinarily-rich-gentlemen|website=Bloomberg|publisher=Bloomberg|accessdate=9 October 2015}}</ref>\n\nIn 2017, [[Marc Mezvinsky]] joined Social Capital as vice chairman as it sought to expand beyond traditional venture capital.<ref>[https://www.bloomberg.com/news/articles/2017-05-19/chelsea-clinton-s-husband-joins-silicon-valley-firm-social-capital Chelsea Clinton's Husband Joins Silicon Valley Firm Social Capital]</ref>\n\nIn August 2017, Hamid left Social Capital to join [[Kleiner Perkins]] as a [[general partner]] and managing member.<ref>[https://www.wsj.com/articles/mamoon-hamid-to-join-kleiner-perkins-as-general-partner-1501800217 Mamoon Hamid to Join Kleiner Perkins as General Partner]</ref>\n\nIn spring of 2018, Mezvinsky departed Social Capital. Later in 2018, then-partners [[Arjun Sethi (entrepreneur)|Arjun Sethi]], Jonathan Hsu, and Ted Maidenberg left the firm to co-found Tribe Capital.<ref name=Tribe>{{cite web|url=https://www.bloomberg.com/news/articles/2018-08-16/former-social-capital-partners-make-first-investment-since-exit|title=Former Social Capital Partners Make First Investment Since Exit|last=Verhage|first=Julie|date=16 August 2018|publisher=[[Bloomberg L.P.]]|access-date=5 February 2019}}</ref>\n\n==Investments==\nSocial Capital invested in [[Yammer]] in 2011, which was later bought by [[Microsoft]].<ref name=businessweek /> In 2012, the firm invested in [[Impermium]], which was acquired by [[Google]] in 2014.<ref>{{cite web|last1=Shontell|first1=Alyson|title=That Big Round Ex-Yahoos Were Raising? It Closed And Here Are The Details|url=http://www.businessinsider.com/that-big-round-ex-yahoos-were-raising-it-closed-and-here-are-the-details-2011-11|website=Business Insider|accessdate=26 August 2015}}</ref> Also in 2012, the firm was a venture investor in [[InstaEDU]], acquired by [[Chegg]] in 2014. Social Capital led a round of Series B funding for [[Wave Accounting]].\n\nIn May 2015, the firm was a leading investor in a funding round for [[Slack Technologies]].<ref>{{cite web| url=https://www.inc.com/magazine/201512/jeff-bercovici/slack-company-of-the-year-2015.html| publisher=Inc| title=Slack Is Our Company of the Year. Here's Why Everybody's Talking About It| author=Jeff Bercovici| date=December 2015| access-date=February 7, 2018}}</ref>\n\nThrough 2016 and 2017, the firm led several investments in [[climate crisis | climate]]-related companies Aclima<ref>{{cite web| url=https://techcrunch.com/2018/06/26/aclima-sucks-in-24m-to-scale-its-air-quality-mapping-platform/| publisher=Techcrunch| title=\nAclima sucks in $24M to scale its air quality mapping platform| author=Natasha Lomas}}</ref>, [[UrbanFootprint]]<ref>{{cite web| url=https://www.fastcompany.com/40548501/this-simcity-like-tool-lets-urban-planners-see-the-potential-impact-of-their-ideas| publisher=Fast Company| title=This SimCity-Like Tool Lets Urban Planners See The Potential Impact Of Their Ideas| author=Adele Peters}}</ref>, [[DroneSeed]]<ref>{{cite web| url=https://techcrunch.com/2018/11/26/that-night-a-forest-flew-droneseed-is-planting-trees-from-the-air/| publisher=Techcrunch| title=That night, a forest flew| author=Devin Coldewey}}</ref>, and space technology companies Swarm<ref>{{cite web| url=https://fortune.com/2019/01/24/exclusive-satellite-startup-swarm-raises-25-million-space-internet/| publisher=Fortune| title=Satellite Startup Swarm Raises $25 Million For Space-Based Internet Plan| author=Aaron Pressman}}</ref> and Relativity.\n\nIn 2018, the firm co-led a $22.7 million [[securities offering | round of funding]] for SFOX, a [[cryptocurrency]] [[electronic trading platform | trading platform]], alongside former peers at Tribe Capital.<ref name=Tribe/>\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist}}\n\n==External links==\n*{{Official website}}\n*[https://www.crunchbase.com/organization/social-capital Social Capital at CrunchBase]\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Social Capital}}\n[[Category:Venture capital firms of the United States]]\n[[Category:Companies based in Palo Alto, California]]\n[[Category:Financial services companies established in 2011]]\n[[Category:2011 establishments in California]]\n", "text_old": "{{short description|Venture capital firm}}\n{{Infobox company\n| name = Social Capital\n| logo = Social Capital Logo.png\n| type = [[Private Company|Private]]\n| industry = [[Venture capital]]\n| foundation = 2011\n| founder = [[Chamath Palihapitiya]]\n| location = [[Palo Alto, California]], [[United States]]\n| products = [[Investments]]\n| assets = $1.2 billion\n| num_employees = \n| homepage = {{Official website}}\n}}\n\n'''Social Capital''', formerly known as '''Social+Capital Partnership''', is a [[venture capital]] firm based in [[Palo Alto, California]]. The firm specializes in technology startups, providing [[seed funding]], [[venture capital]] and [[private equity]].<ref name=Fortune /><ref name=\"New York Times name\">{{cite web|last1=de la MERCED|first1=MICHAEL J.|title=Silicon Valley Investment Funds Still Lack Diversity, Study Shows|url=https://www.nytimes.com/2015/10/07/business/dealbook/silicon-valley-still-lacks-diversity-study-shows.html|website=New York Times|publisher=New York Times|accessdate=23 October 2015}}</ref>\n\nThe firm has \"stood out strategically\", according to ''Fortune'', \"with a focus on...healthcare, financial services and education...when those fields were...neglected by the VC community.\"<ref name=Fortune />\n\n==History==\nSocial Capital was founded in 2011 by [[Chamath Palihapitiya]], who had previously worked at [[Facebook]].<ref name=\"Fortune\" /> [[Mamoon Hamid]] and Ted Maidenberg also joined the firm that year as General Partners.<ref>{{cite news|url=https://techcrunch.com/2011/06/03/facebook-vp-chamath-venture-socialcapital/|title = Facebook VP Chamath Palihapitiya Forms New Venture Fund, The Social+